INSERT INTO verses (book_id, chapter, verse, text, version) VALUES
(15, 8, 15, '"Blessed be the LORD, the God of Israel, who has kept the promise he made to my father, David.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 16, 'For he told my father, `From the day I brought my people Israel out of Egypt, I have never chosen a city among the tribes of Israel as the place where a temple should be built to honor my name. But now I have chosen David to be king over my people.''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 17, 'Then Solomon said, "My father, David, wanted to build this Temple to honor the name of the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 18, 'But the LORD told him, `It is right for you to want to build the Temple to honor my name,', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 19, 'but you are not the one to do it. One of your sons will build it instead.''', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 20, '"And now the LORD has done what he promised, for I have become king in my father''s place. I have built this Temple to honor the name of the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 21, 'And I have prepared a place there for the Ark, which contains the covenant that the LORD made with our ancestors when he brought them out of Egypt."', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 22, 'Then Solomon stood with his hands lifted toward heaven before the altar of the LORD in front of the entire community of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 23, 'He prayed, "O LORD, God of Israel, there is no God like you in all of heaven or earth. You keep your promises and show unfailing love to all who obey you and are eager to do your will.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 24, 'You have kept your promise to your servant David, my father. You made that promise with your own mouth, and today you have fulfilled it with your own hands.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 25, 'And now, O LORD, God of Israel, carry out your further promise to your servant David, my father. For you said to him, `If your descendants guard their behavior as you have done, they will always reign over Israel.''', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 26, 'Now, O God of Israel, fulfill this promise to your servant David, my father.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 27, '"But will God really live on earth? Why, even the highest heavens cannot contain you. How much less this Temple I have built!', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 28, 'Listen to my prayer and my request, O LORD my God. Hear the cry and the prayer that your servant is making to you today.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 29, 'May you watch over this Temple both day and night, this place where you have said you would put your name. May you always hear the prayers I make toward this place.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 30, 'May you hear the humble and earnest requests from me and your people Israel when we pray toward this place. Yes, hear us from heaven where you live, and when you hear, forgive.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 31, '"If someone wrongs another person and is required to take an oath of innocence in front of the altar at this Temple,', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 32, 'then hear from heaven and judge between your servants--the accuser and the accused. Punish the guilty party and acquit the one who is innocent.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 33, '"If your people Israel are defeated by their enemies because they have sinned against you, and if they turn to you and call on your name and pray to you here in this Temple,', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 34, 'then hear from heaven and forgive their sins and return them to this land you gave their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 35, '"If the skies are shut up and there is no rain because your people have sinned against you, and then they pray toward this Temple and confess your name and turn from their sins because you have punished them,', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 36, 'then hear from heaven and forgive the sins of your servants, your people Israel. Teach them to do what is right, and send rain on your land that you have given to your people as their special possession.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 37, '"If there is a famine in the land, or plagues, or crop disease, or attacks of locusts or caterpillars, or if your people''s enemies are in the land besieging their towns--whatever the trouble is--', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 38, 'and if your people offer a prayer concerning their troubles or sorrow, raising their hands toward this Temple,', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 39, 'then hear from heaven where you live, and forgive. Give your people whatever they deserve, for you alone know the human heart.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 40, 'Then they will fear you and walk in your ways as long as they live in the land you gave to our ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 41, '"And when foreigners hear of you and come from distant lands to worship your great name--', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 42, 'for they will hear of you and of your mighty miracles and your power--and when they pray toward this Temple,', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 43, 'then hear from heaven where you live, and grant what they ask of you. Then all the people of the earth will come to know and fear you, just as your own people Israel do. They, too, will know that this Temple I have built bears your name.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 44, '"If your people go out at your command to fight their enemies, and if they pray to the LORD toward this city that you have chosen and toward this Temple that I have built for your name,', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 45, 'then hear their prayers from heaven and uphold their cause.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 46, '"If they sin against you--and who has never sinned?--you may become angry with them and let their enemies conquer them and take them captive to a foreign land far or near.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 47, 'But in that land of exile, they may turn to you again in repentance and pray, `We have sinned, done evil, and acted wickedly.''', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 48, 'Then if they turn to you with their whole heart and soul and pray toward the land you gave to their ancestors, toward this city you have chosen, and toward this Temple I have built to honor your name,', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 49, 'then hear their prayers from heaven where you live. Uphold their cause', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 50, 'and forgive your people who have sinned against you. Make their captors merciful to them,', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 51, 'for they are your people--your special possession--whom you brought out of the iron-smelting furnace of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 52, '"May your eyes be open to my requests and to the requests of your people Israel. Hear and answer them whenever they cry out to you.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 53, 'For when you brought our ancestors out of Egypt, O Sovereign LORD, you told your servant Moses that you had separated Israel from among all the nations of the earth to be your own special possession."', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 54, 'When Solomon finished making these prayers and requests to the LORD, he stood up in front of the altar of the LORD, where he had been kneeling with his hands raised toward heaven.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 55, 'He stood there and shouted this blessing over the entire community of Israel:', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 56, '"Praise the LORD who has given rest to his people Israel, just as he promised. Not one word has failed of all the wonderful promises he gave through his servant Moses.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 57, 'May the LORD our God be with us as he was with our ancestors; may he never forsake us.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 58, 'May he give us the desire to do his will in everything and to obey all the commands, laws, and regulations that he gave our ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 59, 'And may these words that I have prayed in the presence of the LORD be before him constantly, day and night, so that the LORD our God may uphold my cause and the cause of his people Israel, fulfilling our daily needs.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 60, 'May people all over the earth know that the LORD is God and that there is no other god.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 61, 'And may you, his people, always be faithful to the LORD our God. May you always obey his laws and commands, just as you are doing today."', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 62, 'Then the king and all Israel with him offered sacrifices to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 63, 'Solomon sacrificed peace offerings to the LORD numbering 22,000 oxen and 120,000 sheep. And so the king and all Israel dedicated the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 64, 'That same day the king dedicated the central area of the courtyard in front of the LORD''s Temple. He offered burnt offerings, grain offerings, and the fat of peace offerings there, because the bronze altar in the LORD''s presence was too small to handle so many offerings.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 65, 'Then Solomon and all Israel celebrated the Festival of Shelters in the presence of the LORD their God. A large crowd had gathered from as far away as Lebo-hamath in the north to the brook of Egypt in the south. The celebration went on for fourteen days in all--seven days for the dedication of the altar and seven days for the Festival of Shelters.', 'NLT'),
(15, 8, 66, 'After the festival was over, Solomon sent the people home. They blessed the king as they went, and they were all joyful and happy because the LORD had been good to his servant David and to his people Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 1, 'So Solomon finished building the Temple of the LORD, as well as the royal palace. He completed everything he had planned to do.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 2, 'Then the LORD appeared to Solomon a second time, as he had done before at Gibeon.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 3, 'The LORD said to him, "I have heard your prayer and your request. I have set apart this Temple you have built so that my name will be honored there forever. I will always watch over it and care for it.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 4, 'As for you, if you will follow me with integrity and godliness, as David your father did, always obeying my commands and keeping my laws and regulations,', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 5, 'then I will establish the throne of your dynasty over Israel forever. For I made this promise to your father, David: `You will never fail to have a successor on the throne of Israel.''', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 6, '"But if you or your descendants abandon me and disobey my commands and laws, and if you go and worship other gods,', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 7, 'then I will uproot the people of Israel from this land I have given them. I will reject this Temple that I have set apart to honor my name. I will make Israel an object of mockery and ridicule among the nations.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 8, 'And though this Temple is impressive now, it will become an appalling sight for all who pass by. They will scoff and ask, `Why did the LORD do such terrible things to his land and to his Temple?''', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 9, 'And the answer will be, `Because his people forgot the LORD their God, who brought their ancestors out of Egypt, and they worshiped other gods instead. That is why the LORD has brought all these disasters upon them.''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 10, 'Now at the end of the twenty years during which Solomon built the Temple of the LORD and the royal palace,', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 11, 'Solomon gave twenty towns in the land of Galilee to King Hiram of Tyre as payment for all the cedar and cypress lumber and gold he had furnished for the construction of the buildings.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 12, 'Hiram came from Tyre to see the towns Solomon had given him, but he was not at all pleased with them.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 13, '"What kind of towns are these, my brother?" he asked. "These towns are worthless!" So Hiram called that area Cabul--"worthless"--as it is still known today.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 14, 'Hiram had sent Solomon nine thousand pounds of gold.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 15, 'This is the account of the forced labor that Solomon conscripted to build the LORD''s Temple, the royal palace, the Millo, the wall of Jerusalem, and the cities of Hazor, Megiddo, and Gezer.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 16, '(The king of Egypt had attacked and captured Gezer, killing the Canaanite population and burning it down. He gave the city to his daughter as a wedding gift when she married Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 17, 'So Solomon rebuilt the city of Gezer.) He also built up the towns of Lower Beth-horon,', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 18, 'Baalath, and Tamar in the desert, within his land.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 19, 'He built towns as supply centers and constructed cities where his chariots and horses could be kept. He built to his heart''s content in Jerusalem and Lebanon and throughout the entire realm.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 20, 'There were still some people living in the land who were not Israelites, including Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 21, 'These were descendants of the nations that Israel had not completely destroyed. So Solomon conscripted them for his labor force, and they serve in the labor force to this day.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 22, 'But Solomon did not conscript any of the Israelites for forced labor. Instead, he assigned them to serve as fighting men, government officials, officers in his army, commanders of his chariots, and charioteers.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 23, 'He also appointed 550 of them to supervise the various projects.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 24, 'After Solomon moved his wife, Pharaoh''s daughter, from the City of David to the new palace he had built for her, he constructed the Millo.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 25, 'Three times each year Solomon offered burnt offerings and peace offerings to the LORD on the altar he had built. He also burned incense to the LORD. And so he finished the work of building the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 26, 'Later King Solomon built a fleet of ships at Ezion-geber, a port near Elath in the land of Edom, along the shore of the Red Sea.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 27, 'Hiram sent experienced crews of sailors to sail the ships with Solomon''s men.', 'NLT'),
(15, 9, 28, 'They sailed to Ophir and brought back to Solomon some sixteen tons of gold.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 1, 'When the queen of Sheba heard of Solomon''s reputation, which brought honor to the name of the LORD, she came to test him with hard questions.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 2, 'She arrived in Jerusalem with a large group of attendants and a great caravan of camels loaded with spices, huge quantities of gold, and precious jewels. When she met with Solomon, they talked about everything she had on her mind.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 3, 'Solomon answered all her questions; nothing was too hard for the king to explain to her.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 4, 'When the queen of Sheba realized how wise Solomon was, and when she saw the palace he had built,', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 5, 'she was breathless. She was also amazed at the food on his tables, the organization of his officials and their splendid clothing, the cup-bearers and their robes, and the burnt offerings Solomon made at the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 6, 'She exclaimed to the king, "Everything I heard in my country about your achievements and wisdom is true!', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 7, 'I didn''t believe it until I arrived here and saw it with my own eyes. Truly I had not heard the half of it! Your wisdom and prosperity are far greater than what I was told.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 8, 'How happy these people must be! What a privilege for your officials to stand here day after day, listening to your wisdom!', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 9, 'The LORD your God is great indeed! He delights in you and has placed you on the throne of Israel. Because the LORD loves Israel with an eternal love, he has made you king so you can rule with justice and righteousness."', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 10, 'Then she gave the king a gift of nine thousand pounds of gold, and great quantities of spices and precious jewels. Never again were so many spices brought in as those the queen of Sheba gave to Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 11, '(When Hiram''s ships brought gold from Ophir, they also brought rich cargoes of almug wood and precious jewels.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 12, 'The king used the almug wood to make railings for the Temple of the LORD and the royal palace, and to construct harps and lyres for the musicians. Never before or since has there been such a supply of beautiful almug wood.)', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 13, 'King Solomon gave the queen of Sheba whatever she asked for, besides all the other customary gifts he had so generously given. Then she and all her attendants left and returned to their own land.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 14, 'Each year Solomon received about twenty-five tons of gold.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 15, 'This did not include the additional revenue he received from merchants and traders, all the kings of Arabia, and the governors of the land.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 16, 'King Solomon made two hundred large shields of hammered gold, each containing over fifteen pounds of gold.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 17, 'He also made three hundred smaller shields of hammered gold, each containing nearly four pounds of gold. The king placed these shields in the Palace of the Forest of Lebanon.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 18, 'Then the king made a huge ivory throne and overlaid it with pure gold.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 19, 'The throne had six steps and a rounded back. On both sides of the seat were armrests, with the figure of a lion standing on each side of the throne.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 20, 'Solomon made twelve other lion figures, one standing on each end of each of the six steps. No other throne in all the world could be compared with it!', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 21, 'All of King Solomon''s drinking cups were solid gold, as were all the utensils in the Palace of the Forest of Lebanon. They were not made of silver because silver was considered of little value in Solomon''s day!', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 22, 'The king had a fleet of trading ships that sailed with Hiram''s fleet. Once every three years the ships returned, loaded down with gold, silver, ivory, apes, and peacocks.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 23, 'So King Solomon became richer and wiser than any other king in all the earth.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 24, 'People from every nation came to visit him and to hear the wisdom God had given him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 25, 'Year after year, everyone who came to visit brought him gifts of silver and gold, clothing, weapons, spices, horses, and mules.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 26, 'Solomon built up a huge force of chariots and horses. He had fourteen hundred chariots and twelve thousand horses. He stationed many of them in the chariot cities, and some near him in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 27, 'The king made silver as plentiful in Jerusalem as stones. And valuable cedarwood was as common as the sycamore wood that grows in the foothills of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 28, 'Solomon''s horses were imported from Egypt and from Cilicia; the king''s traders acquired them from Cilicia at the standard price.', 'NLT'),
(15, 10, 29, 'At that time, Egyptian chariots delivered to Jerusalem could be purchased for 600 pieces of silver, and horses could be bought for 150 pieces of silver. Many of these were then resold to the kings of the Hittites and the kings of Aram.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 1, 'Now King Solomon loved many foreign women. Besides Pharaoh''s daughter, he married women from Moab, Ammon, Edom, Sidon, and from among the Hittites.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 2, 'The LORD had clearly instructed his people not to intermarry with those nations, because the women they married would lead them to worship their gods. Yet Solomon insisted on loving them anyway.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 3, 'He had seven hundred wives and three hundred concubines. And sure enough, they led his heart away from the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 4, 'In Solomon''s old age, they turned his heart to worship their gods instead of trusting only in the LORD his God, as his father, David, had done.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 5, 'Solomon worshiped Ashtoreth, the goddess of the Sidonians, and Molech, the detestable god of the Ammonites.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 6, 'Thus, Solomon did what was evil in the LORD''s sight; he refused to follow the LORD completely, as his father, David, had done.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 7, 'On the Mount of Olives, east of Jerusalem, he even built a shrine for Chemosh, the detestable god of Moab, and another for Molech, the detestable god of the Ammonites.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 8, 'Solomon built such shrines for all his foreign wives to use for burning incense and sacrificing to their gods.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 9, 'The LORD was very angry with Solomon, for his heart had turned away from the LORD, the God of Israel, who had appeared to him twice.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 10, 'He had warned Solomon specifically about worshiping other gods, but Solomon did not listen to the LORD''s command.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 11, 'So now the LORD said to him, "Since you have not kept my covenant and have disobeyed my laws, I will surely tear the kingdom away from you and give it to one of your servants.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 12, 'But for the sake of your father, David, I will not do this while you are still alive. I will take the kingdom away from your son.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 13, 'And even so, I will let him be king of one tribe, for the sake of my servant David and for the sake of Jerusalem, my chosen city."', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 14, 'Then the LORD raised up Hadad the Edomite, a member of Edom''s royal family, to be an enemy against Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 15, 'Years before, David had gone to Edom with Joab, his army commander, to bury some Israelites who had died in battle. While there, the Israelite army had killed nearly every male in Edom.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 16, 'Joab and the army had stayed there for six months, killing them.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 17, 'But Hadad and a few of his father''s royal officials had fled. (Hadad was a very small child at the time.)', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 18, 'They escaped from Midian and went to Paran, where others joined them. Then they traveled to Egypt and went to Pharaoh, who gave them a home, food, and some land.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 19, 'Pharaoh grew very fond of Hadad, and he gave him a wife--the sister of Queen Tahpenes.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 20, 'She bore him a son, Genubath, who was brought up in Pharaoh''s palace among Pharaoh''s own sons.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 21, 'When the news reached Hadad in Egypt that David and his commander Joab were both dead, he said to Pharaoh, "Let me return to my own country."', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 22, '"Why?" Pharaoh asked him. "What do you lack here? How have we disappointed you that you want to go home?Nothing is wrong," he replied. "But even so, I must return home."', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 23, 'God also raised up Rezon son of Eliada to be an enemy against Solomon. Rezon had fled from his master, King Hadadezer of Zobah,', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 24, 'and had become the leader of a gang of rebels. After David conquered Hadadezer, Rezon and his men fled to Damascus, where he became king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 25, 'Rezon was Israel''s bitter enemy for the rest of Solomon''s reign, and he made trouble, just as Hadad did. Rezon hated Israel intensely and continued to reign in Aram.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 26, 'Another rebel leader was Jeroboam son of Nebat, one of Solomon''s own officials. He came from the city of Zeredah in Ephraim, and his mother was Zeruah, a widow.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 27, 'This is the story behind his rebellion. Solomon was rebuilding the Millo and repairing the walls of the city of his father, David.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 28, 'Jeroboam was a very capable young man, and when Solomon saw how industrious he was, he put him in charge of the labor force from the tribes of Ephraim and Manasseh.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 29, 'One day as Jeroboam was leaving Jerusalem, the prophet Ahijah from Shiloh met him on the road, wearing a new cloak. The two of them were alone in a field,', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 30, 'and Ahijah took the new cloak he was wearing and tore it into twelve pieces.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 31, 'Then he said to Jeroboam, "Take ten of these pieces, for this is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: `I am about to tear the kingdom from the hand of Solomon, and I will give ten of the tribes to you!', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 32, 'But I will leave him one tribe for the sake of my servant David and for the sake of Jerusalem, which I have chosen out of all the tribes of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 33, 'For Solomon has abandoned me and worshiped Ashtoreth, the goddess of the Sidonians; Chemosh, the god of Moab; and Molech, the god of the Ammonites. He has not followed my ways and done what is pleasing in my sight. He has not obeyed my laws and regulations as his father, David, did.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 34, '" `But I will not take the entire kingdom from Solomon at this time. For the sake of my servant David, the one whom I chose and who obeyed my commands and laws, I will let Solomon reign for the rest of his life.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 35, 'But I will take the kingdom away from his son and give ten of the tribes to you.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 36, 'His son will have one tribe so that the descendants of David my servant will continue to reign in Jerusalem, the city I have chosen to be the place for my name.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 37, 'And I will place you on the throne of Israel, and you will rule over all that your heart desires.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 38, 'If you listen to what I tell you and follow my ways and do whatever I consider to be right, and if you obey my laws and commands, as my servant David did, then I will always be with you. I will establish an enduring dynasty for you as I did for David, and I will give Israel to you.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 39, 'But I will punish the descendants of David because of Solomon''s sin--though not forever.''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 40, 'Solomon tried to kill Jeroboam, but he fled to King Shishak of Egypt and stayed there until Solomon died.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 41, 'The rest of the events in Solomon''s reign, including his wisdom, are recorded in The Book of the Acts of Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 42, 'Solomon ruled in Jerusalem over all Israel for forty years.', 'NLT'),
(15, 11, 43, 'When Solomon died, he was buried in the city of his father, David. Then his son Rehoboam became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 1, 'Rehoboam went to Shechem, where all Israel had gathered to make him king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 2, 'When Jeroboam son of Nebat heard of Solomon''s death, he returned from Egypt, for he had fled to Egypt to escape from King Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 3, 'The leaders of Israel sent for Jeroboam, and the whole assembly of Israel went to speak with Rehoboam.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 4, '"Your father was a hard master," they said. "Lighten the harsh labor demands and heavy taxes that your father imposed on us. Then we will be your loyal subjects."', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 5, 'Rehoboam replied, "Give me three days to think this over. Then come back for my answer." So the people went away.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 6, 'Then King Rehoboam went to discuss the matter with the older men who had counseled his father, Solomon. "What is your advice?" he asked. "How should I answer these people?"', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 7, 'The older counselors replied, "If you are willing to serve the people today and give them a favorable answer, they will always be your loyal subjects."', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 8, 'But Rehoboam rejected the advice of the elders and instead asked the opinion of the young men who had grown up with him and who were now his advisers.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 9, '"What is your advice?" he asked them. "How should I answer these people who want me to lighten the burdens imposed by my father?"', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 10, 'The young men replied, "This is what you should tell those complainers: `My little finger is thicker than my father''s waist--if you think he was hard on you, just wait and see what I''ll be like!', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 11, 'Yes, my father was harsh on you, but I''ll be even harsher! My father used whips on you, but I''ll use scorpions!''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 12, 'Three days later, Jeroboam and all the people returned to hear Rehoboam''s decision, just as the king had requested.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 13, 'But Rehoboam spoke harshly to them, for he rejected the advice of the older counselors', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 14, 'and followed the counsel of his younger advisers. He told the people, "My father was harsh on you, but I''ll be even harsher! My father used whips on you, but I''ll use scorpions!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 15, 'So the king paid no attention to the people''s demands. This turn of events was the will of the LORD, for it fulfilled the LORD''s message to Jeroboam son of Nebat through the prophet Ahijah from Shiloh.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 16, 'When all Israel realized that the king had rejected their request, they shouted, "Down with David and his dynasty! We have no share in Jesse''s son! Let''s go home, Israel! Look out for your own house, O David!" So the people of Israel returned home.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 17, 'But Rehoboam continued to rule over the Israelites who lived in the towns of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 18, 'King Rehoboam sent Adoniram, who was in charge of the labor force, to restore order, but all Israel stoned him to death. When this news reached King Rehoboam, he quickly jumped into his chariot and fled to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 19, 'The northern tribes of Israel have refused to be ruled by a descendant of David to this day.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 20, 'When the people of Israel learned of Jeroboam''s return from Egypt, they called an assembly and made him king over all Israel. So only the tribe of Judah remained loyal to the family of David.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 21, 'When Rehoboam arrived at Jerusalem, he mobilized the armies of Judah and Benjamin--180,000 select troops--to fight against the army of Israel and to restore the kingdom to himself.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 22, 'But God said to Shemaiah, the man of God,', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 23, '"Say to Rehoboam son of Solomon, king of Judah, and to all the people of Judah and Benjamin,', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 24, '`This is what the LORD says: Do not fight against your relatives, the Israelites. Go back home, for what has happened is my doing!''" So they obeyed the message of the LORD and went home, as the LORD had commanded.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 25, 'Jeroboam then built up the city of Shechem in the hill country of Ephraim, and it became his capital. Later he went and built up the town of Peniel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 26, 'Jeroboam thought to himself, "Unless I am careful, the kingdom will return to the dynasty of David.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 27, 'When they go to Jerusalem to offer sacrifices at the Temple of the LORD, they will again give their allegiance to King Rehoboam of Judah. They will kill me and make him their king instead."', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 28, 'So on the advice of his counselors, the king made two gold calves. He said to the people, "It is too much trouble for you to worship in Jerusalem. O Israel, these are the gods who brought you out of Egypt!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 29, 'He placed these calf idols at the southern and northern ends of Israel--in Bethel and in Dan.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 30, 'This became a great sin, for the people worshiped them, traveling even as far as Dan.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 31, 'Jeroboam built shrines at the pagan high places and ordained priests from the rank and file of the people--those who were not from the priestly tribe of Levi.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 32, 'Jeroboam also instituted a religious festival in Bethel, held on a day in midautumn, similar to the annual Festival of Shelters in Judah. There at Bethel he himself offered sacrifices to the calves he had made. And it was at Bethel that he appointed priests for the pagan shrines he had made.', 'NLT'),
(15, 12, 33, 'So on the appointed day in midautumn, a day that he himself had designated, Jeroboam offered sacrifices on the altar at Bethel. He instituted a religious festival for Israel, and he went up to the altar to burn incense.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 1, 'At the LORD''s command, a man of God from Judah went to Bethel, and he arrived there just as Jeroboam was approaching the altar to offer a sacrifice.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 2, 'Then at the LORD''s command, he shouted, "O altar, altar! This is what the LORD says: A child named Josiah will be born into the dynasty of David. On you he will sacrifice the priests from the pagan shrines who come here to burn incense, and human bones will be burned on you."', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 3, 'That same day the man of God gave a sign to prove his message, and he said, "The LORD has promised to give this sign: This altar will split apart, and its ashes will be poured out on the ground."', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 4, 'King Jeroboam was very angry with the man of God for speaking against the altar. So he pointed at the man and shouted, "Seize that man!" But instantly the king''s hand became paralyzed in that position, and he couldn''t pull it back.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 5, 'At the same time a wide crack appeared in the altar, and the ashes poured out, just as the man of God had predicted in his message from the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 6, 'The king cried out to the man of God, "Please ask the LORD your God to restore my hand again!" So the man of God prayed to the LORD, and the king''s hand became normal again.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 7, 'Then the king said to the man of God, "Come to the palace with me and have something to eat, and I will give you a gift."', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 8, 'But the man of God said to the king, "Even if you gave me half of everything you own, I would not go with you. I would not eat any food or drink any water in this place.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 9, 'For the LORD gave me this command: `You must not eat any food or drink any water while you are there, and do not return to Judah by the same way you came.''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 10, 'So he left Bethel and went home another way.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 11, 'As it happened, there was an old prophet living in Bethel, and his sons came home and told him what the man of God had done in Bethel that day. They also told him what he had said to the king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 12, 'The old prophet asked them, "Which way did he go?" So they told their father which road the man of God had taken.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 13, '"Quick, saddle the donkey," the old man said. And when they had saddled the donkey for him,', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 14, 'he rode after the man of God and found him sitting under an oak tree. The old prophet asked him, "Are you the man of God who came from Judah?Yes," he replied, "I am."', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 15, 'Then he said to the man of God, "Come home with me and eat some food."', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 16, '"No, I cannot," he replied. "I am not allowed to eat any food or drink any water here in this place.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 17, 'For the LORD gave me this command: `You must not eat any food or drink any water while you are there, and do not return to Judah by the same way you came.''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 18, 'But the old prophet answered, "I am a prophet, too, just as you are. And an angel gave me this message from the LORD: `Bring him home with you, and give him food to eat and water to drink.''" But the old man was lying to him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 19, 'So they went back together, and the man of God ate some food and drank some water at the prophet''s home.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 20, 'Then while they were sitting at the table, a message from the LORD came to the old prophet.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 21, 'He cried out to the man of God from Judah, "This is what the LORD says: You have defied the LORD''s message and have disobeyed the command the LORD your God gave you.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 22, 'You came back to this place and ate food and drank water where he told you not to eat or drink. Because of this, your body will not be buried in the grave of your ancestors."', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 23, 'Now after the man of God had finished eating and drinking, the prophet saddled his own donkey for him,', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 24, 'and the man of God started off again. But as he was traveling along, a lion came out and killed him. His body lay there on the road, with the donkey and the lion standing beside it.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 25, 'People came by and saw the body lying in the road and the lion standing beside it, and they went and reported it in Bethel, where the old prophet lived.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 26, 'When the old prophet heard the report, he said, "It is the man of God who disobeyed the LORD''s command. The LORD has fulfilled his word by causing the lion to attack and kill him."', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 27, 'Then the prophet said to his sons, "Saddle a donkey for me." So they saddled a donkey,', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 28, 'and he went out and found the body lying in the road. The donkey and lion were still standing there beside it, for the lion had not eaten the body nor attacked the donkey.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 29, 'So the prophet laid the body of the man of God on the donkey and took it back to the city to mourn over him and bury him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 30, 'He laid the body in his own grave, crying out in grief, "Oh, my brother!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 31, 'Afterward the prophet said to his sons, "When I die, bury me in the grave where the man of God is buried. Lay my bones beside his bones.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 32, 'For the message the LORD told him to proclaim against the altar in Bethel and against the pagan shrines in the towns of Samaria will surely come true."', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 33, 'But even after this, Jeroboam did not turn from his evil ways. He continued to choose priests from the rank and file of the people. Anyone who wanted to could become a priest for the pagan shrines.', 'NLT'),
(15, 13, 34, 'This became a great sin and resulted in the destruction of Jeroboam''s kingdom and the death of all his family.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 1, 'At that time Jeroboam''s son Abijah became very sick.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 2, 'So Jeroboam told his wife, "Disguise yourself so that no one will recognize you as the queen. Then go to the prophet Ahijah at Shiloh--the man who told me I would become king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 3, 'Take him a gift of ten loaves of bread, some cakes, and a jar of honey, and ask him what will happen to the boy."', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 4, 'So Jeroboam''s wife went to Ahijah''s home at Shiloh. He was an old man now and could no longer see.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 5, 'But the LORD had told Ahijah, "Jeroboam''s wife will come here, pretending to be someone else. She will ask you about her son, for he is very sick. You must give her the answer that I give you."', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 6, 'So when Ahijah heard her footsteps at the door, he called out, "Come in, wife of Jeroboam! Why are you pretending to be someone else?" Then he told her, "I have bad news for you.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 7, 'Give your husband, Jeroboam, this message from the LORD, the God of Israel: `I promoted you from the ranks of the common people and made you ruler over my people Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 8, 'I ripped the kingdom away from the family of David and gave it to you. But you have not been like my servant David, who obeyed my commands and followed me with all his heart and always did whatever I wanted him to do.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 9, 'You have done more evil than all who lived before you. You have made other gods and have made me furious with your gold calves. And since you have turned your back on me,', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 10, 'I will bring disaster on your dynasty and kill all your sons, slave or free alike. I will burn up your royal dynasty as one burns up trash until it is all gone.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 11, 'I, the LORD, vow that the members of your family who die in the city will be eaten by dogs, and those who die in the field will be eaten by vultures.''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 12, 'Then Ahijah said to Jeroboam''s wife, "Go on home, and when you enter the city, the child will die.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 13, 'All Israel will mourn for him and bury him. He is the only member of your family who will have a proper burial, for this child is the only good thing that the LORD, the God of Israel, sees in the entire family of Jeroboam.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 14, 'And the LORD will raise up a king over Israel who will destroy the family of Jeroboam. This will happen today, even now!', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 15, 'Then the LORD will shake Israel like a reed whipped about in a stream. He will uproot the people of Israel from this good land that he gave their ancestors and will scatter them beyond the Euphrates River, for they have angered the LORD by worshiping Asherah poles.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 16, 'He will abandon Israel because Jeroboam sinned and made all of Israel sin along with him."', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 17, 'So Jeroboam''s wife returned to Tirzah, and the child died just as she walked through the door of her home.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 18, 'When the people of Israel buried him, they mourned for him, as the LORD had promised through the prophet Ahijah.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 19, 'The rest of the events of Jeroboam''s reign, all his wars and how he ruled, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 20, 'Jeroboam reigned in Israel twenty-two years. When Jeroboam died, his son Nadab became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 21, 'Meanwhile, Rehoboam son of Solomon was king in Judah. He was forty-one years old when he became king, and he reigned seventeen years in Jerusalem, the city the LORD had chosen from among all the tribes of Israel as the place to honor his name. Rehoboam''s mother was Naamah, an Ammonite woman.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 22, 'During Rehoboam''s reign, the people of Judah did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, arousing his anger with their sin, for it was even worse than that of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 23, 'They built pagan shrines and set up sacred pillars and Asherah poles on every high hill and under every green tree.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 24, 'There were even shrine prostitutes throughout the land. The people imitated the detestable practices of the pagan nations the LORD had driven from the land ahead of the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 25, 'In the fifth year of King Rehoboam''s reign, King Shishak of Egypt came up and attacked Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 26, 'He ransacked the Temple of the LORD and the royal palace and stole everything, including all the gold shields Solomon had made.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 27, 'Afterward Rehoboam made bronze shields as substitutes, and he entrusted them to the care of the palace guard officers.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 28, 'Whenever the king went to the Temple of the LORD, the guards would carry them along and then return them to the guardroom.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 29, 'The rest of the events in Rehoboam''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 30, 'There was constant war between Rehoboam and Jeroboam.', 'NLT'),
(15, 14, 31, 'When Rehoboam died, he was buried among his ancestors in the City of David. His mother was Naamah, an Ammonite woman. Then his son Abijam became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 1, 'Abijam began to rule over Judah in the eighteenth year of Jeroboam''s reign in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 2, 'He reigned in Jerusalem three years. His mother was Maacah, the daughter of Absalom.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 3, 'He committed the same sins as his father before him, and his heart was not right with the LORD his God, as the heart of his ancestor David had been.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 4, 'But for David''s sake, the LORD his God allowed his dynasty to continue, and he gave Abijam a son to rule after him in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 5, 'For David had done what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight and had obeyed the LORD''s commands throughout his life, except in the affair concerning Uriah the Hittite.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 6, 'There was war between Abijam and Jeroboam throughout Abijam''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 7, 'The rest of the events in Abijam''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah. There was constant war between Abijam and Jeroboam.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 8, 'When Abijam died, he was buried in the City of David. Then his son Asa became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 9, 'Asa began to rule over Judah in the twentieth year of Jeroboam''s reign in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 10, 'He reigned in Jerusalem forty-one years. His grandmother was Maacah, the daughter of Absalom.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 11, 'Asa did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight, as his ancestor David had done.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 12, 'He banished the shrine prostitutes from the land and removed all the idols his ancestors had made.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 13, 'He even deposed his grandmother Maacah from her position as queen mother because she had made an obscene Asherah pole. He cut down the pole and burned it in the Kidron Valley.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 14, 'Although the pagan shrines were not completely removed, Asa remained faithful to the LORD throughout his life.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 15, 'He brought into the Temple of the LORD the silver and gold and the utensils that he and his father had dedicated.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 16, 'There was constant war between King Asa of Judah and King Baasha of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 17, 'King Baasha of Israel invaded Judah and fortified Ramah in order to prevent anyone from entering or leaving King Asa''s territory in Judah.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 18, 'Asa responded by taking all the silver and gold that was left in the treasuries of the LORD''s Temple and the royal palace. He sent it with some of his officials to Ben-hadad son of Tabrimmon and grandson of Hezion, the king of Aram, who was ruling in Damascus, along with this message:', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 19, '"Let us renew the treaty that existed between your father and my father. See, I am sending you a gift of silver and gold. Break your treaty with King Baasha of Israel so that he will leave me alone."', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 20, 'Ben-hadad agreed to King Asa''s request and sent his armies to attack Israel. They conquered the towns of Ijon, Dan, Abel-beth-maacah, and all Kinnereth, with all the land of Naphtali.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 21, 'As soon as Baasha of Israel heard what was happening, he abandoned his project of fortifying Ramah and withdrew to Tirzah.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 22, 'Then King Asa sent an order throughout Judah, requiring that everyone, without exception, help to carry away the building stones and timbers that Baasha had been using to fortify Ramah. Asa used these materials to fortify the town of Geba in Benjamin and the town of Mizpah.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 23, 'The rest of the events in Asa''s reign, the extent of his power, and the names of the cities he built are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah. In his old age his feet became diseased.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 24, 'When Asa died, he was buried with his ancestors in the City of David. Then his son Jehoshaphat became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 25, 'Nadab son of Jeroboam began to rule over Israel in the second year of King Asa''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Israel two years.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 26, 'But he did what was evil in the LORD''s sight and followed the example of his father, continuing the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 27, 'Then Baasha son of Ahijah, from the tribe of Issachar, plotted against Nadab and assassinated him while he and the Israelite army were laying siege to the Philistine town of Gibbethon.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 28, 'Baasha killed Nadab in the third year of King Asa''s reign in Judah, and he became the next king of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 29, 'He immediately killed all the descendants of King Jeroboam, so that not one of the royal family was left, just as the LORD had promised concerning Jeroboam by the prophet Ahijah from Shiloh.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 30, 'This was done because Jeroboam had aroused the anger of the LORD, the God of Israel, by the sins he had committed and the sins he had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 31, 'The rest of the events in Nadab''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel. Baasha Rules in Israel', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 32, 'There was constant war between Asa and King Baasha of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 33, 'Baasha began to rule over Israel in the third year of King Asa''s reign in Judah. Baasha reigned in Tirzah twenty-four years.', 'NLT'),
(15, 15, 34, 'But he did what was evil in the LORD''s sight and followed the example of Jeroboam, continuing the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 1, 'This message from the LORD was delivered to King Baasha by the prophet Jehu son of Hanani:', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 2, '"I lifted you out of the dust to make you ruler of my people Israel, but you have followed the evil example of Jeroboam. You have aroused my anger by causing my people to sin.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 3, 'So now I will destroy you and your family, just as I destroyed the descendants of Jeroboam son of Nebat.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 4, 'Those of your family who die in the city will be eaten by dogs, and those who die in the field will be eaten by the vultures."', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 5, 'The rest of the events in Baasha''s reign and the extent of his power are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 6, 'When Baasha died, he was buried in Tirzah. Then his son Elah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 7, 'This message from the LORD had been spoken against Baasha and his family through the prophet Jehu son of Hanani. It was delivered because Baasha had done what was evil in the LORD''s sight, arousing him to anger by his sins, just like the family of Jeroboam, and also because Baasha had destroyed the family of Jeroboam.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 8, 'Elah son of Baasha began to rule over Israel from Tirzah in the twenty-sixth year of King Asa''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Israel two years.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 9, 'Then Zimri, who commanded half of the royal chariots, made plans to kill him. One day in Tirzah, Elah was getting drunk at the home of Arza, the supervisor of the palace.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 10, 'Zimri walked in and struck him down and killed him. This happened in the twenty-seventh year of King Asa''s reign in Judah. Then Zimri became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 11, 'Zimri immediately killed the entire royal family of Baasha, and he did not leave a single male child. He even destroyed distant relatives and friends.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 12, 'So Zimri destroyed the dynasty of Baasha as the LORD had promised through the prophet Jehu.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 13, 'This happened because of the sins of Baasha and his son Elah and because of all the sins they led Israel to commit, arousing the anger of the LORD, the God of Israel, with their idols.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 14, 'The rest of the events in Elah''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel. Zimri Rules in Israel', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 15, 'Zimri began to rule over Israel from Tirzah in the twenty-seventh year of King Asa''s reign in Judah, but he reigned only seven days. When the army of Israel, which was then engaged in attacking the Philistine town of Gibbethon,', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 16, 'heard that Zimri had assassinated the king, they chose Omri, commander of the army, as their new king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 17, 'So Omri led the army of Israel away from Gibbethon to attack Tirzah, Israel''s capital.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 18, 'When Zimri saw that the city had been taken, he went into the citadel of the king''s house and burned it down over himself and died in the flames.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 19, 'For he, too, had done what was evil in the LORD''s sight and followed the example of Jeroboam, continuing the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 20, 'The rest of the events of Zimri''s reign and his conspiracy are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel. Omri Rules in Israel', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 21, 'But now the people of Israel were divided into two groups. Half the people tried to make Tibni son of Ginath their king, while the other half supported Omri.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 22, 'But Omri''s supporters defeated the supporters of Tibni son of Ginath. So Tibni was killed, and Omri became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 23, 'Omri began to rule over Israel in the thirty-first year of King Asa''s reign in Judah. He reigned twelve years in all, six of them in Tirzah.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 24, 'Then Omri bought the hill now known as Samaria from its owner, Shemer, for 150 pounds of silver. He built a city on it and called the city Samaria in honor of Shemer.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 25, 'But Omri did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, even more than any of the kings before him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 26, 'He followed the example of Jeroboam, continuing the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam had led Israel to commit. Thus, he aroused the anger of the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 27, 'The rest of the events in Omri''s reign, the extent of his power, and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 28, 'When Omri died, he was buried in Samaria. Then his son Ahab became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 29, 'Ahab son of Omri began to rule over Israel in the thirty-eighth year of King Asa''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria twenty-two years.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 30, 'But Ahab did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, even more than any of the kings before him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 31, 'And as though it were not enough to live like Jeroboam, he married Jezebel, the daughter of King Ethbaal of the Sidonians, and he began to worship Baal.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 32, 'First he built a temple and an altar for Baal in Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 33, 'Then he set up an Asherah pole. He did more to arouse the anger of the LORD, the God of Israel, than any of the other kings of Israel before him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 16, 34, 'It was during his reign that Hiel, a man from Bethel, rebuilt Jericho. When he laid the foundations, his oldest son, Abiram, died. And when he finally completed it by setting up the gates, his youngest son, Segub, died. This all happened according to the message from the LORD concerning Jericho spoken by Joshua son of Nun.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 1, 'Now Elijah, who was from Tishbe in Gilead, told King Ahab, "As surely as the LORD, the God of Israel, lives--the God whom I worship and serve--there will be no dew or rain during the next few years unless I give the word!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 2, 'Then the LORD said to Elijah,', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 3, '"Go to the east and hide by Kerith Brook at a place east of where it enters the Jordan River.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 4, 'Drink from the brook and eat what the ravens bring you, for I have commanded them to bring you food."', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 5, 'So Elijah did as the LORD had told him and camped beside Kerith Brook.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 6, 'The ravens brought him bread and meat each morning and evening, and he drank from the brook.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 7, 'But after a while the brook dried up, for there was no rainfall anywhere in the land.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 8, 'Then the LORD said to Elijah,', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 9, '"Go and live in the village of Zarephath, near the city of Sidon. There is a widow there who will feed you. I have given her my instructions."', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 10, 'So he went to Zarephath. As he arrived at the gates of the village, he saw a widow gathering sticks, and he asked her, "Would you please bring me a cup of water?"', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 11, 'As she was going to get it, he called to her, "Bring me a bite of bread, too."', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 12, 'But she said, "I swear by the LORD your God that I don''t have a single piece of bread in the house. And I have only a handful of flour left in the jar and a little cooking oil in the bottom of the jug. I was just gathering a few sticks to cook this last meal, and then my son and I will die."', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 13, 'But Elijah said to her, "Don''t be afraid! Go ahead and cook that `last meal,'' but bake me a little loaf of bread first. Afterward there will still be enough food for you and your son.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 14, 'For this is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: There will always be plenty of flour and oil left in your containers until the time when the LORD sends rain and the crops grow again!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 15, 'So she did as Elijah said, and she and Elijah and her son continued to eat from her supply of flour and oil for many days.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 16, 'For no matter how much they used, there was always enough left in the containers, just as the LORD had promised through Elijah.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 17, 'Some time later, the woman''s son became sick. He grew worse and worse, and finally he died.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 18, 'She then said to Elijah, "O man of God, what have you done to me? Have you come here to punish my sins by killing my son?"', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 19, 'But Elijah replied, "Give me your son." And he took the boy''s body from her, carried him up to the upper room, where he lived, and laid the body on his bed.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 20, 'Then Elijah cried out to the LORD, "O LORD my God, why have you brought tragedy on this widow who has opened her home to me, causing her son to die?"', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 21, 'And he stretched himself out over the child three times and cried out to the LORD, "O LORD my God, please let this child''s life return to him."', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 22, 'The LORD heard Elijah''s prayer, and the life of the child returned, and he came back to life!', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 23, 'Then Elijah brought him down from the upper room and gave him to his mother. "Look, your son is alive!" he said.', 'NLT'),
(15, 17, 24, 'Then the woman told Elijah, "Now I know for sure that you are a man of God, and that the LORD truly speaks through you."', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 1, 'After many months passed, in the third year of the drought, the LORD said to Elijah, "Go and present yourself to King Ahab. Tell him that I will soon send rain!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 2, 'So Elijah went to appear before Ahab. Meanwhile, the famine had become very severe in Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 3, 'So Ahab summoned Obadiah, who was in charge of the palace. (Now Obadiah was a devoted follower of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 4, 'Once when Jezebel had tried to kill all the LORD''s prophets, Obadiah had hidden one hundred of them in two caves. He had put fifty prophets in each cave and had supplied them with food and water.)', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 5, 'Ahab said to Obadiah, "We must check every spring and valley to see if we can find enough grass to save at least some of my horses and mules."', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 6, 'So they divided the land between them. Ahab went one way by himself, and Obadiah went another way by himself.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 7, 'As Obadiah was walking along, he saw Elijah coming toward him. Obadiah recognized him at once and fell to the ground before him. "Is it really you, my lord Elijah?" he asked.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 8, '"Yes, it is," Elijah replied. "Now go and tell your master I am here."', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 9, '"Oh, sir," Obadiah protested, "what harm have I done to you that you are sending me to my death at the hands of Ahab?', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 10, 'For I swear by the LORD your God that the king has searched every nation and kingdom on earth from end to end to find you. And each time when he was told, `Elijah isn''t here,'' King Ahab forced the king of that nation to swear to the truth of his claim.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 11, 'And now you say, `Go and tell your master that Elijah is here''!', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 12, 'But as soon as I leave you, the Spirit of the LORD will carry you away to who knows where. When Ahab comes and cannot find you, he will kill me. Yet I have been a true servant of the LORD all my life.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 13, 'Has no one told you, my lord, about the time when Jezebel was trying to kill the LORD''s prophets? I hid a hundred of them in two caves and supplied them with food and water.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 14, 'And now you say, `Go and tell your master that Elijah is here''! Sir, if I do that, I''m as good as dead!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 15, 'But Elijah said, "I swear by the LORD Almighty, in whose presence I stand, that I will present myself to Ahab today."', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 16, 'So Obadiah went to tell Ahab that Elijah had come, and Ahab went out to meet him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 17, '"So it''s you, is it--Israel''s troublemaker?" Ahab asked when he saw him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 18, '"I have made no trouble for Israel," Elijah replied. "You and your family are the troublemakers, for you have refused to obey the commands of the LORD and have worshiped the images of Baal instead.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 19, 'Now bring all the people of Israel to Mount Carmel, with all 450 prophets of Baal and the 400 prophets of Asherah, who are supported by Jezebel."', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 20, 'So Ahab summoned all the people and the prophets to Mount Carmel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 21, 'Then Elijah stood in front of them and said, "How long are you going to waver between two opinions? If the LORD is God, follow him! But if Baal is God, then follow him!" But the people were completely silent.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 22, 'Then Elijah said to them, "I am the only prophet of the LORD who is left, but Baal has 450 prophets.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 23, 'Now bring two bulls. The prophets of Baal may choose whichever one they wish and cut it into pieces and lay it on the wood of their altar, but without setting fire to it. I will prepare the other bull and lay it on the wood on the altar, but not set fire to it.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 24, 'Then call on the name of your god, and I will call on the name of the LORD. The god who answers by setting fire to the wood is the true God!" And all the people agreed.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 25, 'Then Elijah said to the prophets of Baal, "You go first, for there are many of you. Choose one of the bulls and prepare it and call on the name of your god. But do not set fire to the wood."', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 26, 'So they prepared one of the bulls and placed it on the altar. Then they called on the name of Baal all morning, shouting, "O Baal, answer us!" But there was no reply of any kind. Then they danced wildly around the altar they had made.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 27, 'About noontime Elijah began mocking them. "You''ll have to shout louder," he scoffed, "for surely he is a god! Perhaps he is deep in thought, or he is relieving himself. Or maybe he is away on a trip, or he is asleep and needs to be wakened!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 28, 'So they shouted louder, and following their normal custom, they cut themselves with knives and swords until the blood gushed out.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 29, 'They raved all afternoon until the time of the evening sacrifice, but still there was no reply, no voice, no answer.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 30, 'Then Elijah called to the people, "Come over here!" They all crowded around him as he repaired the altar of the LORD that had been torn down.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 31, 'He took twelve stones, one to represent each of the tribes of Israel,', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 32, 'and he used the stones to rebuild the LORD''s altar. Then he dug a trench around the altar large enough to hold about three gallons.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 33, 'He piled wood on the altar, cut the bull into pieces, and laid the pieces on the wood. Then he said, "Fill four large jars with water, and pour the water over the offering and the wood." After they had done this,', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 34, 'he said, "Do the same thing again!" And when they were finished, he said, "Now do it a third time!" So they did as he said,', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 35, 'and the water ran around the altar and even overflowed the trench.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 36, 'At the customary time for offering the evening sacrifice, Elijah the prophet walked up to the altar and prayed, "O LORD, God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, prove today that you are God in Israel and that I am your servant. Prove that I have done all this at your command.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 37, 'O LORD, answer me! Answer me so these people will know that you, O LORD, are God and that you have brought them back to yourself."', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 38, 'Immediately the fire of the LORD flashed down from heaven and burned up the young bull, the wood, the stones, and the dust. It even licked up all the water in the ditch!', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 39, 'And when the people saw it, they fell on their faces and cried out, "The LORD is God! The LORD is God!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 40, 'Then Elijah commanded, "Seize all the prophets of Baal. Don''t let a single one escape!" So the people seized them all, and Elijah took them down to the Kishon Valley and killed them there.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 41, 'Then Elijah said to Ahab, "Go and enjoy a good meal! For I hear a mighty rainstorm coming!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 42, 'So Ahab prepared a feast. But Elijah climbed to the top of Mount Carmel and fell to the ground and prayed.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 43, 'Then he said to his servant, "Go and look out toward the sea." The servant went and looked, but he returned to Elijah and said, "I didn''t see anything." Seven times Elijah told him to go and look, and seven times he went.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 44, 'Finally the seventh time, his servant told him, "I saw a little cloud about the size of a hand rising from the sea." Then Elijah shouted, "Hurry to Ahab and tell him, `Climb into your chariot and go back home. If you don''t hurry, the rain will stop you!''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 45, 'And sure enough, the sky was soon black with clouds. A heavy wind brought a terrific rainstorm, and Ahab left quickly for Jezreel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 18, 46, 'Now the LORD gave special strength to Elijah. He tucked his cloak into his belt and ran ahead of Ahab''s chariot all the way to the entrance of Jezreel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 1, 'When Ahab got home, he told Jezebel what Elijah had done and that he had slaughtered the prophets of Baal.', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 2, 'So Jezebel sent this message to Elijah: "May the gods also kill me if by this time tomorrow I have failed to take your life like those whom you killed."', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 3, 'Elijah was afraid and fled for his life. He went to Beersheba, a town in Judah, and he left his servant there.', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 4, 'Then he went on alone into the desert, traveling all day. He sat down under a solitary broom tree and prayed that he might die. "I have had enough, LORD," he said. "Take my life, for I am no better than my ancestors."', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 5, 'Then he lay down and slept under the broom tree. But as he was sleeping, an angel touched him and told him, "Get up and eat!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 6, 'He looked around and saw some bread baked on hot stones and a jar of water! So he ate and drank and lay down again.', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 7, 'Then the angel of the LORD came again and touched him and said, "Get up and eat some more, for there is a long journey ahead of you."', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 8, 'So he got up and ate and drank, and the food gave him enough strength to travel forty days and forty nights to Mount Sinai, the mountain of God.', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 9, 'There he came to a cave, where he spent the night. But the LORD said to him, "What are you doing here, Elijah?"', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 10, 'Elijah replied, "I have zealously served the LORD God Almighty. But the people of Israel have broken their covenant with you, torn down your altars, and killed every one of your prophets. I alone am left, and now they are trying to kill me, too."', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 11, '"Go out and stand before me on the mountain," the LORD told him. And as Elijah stood there, the LORD passed by, and a mighty windstorm hit the mountain. It was such a terrible blast that the rocks were torn loose, but the LORD was not in the wind. After the wind there was an earthquake, but the LORD was not in the earthquake.', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 12, 'And after the earthquake there was a fire, but the LORD was not in the fire. And after the fire there was the sound of a gentle whisper.', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 13, 'When Elijah heard it, he wrapped his face in his cloak and went out and stood at the entrance of the cave. And a voice said, "What are you doing here, Elijah?"', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 14, 'He replied again, "I have zealously served the LORD God Almighty. But the people of Israel have broken their covenant with you, torn down your altars, and killed every one of your prophets. I alone am left, and now they are trying to kill me, too."', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 15, 'Then the LORD told him, "Go back the way you came, and travel to the wilderness of Damascus. When you arrive there, anoint Hazael to be king of Aram.', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 16, 'Then anoint Jehu son of Nimshi to be king of Israel, and anoint Elisha son of Shaphat from Abel-meholah to replace you as my prophet.', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 17, 'Anyone who escapes from Hazael will be killed by Jehu, and those who escape Jehu will be killed by Elisha!', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 18, 'Yet I will preserve seven thousand others in Israel who have never bowed to Baal or kissed him!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 19, 'So Elijah went and found Elisha son of Shaphat plowing a field with a team of oxen. There were eleven teams of oxen ahead of him, and he was plowing with the twelfth team. Elijah went over to him and threw his cloak across his shoulders and walked away again.', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 20, 'Elisha left the oxen standing there, ran after Elijah, and said to him, "First let me go and kiss my father and mother good-bye, and then I will go with you!" Elijah replied, "Go on back! But consider what I have done to you."', 'NLT'),
(15, 19, 21, 'Elisha then returned to his oxen, killed them, and used the wood from the plow to build a fire to roast their flesh. He passed around the meat to the other plowmen, and they all ate. Then he went with Elijah as his assistant.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 1, 'Now King Ben-hadad of Aram mobilized his army, supported by the chariots and horses of thirty-two allied kings. They went to besiege Samaria, the Israelite capital, and launched attacks against it.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 2, 'Ben-hadad sent messengers into the city to relay this message to King Ahab of Israel: "This is what Ben-hadad says:', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 3, '`Your silver and gold are mine, and so are the best of your wives and children!''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 4, '"All right, my lord," Ahab replied. "All that I have is yours!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 5, 'Soon Ben-hadad''s messengers returned again and said, "This is what Ben-hadad says: `I have already demanded that you give me your silver, gold, wives, and children.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 6, 'But about this time tomorrow I will send my officials to search your palace and the homes of your people. They will take away everything you consider valuable!''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 7, 'Then Ahab summoned all the leaders of the land and said to them, "Look how this man is stirring up trouble! I already agreed when he sent the message demanding that I give him my wives and children and silver and gold."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 8, '"Don''t give in to any more demands," the leaders and people advised.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 9, 'So Ahab told the messengers from Ben-hadad, "Say this to my lord the king: `I will give you everything you asked for the first time, but this last demand of yours I simply cannot meet.''" So the messengers returned to Ben-hadad with the response.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 10, 'Then Ben-hadad sent this message to Ahab: "May the gods bring tragedy on me, and even worse than that, if there remains enough dust from Samaria to provide more than a handful for each of my soldiers."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 11, 'The king of Israel sent back this answer: "A warrior still dressing for battle should not boast like a warrior who has already won."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 12, 'This reply of Ahab''s reached Ben-hadad and the other kings as they were drinking in their tents. "Prepare to attack!" Ben-hadad commanded his officers. So they prepared to attack the city.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 13, 'Then a prophet came to see King Ahab and told him, "This is what the LORD says: Do you see all these enemy forces? Today I will hand them all over to you. Then you will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 14, 'Ahab asked, "How will he do it?" And the prophet replied, "This is what the LORD says: The troops of the provincial commanders will do it.Should we attack first?" Ahab asked. "Yes," the prophet answered.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 15, 'So Ahab mustered the troops of the 232 provincial commanders. Then he called out the rest of his army of seven thousand men.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 16, 'About noontime, as Ben-hadad and the thirty-two allied kings were still in their tents getting drunk,', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 17, 'the troops of the provincial commanders marched out of the city. As they approached, Ben-hadad''s scouts reported to him, "Some troops are coming from Samaria."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 18, '"Take them alive," Ben-hadad commanded, "whether they have come for peace or for war."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 19, 'But by now Ahab''s provincial commanders had led the army out to fight.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 20, 'Each Israelite soldier killed his Aramean opponent, and suddenly the entire Aramean army panicked and fled. The Israelites chased them, but King Ben-hadad and a few others escaped on horses.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 21, 'However, the other horses and chariots were destroyed, and the Arameans were killed in a great slaughter.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 22, 'Afterward the prophet said to King Ahab, "Get ready for another attack by the king of Aram next spring."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 23, 'After their defeat, Ben-hadad''s officers said to him, "The Israelite gods are gods of the hills; that is why they won. But we can beat them easily on the plains.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 24, 'Only this time replace the kings with field commanders!', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 25, 'Recruit another army like the one you lost. Give us the same number of horses, chariots, and men, and we will fight against them in the plains. There''s not a shadow of a doubt that we will beat them." So King Ben-hadad did as they suggested.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 26, 'The following spring he called up the Aramean army and marched out against Israel, this time at Aphek.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 27, 'Israel then mustered its army, set up supply lines, and moved into the battle. But the Israelite army looked like two little flocks of goats in comparison to the vast Aramean forces that filled the countryside!', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 28, 'Then the man of God went to the king of Israel and said, "This is what the LORD says: The Arameans have said that the LORD is a god of the hills and not of the plains. So I will help you defeat this vast army. Then you will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 29, 'The two armies camped opposite each other for seven days, and on the seventh day the battle began. The Israelites killed 100,000 Aramean foot soldiers in one day.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 30, 'The rest fled behind the walls of Aphek, but the wall fell on them and killed another 27,000. Ben-hadad fled into the city and hid in a secret room.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 31, 'Ben-hadad''s officers said to him, "Sir, we have heard that the kings of Israel are very merciful. So let''s humble ourselves by wearing sackcloth and putting ropes on our heads. Then perhaps King Ahab will let you live."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 32, 'So they put on sackcloth and ropes and went to the king of Israel and begged, "Your servant Ben-hadad says, `Please let me live!''" The king of Israel responded, "Is he still alive? He is my brother!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 33, 'The men were quick to grasp at this straw of hope, and they replied, "Yes, your brother Ben-hadad!Go and get him," the king of Israel told them. And when Ben-hadad arrived, Ahab invited him up into his chariot!', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 34, 'Ben-hadad told him, "I will give back the towns my father took from your father, and you may establish places of trade in Damascus, as my father did in Samaria." Then Ahab said, "I will let you go under these conditions." So they made a treaty, and Ben-hadad was set free.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 35, 'Meanwhile, the LORD instructed one of the group of prophets to say to another man, "Strike me!" But the man refused to strike the prophet.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 36, 'Then the prophet told him, "Because you have not obeyed the voice of the LORD, a lion will kill you as soon as you leave me." And sure enough, when he had gone, a lion attacked and killed him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 37, 'Then the prophet turned to another man and said, "Strike me!" So he struck the prophet and wounded him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 38, 'The prophet waited for the king beside the road, having placed a bandage over his eyes to disguise himself.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 39, 'As the king passed by, the prophet called out to him, "Sir, I was in the battle, and a man brought me a prisoner. He said, `Guard this man; if for any reason he gets away, you will either die or pay a fine of seventy-five pounds of silver!''', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 40, 'But while I was busy doing something else, the prisoner disappeared!Well, it''s your own fault," the king replied. "You have determined your own judgment."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 41, 'Then the prophet pulled the bandage from his eyes, and the king of Israel recognized him as one of the prophets.', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 42, 'And the prophet told him, "This is what the LORD says: Because you have spared the man I said must be destroyed, now you must die in his place, and your people will die instead of his people."', 'NLT'),
(15, 20, 43, 'So the king of Israel went home to Samaria angry and sullen.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 1, 'King Ahab had a palace in Jezreel, and near the palace was a vineyard owned by a man named Naboth.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 2, 'One day Ahab said to Naboth, "Since your vineyard is so convenient to the palace, I would like to buy it to use as a vegetable garden. I will give you a better vineyard in exchange, or if you prefer, I will pay you for it."', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 3, 'But Naboth replied, "The LORD forbid that I should give you the inheritance that was passed down by my ancestors."', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 4, 'So Ahab went home angry and sullen because of Naboth''s answer. The king went to bed with his face to the wall and refused to eat!', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 5, '"What in the world is the matter?" his wife, Jezebel, asked him. "What has made you so upset that you are not eating?"', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 6, '"I asked Naboth to sell me his vineyard or to trade it, and he refused!" Ahab told her.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 7, '"Are you the king of Israel or not?" Jezebel asked. "Get up and eat and don''t worry about it. I''ll get you Naboth''s vineyard!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 8, 'So she wrote letters in Ahab''s name, sealed them with his seal, and sent them to the elders and other leaders of the city where Naboth lived.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 9, 'In her letters she commanded: "Call the citizens together for fasting and prayer and give Naboth a place of honor.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 10, 'Find two scoundrels who will accuse him of cursing God and the king. Then take him out and stone him to death."', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 11, 'So the elders and other leaders followed the instructions Jezebel had written in the letters.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 12, 'They called for a fast and put Naboth at a prominent place before the people.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 13, 'Then two scoundrels accused him before all the people of cursing God and the king. So he was dragged outside the city and stoned to death.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 14, 'The city officials then sent word to Jezebel, "Naboth has been stoned to death."', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 15, 'When Jezebel heard the news, she said to Ahab, "You know the vineyard Naboth wouldn''t sell you? Well, you can have it now! He''s dead!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 16, 'So Ahab immediately went down to the vineyard to claim it.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 17, 'But the LORD said to Elijah, who was from Tishbe,', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 18, '"Go down to meet King Ahab, who rules in Samaria. He will be at Naboth''s vineyard in Jezreel, taking possession of it.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 19, 'Give him this message: `This is what the LORD says: Isn''t killing Naboth bad enough? Must you rob him, too? Because you have done this, dogs will lick your blood outside the city just as they licked the blood of Naboth!''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 20, '"So my enemy has found me!" Ahab exclaimed to Elijah. "Yes," Elijah answered, "I have come because you have sold yourself to what is evil in the LORD''s sight.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 21, 'The LORD is going to bring disaster to you and sweep you away. He will not let a single one of your male descendants, slave or free alike, survive in Israel!', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 22, 'He is going to destroy your family as he did the family of Jeroboam son of Nebat and the family of Baasha son of Ahijah, for you have made him very angry and have led all of Israel into sin.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 23, 'The LORD has also told me that the dogs of Jezreel will eat the body of your wife, Jezebel, at the city wall.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 24, 'The members of your family who die in the city will be eaten by dogs, and those who die in the field will be eaten by vultures."', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 25, 'No one else so completely sold himself to what was evil in the LORD''s sight as did Ahab, for his wife, Jezebel, influenced him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 26, 'He was especially guilty because he worshiped idols just as the Amorites had done--the people whom the LORD had driven from the land ahead of the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 27, 'When Ahab heard this message, he tore his clothing, dressed in sackcloth, and fasted. He even slept in sackcloth and went about in deep mourning.', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 28, 'Then another message from the LORD came to Elijah, who was from Tishbe:', 'NLT'),
(15, 21, 29, '"Do you see how Ahab has humbled himself before me? Because he has done this, I will not do what I promised during his lifetime. It will happen to his sons; I will destroy all his descendants."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 1, 'For three years there was no war between Aram and Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 2, 'Then during the third year, King Jehoshaphat of Judah went to visit King Ahab of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 3, 'During the visit, Ahab said to his officials, "Do you realize that the Arameans are still occupying our city of Ramoth-gilead? And we haven''t done a thing about it!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 4, 'Then he turned to Jehoshaphat and asked, "Will you join me in fighting against Ramoth-gilead?" And Jehoshaphat replied to King Ahab, "Why, of course! You and I are brothers, and my troops are yours to command. Even my horses are at your service."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 5, 'Then Jehoshaphat added, "But first let''s find out what the LORD says."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 6, 'So King Ahab summoned his prophets, about four hundred of them, and asked them, "Should I go to war against Ramoth-gilead or not?" They all replied, "Go right ahead! The Lord will give you a glorious victory!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 7, 'But Jehoshaphat asked, "Isn''t there a prophet of the LORD around, too? I would like to ask him the same question."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 8, 'King Ahab replied, "There is still one prophet of the LORD, but I hate him. He never prophesies anything but bad news for me! His name is Micaiah son of Imlah.You shouldn''t talk like that," Jehoshaphat said. "Let''s hear what he has to say."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 9, 'So the king of Israel called one of his officials and said, "Quick! Go and get Micaiah son of Imlah."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 10, 'King Ahab of Israel and King Jehoshaphat of Judah, dressed in their royal robes, were sitting on thrones at the threshing floor near the gate of Samaria. All of Ahab''s prophets were prophesying there in front of them.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 11, 'One of them, Zedekiah son of Kenaanah, made some iron horns and proclaimed, "This is what the LORD says: With these horns you will gore the Arameans to death!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 12, 'All the other prophets agreed. "Yes," they said, "go up to Ramoth-gilead and be victorious, for the LORD will give you victory!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 13, 'Meanwhile, the messenger who went to get Micaiah said to him, "Look, all the prophets are promising victory for the king. Be sure that you agree with them and promise success."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 14, 'But Micaiah replied, "As surely as the LORD lives, I will say only what the LORD tells me to say."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 15, 'When Micaiah arrived before the king, Ahab asked him, "Micaiah, should we go to war against Ramoth-gilead or not?" And Micaiah replied, "Go right ahead! The LORD will give the king a glorious victory!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 16, 'But the king replied sharply, "How many times must I demand that you speak only the truth when you speak for the LORD?"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 17, 'So Micaiah told him, "In a vision I saw all Israel scattered on the mountains, like sheep without a shepherd. And the LORD said, `Their master has been killed. Send them home in peace.''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 18, '"Didn''t I tell you?" the king of Israel said to Jehoshaphat. "He does it every time. He never prophesies anything but bad news for me."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 19, 'Then Micaiah continued, "Listen to what the LORD says! I saw the LORD sitting on his throne with all the armies of heaven around him, on his right and on his left.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 20, 'And the LORD said, `Who can entice Ahab to go into battle against Ramoth-gilead so that he can be killed there?'' There were many suggestions,', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 21, 'until finally a spirit approached the LORD and said, `I can do it!''', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 22, '" `How will you do this?'' the LORD asked. "And the spirit replied, `I will go out and inspire all Ahab''s prophets to speak lies.''" `You will succeed,'' said the LORD. `Go ahead and do it.''', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 23, '"So you see, the LORD has put a lying spirit in the mouths of your prophets. For the LORD has determined disaster for you."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 24, 'Then Zedekiah son of Kenaanah walked up to Micaiah and slapped him across the face. "When did the Spirit of the LORD leave me to speak to you?" he demanded.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 25, 'And Micaiah replied, "You will find out soon enough when you find yourself hiding in some secret room!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 26, 'King Ahab of Israel then ordered, "Arrest Micaiah and take him back to Amon, the governor of the city, and to my son Joash.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 27, 'Give them this order from the king: `Put this man in prison, and feed him nothing but bread and water until I return safely from the battle!''"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 28, 'But Micaiah replied, "If you return safely, the LORD has not spoken through me!" Then he added to those standing around, "Take note of what I have said."', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 29, 'So the king of Israel and King Jehoshaphat of Judah led their armies against Ramoth-gilead.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 30, 'Now King Ahab said to Jehoshaphat, "As we go into battle, I will disguise myself so no one will recognize me, but you wear your royal robes." So Ahab disguised himself, and they went into battle.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 31, 'Now the king of Aram had issued these orders to his thirty-two charioteers: "Attack only the king of Israel!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 32, 'So when the Aramean charioteers saw Jehoshaphat in his royal robes, they went after him. "There is the king of Israel!" they shouted. But when Jehoshaphat cried out,', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 33, 'the charioteers realized he was not the king of Israel, and they stopped chasing him.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 34, 'An Aramean soldier, however, randomly shot an arrow at the Israelite troops, and the arrow hit the king of Israel between the joints of his armor. "Get me out of here!" Ahab groaned to the driver of his chariot. "I have been badly wounded!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 35, 'The battle raged all that day, and Ahab was propped up in his chariot facing the Arameans. The blood from his wound ran down to the floor of his chariot, and as evening arrived he died.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 36, 'Just as the sun was setting, the cry ran through his troops: "It''s all over--return home!"', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 37, 'So the king died, and his body was taken to Samaria and buried there.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 38, 'Then his chariot was washed beside the pool of Samaria, where the prostitutes bathed, and dogs came and licked the king''s blood, just as the LORD had promised.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 39, 'The rest of the events in Ahab''s reign and the story of the ivory palace and the cities he built are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 40, 'When Ahab died, he was buried among his ancestors. Then his son Ahaziah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 41, 'Jehoshaphat son of Asa began to rule over Judah in the fourth year of King Ahab''s reign in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 42, 'He was thirty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem twenty-five years. His mother was Azubah, the daughter of Shilhi.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 43, 'Jehoshaphat was a good king, following the example of his father, Asa. He did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight. During his reign, however, he failed to remove all the pagan shrines, and the people still offered sacrifices and burned incense there.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 44, 'Jehoshaphat also made peace with the king of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 45, 'The rest of the events in Jehoshaphat''s reign, the extent of his power, and the wars he waged are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 46, 'He banished from the land the rest of the shrine prostitutes, who still continued their practices from the days of his father, Asa.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 47, 'There was no king in Edom at that time, only a deputy.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 48, 'Jehoshaphat also built a fleet of trading ships to sail to Ophir for gold. But the ships never set sail, for they were wrecked at Ezion-geber.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 49, 'At that time Ahaziah son of Ahab proposed to Jehoshaphat, "Let my men sail an expedition with your men." But Jehoshaphat refused the offer.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 50, 'When Jehoshaphat died, he was buried with his ancestors in the City of David. Then his son Jehoram became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 51, 'Ahaziah son of Ahab began to rule over Israel in the seventeenth year of King Jehoshaphat''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria two years.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 52, 'But he did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, following the example of his father and mother and the example of Jeroboam son of Nebat, who had led Israel into the sin of idolatry.', 'NLT'),
(15, 22, 53, 'He served Baal and worshiped him, arousing the anger of the LORD, the God of Israel, just as his father had done.', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 1, 'After King Ahab''s death, the nation of Moab declared its independence from Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 2, 'One day Israel''s new king, Ahaziah, fell through the latticework of an upper room at his palace in Samaria, and he was seriously injured. So he sent messengers to the temple of Baal-zebub, the god of Ekron, to ask whether he would recover.', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 3, 'But the angel of the LORD told Elijah, who was from Tishbe, "Go and meet the messengers of the king of Samaria and ask them, `Why are you going to Baal-zebub, the god of Ekron, to ask whether the king will get well? Is there no God in Israel?', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 4, 'Now, therefore, this is what the LORD says: You will never leave the bed on which you are lying, but you will surely die.''" So Elijah went to deliver the message.', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 5, 'When the messengers returned to the king, he asked them, "Why have you returned so soon?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 6, 'They replied, "A man came up to us and said, `Go back to the king and give him this message from the LORD: Why are you sending men to Baal-zebub, the god of Ekron, to ask whether you will get well? Is there no God in Israel? Now, since you have done this, you will never leave the bed on which you are lying, but you will surely die.''"', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 7, '"Who was this man?" the king demanded. "What did he look like?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 8, 'They replied, "He was a hairy man, and he wore a leather belt around his waist.It was Elijah from Tishbe!" the king exclaimed.', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 9, 'Then he sent an army captain with fifty soldiers to arrest him. They found him sitting on top of a hill. The captain said to him, "Man of God, the king has commanded you to come along with us."', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 10, 'But Elijah replied to the captain, "If I am a man of God, let fire come down from heaven and destroy you and your fifty men!" Then fire fell from heaven and killed them all.', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 11, 'So the king sent another captain with fifty men. The captain said to him, "Man of God, the king says that you must come down right away."', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 12, 'Elijah replied, "If I am a man of God, let fire come down from heaven and destroy you and your fifty men!" And again the fire of God fell from heaven and killed them all.', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 13, 'Once more the king sent a captain with fifty men. But this time the captain fell to his knees before Elijah. He pleaded with him, "O man of God, please spare my life and the lives of these, your fifty servants.', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 14, 'See how the fire from heaven has destroyed the first two groups. But now please spare my life!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 15, 'Then the angel of the LORD said to Elijah, "Don''t be afraid. Go with him." So Elijah got up and went to the king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 16, 'And Elijah said to the king, "This is what the LORD says: Why did you send messengers to Baal-zebub, the god of Ekron, to ask whether you will get well? Is there no God in Israel? Now, since you have done this, you will never leave the bed on which you are lying, but you will surely die."', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 17, 'So Ahaziah died, just as the LORD had promised through Elijah. Since Ahaziah did not have a son to succeed him, his brother Joram became the next king. This took place in the second year of the reign of Jehoram son of Jehoshaphat, king of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 1, 18, 'The rest of the events in Ahaziah''s reign are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 1, 'When the LORD was about to take Elijah up to heaven in a whirlwind, Elijah and Elisha were traveling from Gilgal.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 2, 'And Elijah said to Elisha, "Stay here, for the LORD has told me to go to Bethel." But Elisha replied, "As surely as the LORD lives and you yourself live, I will never leave you!" So they went on together to Bethel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 3, 'The group of prophets from Bethel came to Elisha and asked him, "Did you know that the LORD is going to take your master away from you today?Quiet!" Elisha answered. "Of course I know it."', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 4, 'Then Elijah said to Elisha, "Stay here, for the LORD has told me to go to Jericho." But Elisha replied again, "As surely as the LORD lives and you yourself live, I will never leave you." So they went on together to Jericho.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 5, 'Then the group of prophets from Jericho came to Elisha and asked him, "Did you know that the LORD is going to take your master away from you today?Quiet!" he answered again. "Of course I know it."', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 6, 'Then Elijah said to Elisha, "Stay here, for the LORD has told me to go to the Jordan River." But again Elisha replied, "As surely as the LORD lives and you yourself live, I will never leave you." So they went on together.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 7, 'Fifty men from the group of prophets also went and watched from a distance as Elijah and Elisha stopped beside the Jordan River.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 8, 'Then Elijah folded his cloak together and struck the water with it. The river divided, and the two of them went across on dry ground!', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 9, 'When they came to the other side, Elijah said to Elisha, "What can I do for you before I am taken away?" And Elisha replied, "Please let me become your rightful successor."', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 10, '"You have asked a difficult thing," Elijah replied. "If you see me when I am taken from you, then you will get your request. But if not, then you won''t."', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 11, 'As they were walking along and talking, suddenly a chariot of fire appeared, drawn by horses of fire. It drove between them, separating them, and Elijah was carried by a whirlwind into heaven.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 12, 'Elisha saw it and cried out, "My father! My father! The chariots and charioteers of Israel!" And as they disappeared from sight, Elisha tore his robe in two.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 13, 'Then Elisha picked up Elijah''s cloak and returned to the bank of the Jordan River.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 14, 'He struck the water with the cloak and cried out, "Where is the LORD, the God of Elijah?" Then the river divided, and Elisha went across.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 15, 'When the group of prophets from Jericho saw what happened, they exclaimed, "Elisha has become Elijah''s successor!" And they went to meet him and bowed down before him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 16, '"Sir," they said, "just say the word and fifty of our strongest men will search the wilderness for your master. Perhaps the Spirit of the LORD has left him on some mountain or in some valley.No," Elisha said, "don''t send them."', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 17, 'But they kept urging him until he was embarrassed, and he finally said, "All right, send them." So fifty men searched for three days but did not find Elijah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 18, 'Elisha was still at Jericho when they returned. "Didn''t I tell you not to go?" he asked.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 19, 'Now the leaders of the town of Jericho visited Elisha. "We have a problem, my lord," they told him. "This town is located in beautiful natural surroundings, as you can see. But the water is bad, and the land is unproductive."', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 20, 'Elisha said, "Bring me a new bowl with salt in it." So they brought it to him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 21, 'Then he went out to the spring that supplied the town with water and threw the salt into it. And he said, "This is what the LORD says: I have made this water wholesome. It will no longer cause death or infertility. "', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 22, 'And sure enough! The water has remained wholesome ever since, just as Elisha said.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 23, 'Elisha left Jericho and went up to Bethel. As he was walking along the road, a group of boys from the town began mocking and making fun of him. "Go away, you baldhead!" they chanted. "Go away, you baldhead!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 24, 'Elisha turned around and looked at them, and he cursed them in the name of the LORD. Then two bears came out of the woods and mauled forty-two of them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 2, 25, 'From there Elisha went to Mount Carmel and finally returned to Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 1, 'Ahab''s son Joram began to rule over Israel in the eighteenth year of King Jehoshaphat''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria twelve years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 2, 'He did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, but he was not as wicked as his father and mother. He at least tore down the sacred pillar of Baal that his father had set up.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 3, 'Nevertheless he continued in the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led the people of Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 4, 'King Mesha of Moab and his people were sheep breeders. They used to pay the king of Israel an annual tribute of 100,000 lambs and the wool of 100,000 rams.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 5, 'But after Ahab''s death, the king of Moab rebelled against the king of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 6, 'So King Joram mustered the army of Israel and marched from Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 7, 'On the way, he sent this message to King Jehoshaphat of Judah: "The king of Moab has rebelled against me. Will you help me fight him?" And Jehoshaphat replied, "Why, of course! You and I are brothers, and my troops are yours to command. Even my horses are at your service."', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 8, 'Then Jehoshaphat asked, "What route will we take?We will attack from the wilderness of Edom," Joram replied.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 9, 'The king of Edom and his troops joined them, and all three armies traveled along a roundabout route through the wilderness for seven days. But there was no water for the men or their pack animals.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 10, '"What should we do?" the king of Israel cried out. "The LORD has brought the three of us here to let the king of Moab defeat us."', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 11, 'But King Jehoshaphat of Judah asked, "Is there no prophet of the LORD with us? If there is, we can ask the LORD what to do." One of King Joram''s officers replied, "Elisha son of Shaphat is here. He used to be Elijah''s personal assistant. "', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 12, 'Jehoshaphat said, "Then the LORD will speak through him." So the kings of Israel, Judah, and Edom went to consult with Elisha.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 13, '"I want no part of you," Elisha said to the king of Israel. "Go to the pagan prophets of your father and mother!" But King Joram said, "No! For it was the LORD who called us three kings here to be destroyed by the king of Moab!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 14, 'Elisha replied, "As surely as the LORD Almighty lives, whom I serve, I would not bother with you except for my respect for King Jehoshaphat of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 15, 'Now bring me someone who can play the harp." While the harp was being played, the power of the LORD came upon Elisha,', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 16, 'and he said, "This is what the LORD says: This dry valley will be filled with pools of water!', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 17, 'You will see neither wind nor rain, says the LORD, but this valley will be filled with water. You will have plenty for yourselves and for your cattle and your other animals.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 18, 'But this is only a simple thing for the LORD, for he will make you victorious over the army of Moab!', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 19, 'You will conquer the best of their cities, even the fortified ones. You will cut down all their trees, stop up all their springs, and ruin all their good land with stones."', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 20, 'And sure enough, the next day at about the time when the morning sacrifice was offered, water suddenly appeared! It was flowing from the direction of Edom, and soon there was water everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 21, 'Meanwhile, when the people of Moab heard about the three armies marching against them, they mobilized every man who could fight, young and old, and stationed themselves along their border.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 22, 'But when they got up the next morning, the sun was shining across the water, making it look as red as blood.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 23, '"It''s blood!" the Moabites exclaimed. "The three armies have attacked and killed each other! Let''s go and collect the plunder!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 24, 'When they arrived at the Israelite camp, the army of Israel rushed out and attacked the Moabites, who turned and ran. The army of Israel chased them into the land of Moab, destroying everything as they went.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 25, 'They destroyed the cities, covered their good land with stones, stopped up the springs, and cut down the good trees. Finally, only Kir-hareseth was left, but even that came under attack.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 26, 'When the king of Moab saw that he was losing the battle, he led seven hundred of his warriors in a desperate attempt to break through the enemy lines near the king of Edom, but they failed to escape.', 'NLT'),
(16, 3, 27, 'So he took his oldest son, who would have been the next king, and sacrificed him as a burnt offering on the wall. As a result, the anger against Israel was great, so they withdrew and returned to their own land.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 1, 'One day the widow of one of Elisha''s fellow prophets came to Elisha and cried out to him, "My husband who served you is dead, and you know how he feared the LORD. But now a creditor has come, threatening to take my two sons as slaves."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 2, '"What can I do to help you?" Elisha asked. "Tell me, what do you have in the house?Nothing at all, except a flask of olive oil," she replied.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 3, 'And Elisha said, "Borrow as many empty jars as you can from your friends and neighbors.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 4, 'Then go into your house with your sons and shut the door behind you. Pour olive oil from your flask into the jars, setting the jars aside as they are filled."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 5, 'So she did as she was told. Her sons brought many jars to her, and she filled one after another.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 6, 'Soon every container was full to the brim! "Bring me another jar," she said to one of her sons. "There aren''t any more!" he told her. And then the olive oil stopped flowing.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 7, 'When she told the man of God what had happened, he said to her, "Now sell the olive oil and pay your debts, and there will be enough money left over to support you and your sons."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 8, 'One day Elisha went to the town of Shunem. A wealthy woman lived there, and she invited him to eat some food. From then on, whenever he passed that way, he would stop there to eat.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 9, 'She said to her husband, "I am sure this man who stops in from time to time is a holy man of God.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 10, 'Let''s make a little room for him on the roof and furnish it with a bed, a table, a chair, and a lamp. Then he will have a place to stay whenever he comes by."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 11, 'One day Elisha returned to Shunem, and he went up to his room to rest.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 12, 'He said to his servant Gehazi, "Tell the woman I want to speak to her." When she arrived,', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 13, 'Elisha said to Gehazi, "Tell her that we appreciate the kind concern she has shown us. Now ask her what we can do for her. Does she want me to put in a good word for her to the king or to the commander of the army?No," she replied, "my family takes good care of me."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 14, 'Later Elisha asked Gehazi, "What do you think we can do for her?" He suggested, "She doesn''t have a son, and her husband is an old man."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 15, '"Call her back again," Elisha told him. When the woman returned, Elisha said to her as she stood in the doorway,', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 16, '"Next year at about this time you will be holding a son in your arms!No, my lord!" she protested. "Please don''t lie to me like that, O man of God."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 17, 'But sure enough, the woman soon became pregnant. And at that time the following year she had a son, just as Elisha had said.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 18, 'One day when her child was older, he went out to visit his father, who was working with the harvesters.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 19, 'Suddenly he complained, "My head hurts! My head hurts!" His father said to one of the servants, "Carry him home to his mother."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 20, 'So the servant took him home, and his mother held him on her lap. But around noontime he died.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 21, 'She carried him up to the bed of the man of God, then shut the door and left him there.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 22, 'She sent a message to her husband: "Send one of the servants and a donkey so that I can hurry to the man of God and come right back."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 23, '"Why today?" he asked. "It is neither a new moon festival nor a Sabbath." But she said, "It''s all right."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 24, 'So she saddled the donkey and said to the servant, "Hurry! Don''t slow down on my account unless I tell you to."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 25, 'As she approached the man of God at Mount Carmel, Elisha saw her in the distance. He said to Gehazi, "Look, the woman from Shunem is coming.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 26, 'Run out to meet her and ask her, `Is everything all right with you, with your husband, and with your child?'' Yes," the woman told Gehazi, "everything is fine."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 27, 'But when she came to the man of God at the mountain, she fell to the ground before him and caught hold of his feet. Gehazi began to push her away, but the man of God said, "Leave her alone. Something is troubling her deeply, and the LORD has not told me what it is."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 28, 'Then she said, "It was you, my lord, who said I would have a son. And didn''t I tell you not to raise my hopes?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 29, 'Then Elisha said to Gehazi, "Get ready to travel; take my staff and go! Don''t talk to anyone along the way. Go quickly and lay the staff on the child''s face."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 30, 'But the boy''s mother said, "As surely as the LORD lives and you yourself live, I won''t go home unless you go with me." So Elisha returned with her.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 31, 'Gehazi hurried on ahead and laid the staff on the child''s face, but nothing happened. There was no sign of life. He returned to meet Elisha and told him, "The child is still dead."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 32, 'When Elisha arrived, the child was indeed dead, lying there on the prophet''s bed.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 33, 'He went in alone and shut the door behind him and prayed to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 34, 'Then he lay down on the child''s body, placing his mouth on the child''s mouth, his eyes on the child''s eyes, and his hands on the child''s hands. And the child''s body began to grow warm again!', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 35, 'Elisha got up and walked back and forth in the room a few times. Then he stretched himself out again on the child. This time the boy sneezed seven times and opened his eyes!', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 36, 'Then Elisha summoned Gehazi. "Call the child''s mother!" he said. And when she came in, Elisha said, "Here, take your son!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 37, 'She fell at his feet, overwhelmed with gratitude. Then she picked up her son and carried him downstairs.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 38, 'Elisha now returned to Gilgal, but there was a famine in the land. One day as the group of prophets was seated before him, he said to his servant, "Put on a large kettle and make some stew for these men."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 39, 'One of the young men went out into the field to gather vegetables and came back with a pocketful of wild gourds. He shredded them and put them into the kettle without realizing they were poisonous.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 40, 'But after the men had eaten a bite or two they cried out, "Man of God, there''s poison in this stew!" So they would not eat it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 41, 'Elisha said, "Bring me some flour." Then he threw it into the kettle and said, "Now it''s all right; go ahead and eat." And then it did not harm them!', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 42, 'One day a man from Baal-shalishah brought the man of God a sack of fresh grain and twenty loaves of barley bread made from the first grain of his harvest. Elisha said, "Give it to the group of prophets so they can eat."', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 43, '"What?" his servant exclaimed. "Feed one hundred people with only this?" But Elisha repeated, "Give it to the group of prophets so they can eat, for the LORD says there will be plenty for all. There will even be some left over!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 4, 44, 'And sure enough, there was plenty for all and some left over, just as the LORD had promised.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 1, 'The king of Aram had high admiration for Naaman, the commander of his army, because through him the LORD had given Aram great victories. But though Naaman was a mighty warrior, he suffered from leprosy.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 2, 'Now groups of Aramean raiders had invaded the land of Israel, and among their captives was a young girl who had been given to Naaman''s wife as a maid.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 3, 'One day the girl said to her mistress, "I wish my master would go to see the prophet in Samaria. He would heal him of his leprosy."', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 4, 'So Naaman told the king what the young girl from Israel had said.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 5, '"Go and visit the prophet," the king told him. "I will send a letter of introduction for you to carry to the king of Israel." So Naaman started out, taking as gifts 750 pounds of silver, 150 pounds of gold, and ten sets of clothing.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 6, 'The letter to the king of Israel said: "With this letter I present my servant Naaman. I want you to heal him of his leprosy."', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 7, 'When the king of Israel read it, he tore his clothes in dismay and said, "This man sends me a leper to heal! Am I God, that I can kill and give life? He is only trying to find an excuse to invade us again."', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 8, 'But when Elisha, the man of God, heard about the king''s reaction, he sent this message to him: "Why are you so upset? Send Naaman to me, and he will learn that there is a true prophet here in Israel."', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 9, 'So Naaman went with his horses and chariots and waited at the door of Elisha''s house.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 10, 'But Elisha sent a messenger out to him with this message: "Go and wash yourself seven times in the Jordan River. Then your skin will be restored, and you will be healed of leprosy."', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 11, 'But Naaman became angry and stalked away. "I thought he would surely come out to meet me!" he said. "I expected him to wave his hand over the leprosy and call on the name of the LORD his God and heal me!', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 12, 'Aren''t the Abana River and Pharpar River of Damascus better than all the rivers of Israel put together? Why shouldn''t I wash in them and be healed?" So Naaman turned and went away in a rage.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 13, 'But his officers tried to reason with him and said, "Sir, if the prophet had told you to do some great thing, wouldn''t you have done it? So you should certainly obey him when he says simply to go and wash and be cured!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 14, 'So Naaman went down to the Jordan River and dipped himself seven times, as the man of God had instructed him. And his flesh became as healthy as a young child''s, and he was healed!', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 15, 'Then Naaman and his entire party went back to find the man of God. They stood before him, and Naaman said, "I know at last that there is no God in all the world except in Israel. Now please accept my gifts."', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 16, 'But Elisha replied, "As surely as the LORD lives, whom I serve, I will not accept any gifts." And though Naaman urged him to take the gifts, Elisha refused.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 17, 'Then Naaman said, "All right, but please allow me to load two of my mules with earth from this place, and I will take it back home with me. From now on I will never again offer any burnt offerings or sacrifices to any other god except the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 18, 'However, may the LORD pardon me in this one thing. When my master the king goes into the temple of the god Rimmon to worship there and leans on my arm, may the LORD pardon me when I bow, too."', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 19, '"Go in peace," Elisha said. So Naaman started home again.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 20, 'But Gehazi, Elisha''s servant, said to himself, "My master should not have let this Aramean get away without accepting his gifts. As surely as the LORD lives, I will chase after him and get something from him."', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 21, 'So Gehazi set off after him. When Naaman saw him running after him, he climbed down from his chariot and went to meet him. "Is everything all right?" Naaman asked.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 22, '"Yes," Gehazi said, "but my master has sent me to tell you that two young prophets from the hill country of Ephraim have just arrived. He would like 75 pounds of silver and two sets of clothing to give to them."', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 23, '"By all means, take 150 pounds of silver," Naaman insisted. He gave him two sets of clothing, tied up the money in two bags, and sent two of his servants to carry the gifts for Gehazi.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 24, 'But when they arrived at the hill, Gehazi took the gifts from the servants and sent the men back. Then he hid the gifts inside the house.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 25, 'When he went in to his master, Elisha asked him, "Where have you been, Gehazi?I haven''t been anywhere," he replied.', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 26, 'But Elisha asked him, "Don''t you realize that I was there in spirit when Naaman stepped down from his chariot to meet you? Is this the time to receive money and clothing and olive groves and vineyards and sheep and oxen and servants?', 'NLT'),
(16, 5, 27, 'Because you have done this, you and your children and your children''s children will suffer from Naaman''s leprosy forever." When Gehazi left the room, he was leprous; his skin was as white as snow.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 1, 'One day the group of prophets came to Elisha and told him, "As you can see, this place where we meet with you is too small.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 2, 'Let''s go down to the Jordan River, where there are plenty of logs. There we can build a new place for us to meet.All right," he told them, "go ahead."', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 3, '"Please come with us," someone suggested. "I will," he said.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 4, 'When they arrived at the Jordan, they began cutting down trees.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 5, 'But as one of them was chopping, his ax head fell into the river. "Ah, my lord!" he cried. "It was a borrowed ax!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 6, '"Where did it fall?" the man of God asked. When he showed him the place, Elisha cut a stick and threw it into the water. Then the ax head rose to the surface and floated.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 7, '"Grab it," Elisha said to him. And the man reached out and grabbed it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 8, 'When the king of Aram was at war with Israel, he would confer with his officers and say, "We will mobilize our forces at such and such a place."', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 9, 'But immediately Elisha, the man of God, would warn the king of Israel, "Do not go near that place, for the Arameans are planning to mobilize their troops there."', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 10, 'So the king of Israel would send word to the place indicated by the man of God, warning the people there to be on their guard. This happened several times.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 11, 'The king of Aram became very upset over this. He called in his officers and demanded, "Which of you is the traitor? Who has been informing the king of Israel of my plans?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 12, '"It''s not us, my lord," one of the officers replied. "Elisha, the prophet in Israel, tells the king of Israel even the words you speak in the privacy of your bedroom!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 13, 'The king commanded, "Go and find out where Elisha is, and we will send troops to seize him." And the report came back: "Elisha is at Dothan."', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 14, 'So one night the king of Aram sent a great army with many chariots and horses to surround the city.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 15, 'When the servant of the man of God got up early the next morning and went outside, there were troops, horses, and chariots everywhere. "Ah, my lord, what will we do now?" he cried out to Elisha.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 16, '"Don''t be afraid!" Elisha told him. "For there are more on our side than on theirs!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 17, 'Then Elisha prayed, "O LORD, open his eyes and let him see!" The LORD opened his servant''s eyes, and when he looked up, he saw that the hillside around Elisha was filled with horses and chariots of fire.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 18, 'As the Aramean army advanced toward them, Elisha prayed, "O LORD, please make them blind." And the LORD did as Elisha asked.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 19, 'Then Elisha went out and told them, "You have come the wrong way! This isn''t the right city! Follow me, and I will take you to the man you are looking for." And he led them to Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 20, 'As soon as they had entered Samaria, Elisha prayed, "O LORD, now open their eyes and let them see." And the LORD did, and they discovered that they were in Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 21, 'When the king of Israel saw them, he shouted to Elisha, "My father, should I kill them?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 22, '"Of course not!" Elisha told him. "Do we kill prisoners of war? Give them food and drink and send them home again to their master."', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 23, 'So the king made a great feast for them and then sent them home to their king. After that, the Aramean raiders stayed away from the land of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 24, 'Some time later, however, King Ben-hadad of Aram mobilized his entire army and besieged Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 25, 'As a result there was a great famine in the city. After a while even a donkey''s head sold for two pounds of silver, and a cup of dove''s dung cost about two ounces of silver.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 26, 'One day as the king of Israel was walking along the wall of the city, a woman called to him, "Please help me, my lord the king!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 27, '"If the LORD doesn''t help you, what can I do?" he retorted. "I have neither food nor wine to give you."', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 28, 'But then the king asked, "What is the matter?" She replied, "This woman proposed that we eat my son one day and her son the next.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 29, 'So we cooked my son and ate him. Then the next day I said, `Kill your son so we can eat him,'' but she had hidden him."', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 30, 'When the king heard this, he tore his clothes in despair. And as the king walked along the wall, the people could see that he was wearing sackcloth underneath next to his skin.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 31, '"May God kill me if I don''t execute Elisha son of Shaphat this very day," the king vowed.', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 32, 'Elisha was sitting in his house at a meeting with the leaders of Israel when the king sent a messenger to summon him. But before the messenger arrived, Elisha said to the leaders, "A murderer has sent a man to kill me. When he arrives, shut the door and keep him out. His master will soon follow him."', 'NLT'),
(16, 6, 33, 'While Elisha was still saying this, the messenger arrived. And the king said, "It is the LORD who has brought this trouble on us! Why should I wait any longer for the LORD?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 1, 'Elisha replied, "Hear this message from the LORD! This is what the LORD says: By this time tomorrow in the markets of Samaria, five quarts of fine flour will cost only half an ounce of silver, and ten quarts of barley grain will cost only half an ounce of silver. "', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 2, 'The officer assisting the king said to the man of God, "That couldn''t happen even if the LORD opened the windows of heaven!" But Elisha replied, "You will see it happen, but you won''t be able to eat any of it!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 3, 'Now there were four men with leprosy sitting at the entrance of the city gates. "Why should we sit here waiting to die?" they asked each other.', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 4, '"We will starve if we stay here, and we will starve if we go back into the city. So we might as well go out and surrender to the Aramean army. If they let us live, so much the better. But if they kill us, we would have died anyway."', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 5, 'So that evening they went out to the camp of the Arameans, but no one was there!', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 6, 'For the Lord had caused the whole army of Aram to hear the clatter of speeding chariots and the galloping of horses and the sounds of a great army approaching. "The king of Israel has hired the Hittites and Egyptians to attack us!" they cried out.', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 7, 'So they panicked and fled into the night, abandoning their tents, horses, donkeys, and everything else, and they fled for their lives.', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 8, 'When the lepers arrived at the edge of the camp, they went into one tent after another, eating, drinking wine, and carrying out silver and gold and clothing and hiding it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 9, 'Finally, they said to each other, "This is not right. This is wonderful news, and we aren''t sharing it with anyone! If we wait until morning, some terrible calamity will certainly fall upon us. Come on, let''s go back and tell the people at the palace."', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 10, 'So they went back to the city and told the gatekeepers what had happened--that they had gone out to the Aramean camp and no one was there! The horses and donkeys were tethered and the tents were all in order, but there was not a single person around.', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 11, 'Then the gatekeepers shouted the news to the people in the palace.', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 12, 'The king got out of bed in the middle of the night and told his officers, "I know what has happened. The Arameans know we are starving, so they have left their camp and have hidden in the fields. They are expecting us to leave the city, and then they will take us alive and capture the city."', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 13, 'One of his officers replied, "We had better send out scouts to check into this. Let them take five of the remaining horses. If something happens to them, it won''t be a greater loss than if they stay here and die with the rest of us."', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 14, 'So two chariots with horses were prepared, and the king sent scouts to see what had happened to the Aramean army.', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 15, 'They went all the way to the Jordan River, following a trail of clothing and equipment that the Arameans had thrown away in their mad rush to escape. The scouts returned and told the king about it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 16, 'Then the people of Samaria rushed out and plundered the Aramean camp. So it was true that five quarts of fine flour were sold that day for half an ounce of silver, and ten quarts of barley grain were sold for half an ounce of silver, just as the LORD had promised.', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 17, 'The king appointed his officer to control the traffic at the gate, but he was knocked down and trampled to death as the people rushed out. So everything happened exactly as the man of God had predicted when the king came to his house.', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 18, 'The man of God had said to the king, "By this time tomorrow in the markets of Samaria, five quarts of fine flour will cost half an ounce of silver, and ten quarts of barley grain will cost half an ounce of silver."', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 19, 'The king''s officer had replied, "That couldn''t happen even if the LORD opened the windows of heaven!" And the man of God had said, "You will see it happen, but you won''t be able to eat any of it!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 7, 20, 'And so it was, for the people trampled him to death at the gate!', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 1, 'Elisha had told the woman whose son he had brought back to life, "Take your family and move to some other place, for the LORD has called for a famine on Israel that will last for seven years."', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 2, 'So the woman did as the man of God instructed. She took her family and lived in the land of the Philistines for seven years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 3, 'After the famine ended she returned to the land of Israel, and she went to see the king about getting back her house and land.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 4, 'As she came in, the king was talking with Gehazi, the servant of the man of God. The king had just said, "Tell me some stories about the great things Elisha has done."', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 5, 'And Gehazi was telling the king about the time Elisha had brought a boy back to life. At that very moment, the mother of the boy walked in to make her appeal to the king. "Look, my lord!" Gehazi exclaimed. "Here is the woman now, and this is her son--the very one Elisha brought back to life!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 6, '"Is this true?" the king asked her. And she told him that it was. So he directed one of his officials to see to it that everything she had lost was restored to her, including the value of any crops that had been harvested during her absence.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 7, 'Now Elisha went to Damascus, the capital of Aram, where King Ben-hadad lay sick. Someone told the king that the man of God had come.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 8, 'When the king heard the news, he said to Hazael, "Take a gift to the man of God. Then tell him to ask the LORD if I will get well again."', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 9, 'So Hazael loaded down forty camels with the finest products of Damascus as a gift for Elisha. He went in to him and said, "Your servant Ben-hadad, the king of Aram, has sent me to ask you if he will recover."', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 10, 'And Elisha replied, "Go and tell him, `You will recover.'' But the LORD has shown me that he will actually die!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 11, 'Elisha stared at Hazael with a fixed gaze until Hazael became uneasy. Then the man of God started weeping.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 12, '"What''s the matter, my lord?" Hazael asked him. Elisha replied, "I know the terrible things you will do to the people of Israel. You will burn their fortified cities, kill their young men, dash their children to the ground, and rip open their pregnant women!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 13, 'Then Hazael replied, "How could a nobody like me ever accomplish such a great feat?" But Elisha answered, "The LORD has shown me that you are going to be the king of Aram."', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 14, 'When Hazael went back, the king asked him, "What did Elisha tell you?" And Hazael replied, "He told me that you will surely recover."', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 15, 'But the next day Hazael took a blanket, soaked it in water, and held it over the king''s face until he died. Then Hazael became the next king of Aram.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 16, 'Jehoram son of King Jehoshaphat of Judah began to rule over Judah in the fifth year of King Joram''s reign in Israel. Joram was the son of Ahab.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 17, 'Jehoram was thirty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem eight years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 18, 'But Jehoram followed the example of the kings of Israel and was as wicked as King Ahab, for he had married one of Ahab''s daughters. So Jehoram did what was evil in the LORD''s sight.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 19, 'But the LORD was not willing to destroy Judah, for he had made a covenant with David and promised that his descendants would continue to rule forever.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 20, 'During Jehoram''s reign, the Edomites revolted against Judah and crowned their own king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 21, 'So Jehoram went with all his chariots to attack the town of Zair. The Edomites surrounded him and his charioteers, but he escaped at night under cover of darkness. Jehoram''s army, however, deserted him and fled.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 22, 'Edom has been independent from Judah to this day. The town of Libnah revolted about that same time.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 23, 'The rest of the events in Jehoram''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 24, 'When Jehoram died, he was buried with his ancestors in the City of David. Then his son Ahaziah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 25, 'Ahaziah son of Jehoram began to rule over Judah in the twelfth year of King Joram''s reign in Israel. King Joram was the son of Ahab.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 26, 'Ahaziah was twenty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem one year. His mother was Athaliah, a granddaughter of King Omri of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 27, 'Ahaziah followed the evil example of King Ahab''s family, doing what was evil in the LORD''s sight, because he was related by marriage to the family of Ahab.', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 28, 'Ahaziah joined King Joram of Israel in his war against King Hazael of Aram at Ramoth-gilead. When King Joram was wounded in the battle,', 'NLT'),
(16, 8, 29, 'he returned to Jezreel to recover from his wounds. While Joram was there, King Ahaziah of Judah went to visit him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 1, 'Meanwhile, Elisha the prophet had summoned a member of the group of prophets. "Get ready to go to Ramoth-gilead," he told him. "Take this vial of olive oil with you,', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 2, 'and find Jehu son of Jehoshaphat and grandson of Nimshi. Call him into a back room away from his friends,', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 3, 'and pour the oil over his head. Say to him, `This is what the LORD says: I anoint you to be the king over Israel.'' Then open the door and run for your life!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 4, 'So the young prophet did as he was told and went to Ramoth-gilead.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 5, 'When he arrived there, he found Jehu sitting in a meeting with the other army officers. "I have a message for you, Commander," he said. "For which one of us?" Jehu asked. "For you, Commander," he replied.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 6, 'So Jehu left the others and went into the house. Then the young prophet poured the oil over Jehu''s head and said, "This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: I anoint you king over the LORD''s people, Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 7, 'You are to destroy the family of Ahab, your master. In this way, I will avenge the murder of my prophets and all the LORD''s servants who were killed by Jezebel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 8, 'The entire family of Ahab must be wiped out--every male, slave and free alike, in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 9, 'I will destroy the family of Ahab as I destroyed the families of Jeroboam son of Nebat and of Baasha son of Ahijah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 10, 'Dogs will eat Ahab''s wife, Jezebel, at the plot of land in Jezreel, and no one will bury her." Then the young prophet opened the door and ran.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 11, 'Jehu went back to his fellow officers, and one of them asked him, "What did that crazy fellow want? Is everything all right?You know the way such a man babbles on," Jehu replied.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 12, '"You''re lying," they said. "Tell us." So Jehu told them what the man had said and that at the LORD''s command he had been anointed king over Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 13, 'They quickly spread out their cloaks on the bare steps and blew a trumpet, shouting, "Jehu is king!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 14, 'So Jehu son of Jehoshaphat and grandson of Nimshi formed a conspiracy against King Joram. (Now Joram had been with the army at Ramoth-gilead, defending Israel against the forces of King Hazael of Aram.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 15, 'But Joram had been wounded in the fighting and had returned to Jezreel to recover from his wounds.) So Jehu told the men with him, "Since you want me to be king, don''t let anyone escape to Jezreel to report what we have done."', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 16, 'Then Jehu got into a chariot and rode to Jezreel to find King Joram, who was lying there wounded. King Ahaziah of Judah was there, too, for he had gone to visit him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 17, 'The watchman on the tower of Jezreel saw Jehu and his company approaching, so he shouted to Joram, "I see a company of troops coming!Send out a rider to find out if they are coming in peace," King Joram shouted back.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 18, 'So a rider went out to meet Jehu and said, "The king wants to know whether you are coming in peace." Jehu replied, "What do you know about peace? Get behind me!" The watchman called out to the king, "The rider has met them, but he is not returning."', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 19, 'So the king sent out a second rider. He rode up to them and demanded, "The king wants to know whether you come in peace." Again Jehu answered, "What do you know about peace? Get behind me!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 20, 'The watchman exclaimed, "The rider has met them, but he isn''t returning either! It must be Jehu son of Nimshi, for he is driving so recklessly."', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 21, '"Quick! Get my chariot ready!" King Joram commanded. Then King Joram of Israel and King Ahaziah of Judah rode out in their chariots to meet Jehu. They met him at the field that had belonged to Naboth of Jezreel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 22, 'King Joram demanded, "Do you come in peace, Jehu?" Jehu replied, "How can there be peace as long as the idolatry and witchcraft of your mother, Jezebel, are all around us?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 23, 'Then King Joram reined the chariot horses around and fled, shouting to King Ahaziah, "Treason, Ahaziah!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 24, 'Then Jehu drew his bow and shot Joram between the shoulders. The arrow pierced his heart, and he sank down dead in his chariot.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 25, 'Jehu said to Bidkar, his officer, "Throw him into the field of Naboth of Jezreel. Do you remember when you and I were riding along behind his father, Ahab? The LORD pronounced this message against him:', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 26, '`I solemnly swear that I will repay him here on Naboth''s property, says the LORD, for the murder of Naboth and his sons that I saw yesterday.'' So throw him out on Naboth''s field, just as the LORD said."', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 27, 'When King Ahaziah of Judah saw what was happening, he fled along the road to Beth-haggan. Jehu rode after him, shouting, "Shoot him, too!" So they shot Ahaziah in his chariot at the Ascent of Gur, near Ibleam. He was able to go on as far as Megiddo, but he died there.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 28, 'His officials took him by chariot to Jerusalem, where they buried him with his ancestors in the City of David.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 29, 'Ahaziah''s reign over Judah had begun in the eleventh year of King Joram''s reign in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 30, 'When Jezebel, the queen mother, heard that Jehu had come to Jezreel, she painted her eyelids and fixed her hair and sat at a window.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 31, 'When Jehu entered the gate of the palace, she shouted at him, "Have you come in peace, you murderer? You are just like Zimri, who murdered his master!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 32, 'Jehu looked up and saw her at the window and shouted, "Who is on my side?" And two or three eunuchs looked out at him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 33, '"Throw her down!" Jehu yelled. So they threw her out the window, and some of her blood spattered against the wall and on the horses. And Jehu trampled her body under his horses'' hooves.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 34, 'Then Jehu went into the palace and ate and drank. Afterward he said, "Someone go and bury this cursed woman, for she is the daughter of a king."', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 35, 'But when they went out to bury her, they found only her skull, her feet, and her hands.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 36, 'When they returned and told Jehu, he stated, "This fulfills the message from the LORD, which he spoke through his servant Elijah from Tishbe: `At the plot of land in Jezreel, dogs will eat Jezebel''s flesh.', 'NLT'),
(16, 9, 37, 'Her body will be scattered like dung on the field of Jezreel, so that no one will be able to recognize her.''"', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 1, 'Now Ahab had seventy sons living in the city of Samaria. So Jehu wrote a letter and sent copies to Samaria, to the officials of the city, to the leaders of the people, and to the guardians of King Ahab''s sons. The letter said,', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 2, '"The king''s sons are with you, and you have at your disposal chariots, horses, a fortified city, and weapons. As soon as you receive this letter,', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 3, 'select the best qualified of King Ahab''s sons to be your king, and prepare to fight for Ahab''s dynasty."', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 4, 'But they were paralyzed with fear and said, "Two kings couldn''t stand against this man! What can we do?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 5, 'So the palace and city administrators, together with the other leaders and the guardians of the king''s sons, sent this message to Jehu: "We are your servants and will do anything you tell us. We will not make anyone king; do whatever you think is best."', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 6, 'Jehu responded with a second letter: "If you are on my side and are going to obey me, bring the heads of the king''s sons to me at Jezreel at about this time tomorrow." Now the seventy sons of the king were being cared for by the leaders of Samaria, where they had been raised since childhood.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 7, 'When the letter arrived, the leaders killed all seventy of the king''s sons. They placed their heads in baskets and presented them to Jehu at Jezreel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 8, 'A messenger went to Jehu and said, "They have brought the heads of the king''s sons." So Jehu ordered, "Pile them in two heaps at the entrance of the city gate, and leave them there until morning."', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 9, 'In the morning he went out and spoke to the crowd that had gathered around them. "You aren''t to blame," he told them. "I am the one who conspired against my master and killed him. But who killed all these?', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 10, 'You can be sure that the message of the LORD that was spoken concerning Ahab''s family will not fail. The LORD declared through his servant Elijah that this would happen."', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 11, 'Then Jehu killed all of Ahab''s relatives living in Jezreel and all his important officials, personal friends, and priests. So Ahab was left without a single survivor.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 12, 'Then Jehu set out for Samaria. Along the way, while he was at Beth-eked of the Shepherds,', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 13, 'he met some relatives of King Ahaziah of Judah. "Who are you?" he asked them. And they replied, "We are relatives of King Ahaziah. We are going to visit the sons of King Ahab and the queen mother."', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 14, '"Take them alive!" Jehu shouted to his men. And they captured all forty-two of them and killed them at the well of Beth-eked. None of them escaped.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 15, 'When Jehu left there, he met Jehonadab son of Recab, who was coming to meet him. After they had greeted each other, Jehu said to him, "Are you as loyal to me as I am to you?Yes, I am," Jehonadab replied. "If you are," Jehu said, "then give me your hand." So Jehonadab put out his hand, and Jehu helped him into the chariot.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 16, 'Then Jehu said, "Now come with me, and see how devoted I am to the LORD." So Jehonadab rode along with him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 17, 'When Jehu arrived in Samaria, he killed everyone who was left there from Ahab''s family, just as the LORD had promised through Elijah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 18, 'Then Jehu called a meeting of all the people of the city and said to them, "Ahab hardly worshiped Baal at all compared to the way I will worship him!', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 19, 'Summon all the prophets and worshipers of Baal, and call together all his priests. See to it that every one of them comes, for I am going to offer a great sacrifice to Baal. Any of Baal''s worshipers who fail to come will be put to death." But Jehu''s plan was to destroy all the worshipers of Baal.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 20, 'Then Jehu ordered, "Prepare a solemn assembly to worship Baal!" So they did.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 21, 'He sent messengers throughout all Israel summoning those who worshiped Baal. They all came and filled the temple of Baal from one end to the other.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 22, 'And Jehu instructed the keeper of the wardrobe, "Be sure that every worshiper of Baal wears one of these robes." So robes were given to them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 23, 'Then Jehu went into the temple of Baal with Jehonadab son of Recab. Jehu said to the worshipers of Baal, "Make sure that only those who worship Baal are here. Don''t let anyone in who worships the LORD!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 24, 'So they were all inside the temple to offer sacrifices and burnt offerings. Now Jehu had surrounded the building with eighty of his men and had warned them, "If you let anyone escape, you will pay for it with your own life."', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 25, 'As soon as Jehu had finished sacrificing the burnt offering, he commanded his guards and officers, "Go in and kill all of them. Don''t let a single one escape!" So they killed them all with their swords, and the guards and officers dragged their bodies outside. Then Jehu''s men went into the fortress of the temple of Baal.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 26, 'They dragged out the sacred pillar used in the worship of Baal and destroyed it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 27, 'They broke down the sacred pillar of Baal and wrecked the temple of Baal, converting it into a public toilet. That is what it is used for to this day.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 28, 'Thus, Jehu destroyed every trace of Baal worship from Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 29, 'He did not, however, destroy the gold calves at Bethel and Dan, the great sin that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 30, 'Nonetheless the LORD said to Jehu, "You have done well in following my instructions to destroy the family of Ahab. Because of this I will cause your descendants to be the kings of Israel down to the fourth generation."', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 31, 'But Jehu did not obey the law of the LORD, the God of Israel, with all his heart. He refused to turn from the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 32, 'At about that time the LORD began to reduce the size of Israel''s territory. King Hazael conquered several sections of the country', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 33, 'east of the Jordan River, including all of Gilead, Gad, Reuben, and Manasseh. He conquered the area from the town of Aroer by the Arnon Gorge to as far north as Gilead and Bashan.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 34, 'The rest of the events in Jehu''s reign and all his deeds and achievements are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 35, 'When Jehu died, he was buried with his ancestors in Samaria. Then his son Jehoahaz became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 10, 36, 'In all, Jehu reigned over Israel from Samaria for twenty-eight years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 1, 'When Athaliah, the mother of King Ahaziah of Judah, learned that her son was dead, she set out to destroy the rest of the royal family.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 2, 'But Ahaziah''s sister Jehosheba, the daughter of King Jehoram, took Ahaziah''s infant son, Joash, and stole him away from among the rest of the king''s children, who were about to be killed. Jehosheba put Joash and his nurse in a bedroom to hide him from Athaliah, so the child was not murdered.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 3, 'Joash and his nurse remained hidden in the Temple of the LORD for six years while Athaliah ruled over the land.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 4, 'In the seventh year of Athaliah''s reign, Jehoiada the priest summoned the commanders, the Carite mercenaries, and the guards to come to the Temple of the LORD. He made a pact with them and made them swear an oath of loyalty there in the LORD''s Temple; then he showed them the king''s son.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 5, 'Jehoiada told them, "This is what you must do. A third of you who are on duty on the Sabbath are to guard the royal palace itself.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 6, 'Another third of you are to stand guard at the Sur Gate. And the final third must stand guard behind the palace guard. These three groups will all guard the palace.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 7, 'The other two units who are off duty on the Sabbath must stand guard for the king at the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 8, 'Form a bodyguard for the king and keep your weapons in hand. Any unauthorized person who approaches you must be killed. Stay right beside the king at all times."', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 9, 'So the commanders did everything just as Jehoiada the priest ordered. The commanders took charge of the men reporting for duty that Sabbath, as well as those who were going off duty. They brought them all to Jehoiada the priest,', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 10, 'and he supplied them with the spears and shields that had once belonged to King David and were stored in the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 11, 'The guards stationed themselves around the king, with their weapons ready. They formed a line from the south side of the Temple around to the north side and all around the altar.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 12, 'Then Jehoiada brought out Joash, the king''s son, and placed the crown on his head. He presented Joash with a copy of God''s covenant and proclaimed him king. They anointed him, and all the people clapped their hands and shouted, "Long live the king!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 13, 'When Athaliah heard all the noise made by the guards and the people, she hurried to the LORD''s Temple to see what was happening.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 14, 'And she saw the newly crowned king standing in his place of authority by the pillar, as was the custom at times of coronation. The officers and trumpeters were surrounding him, and people from all over the land were rejoicing and blowing trumpets. When Athaliah saw all this, she tore her clothes in despair and shouted, "Treason! Treason!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 15, 'Then Jehoiada the priest ordered the commanders who were in charge of the troops, "Take her out of the Temple, and kill anyone who tries to rescue her. Do not kill her here in the Temple of the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 16, 'So they seized her and led her out to the gate where horses enter the palace grounds, and she was killed there.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 17, 'Then Jehoiada made a covenant between the LORD and the king and the people that they would be the LORD''s people. He also made a covenant between the king and the people.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 18, 'And all the people of the land went over to the temple of Baal and tore it down. They demolished the altars and smashed the idols to pieces, and they killed Mattan the priest of Baal in front of the altars. Jehoiada the priest stationed guards at the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 19, 'Then the commanders, the Carite mercenaries, the guards, and all the people of the land escorted the king from the Temple of the LORD. They went through the gate of the guards and into the palace, and the king took his seat on the royal throne.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 20, 'So all the people of the land rejoiced, and the city was peaceful because Athaliah had been killed at the king''s palace.', 'NLT'),
(16, 11, 21, 'Joash was seven years old when he became king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 1, 'Joash began to rule over Judah in the seventh year of King Jehu''s reign in Israel. He reigned in Jerusalem forty years. His mother was Zibiah, from Beersheba.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 2, 'All his life Joash did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight because Jehoiada the priest instructed him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 3, 'Yet even so, he did not destroy the pagan shrines, and the people still offered sacrifices and burned incense there.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 4, 'One day King Joash said to the priests, "Collect all the money brought as a sacred offering to the LORD''s Temple, whether it is a regular assessment, a payment of vows, or a voluntary gift.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 5, 'Let the priests take some of that money to pay for whatever repairs are needed at the Temple."', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 6, 'But by the twenty-third year of Joash''s reign, the priests still had not repaired the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 7, 'So King Joash called for Jehoiada and the other priests and asked them, "Why haven''t you repaired the Temple? Don''t use any more gifts for your own needs. From now on, it must all be spent on getting the Temple into good condition."', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 8, 'So the priests agreed not to collect any more money from the people, and they also agreed not to undertake the repairs of the Temple themselves.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 9, 'Then Jehoiada the priest bored a hole in the lid of a large chest and set it on the right-hand side of the altar at the entrance of the Temple of the LORD. The priests guarding the entrance put all of the people''s contributions into the chest.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 10, 'Whenever the chest became full, the court secretary and the high priest counted the money that had been brought to the LORD''s Temple and put it into bags.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 11, 'Then they gave the money to the construction supervisors, who used it to pay the people working on the LORD''s Temple--the carpenters, the builders,', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 12, 'the masons, and the stonecutters. They also used the money to buy timber and cut stone for repairing the LORD''s Temple, and they paid any other expenses related to the Temple''s restoration.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 13, 'The money brought to the Temple was not used for making silver cups, lamp snuffers, basins, trumpets, or other articles of gold or silver for the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 14, 'It was paid out to the workmen, who used it for the Temple repairs.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 15, 'No accounting was required from the construction supervisors, because they were honest and faithful workers.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 16, 'However, the money that was contributed for guilt offerings and sin offerings was not brought into the LORD''s Temple. It was given to the priests for their own use.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 17, 'About this time King Hazael of Aram went to war against Gath and captured it. Then he turned to attack Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 18, 'King Joash collected all the sacred objects that Jehoshaphat, Jehoram, and Ahaziah, the previous kings of Judah, had dedicated, along with what he himself had dedicated. He sent them all to Hazael, along with all the gold in the treasuries of the LORD''s Temple and the royal palace. So Hazael called off his attack on Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 19, 'The rest of the events in Joash''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 20, 'But his officers plotted against him and assassinated him at Beth-millo on the road to Silla.', 'NLT'),
(16, 12, 21, 'The assassins were Jozabad son of Shimeath and Jehozabad son of Shomer--both trusted advisers. Joash was buried with his ancestors in the City of David. Then his son Amaziah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 1, 'Jehoahaz son of Jehu began to rule over Israel in the twenty-third year of King Joash''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria seventeen years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 2, 'But he did what was evil in the LORD''s sight. He followed the example of Jeroboam son of Nebat, continuing the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 3, 'So the LORD was very angry with Israel, and he allowed King Hazael of Aram and his son Ben-hadad to defeat them time after time.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 4, 'Then Jehoahaz prayed for the LORD''s help, and the LORD heard his prayer. The LORD could see how terribly the king of Aram was oppressing Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 5, 'So the LORD raised up a deliverer to rescue the Israelites from the tyranny of the Arameans. Then Israel lived in safety again as they had in former days.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 6, 'But they continued to sin, following the evil example of Jeroboam. They even set up an Asherah pole in Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 7, 'Finally, Jehoahaz''s army was reduced to fifty mounted troops, ten chariots, and ten thousand foot soldiers. The king of Aram had killed the others like they were dust under his feet.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 8, 'The rest of the events in Jehoahaz''s reign and all his deeds, including the extent of his power, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 9, 'When Jehoahaz died, he was buried in Samaria with his ancestors. Then his son Jehoash became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 10, 'Jehoash son of Jehoahaz began to rule over Israel in the thirty-seventh year of King Joash''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria sixteen years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 11, 'But he did what was evil in the LORD''s sight. He refused to turn from the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 12, 'The rest of the events in Jehoash''s reign and all his deeds, including the extent of his power and his war with King Amaziah of Judah, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 13, 'When Jehoash died, he was buried with his ancestors in Samaria. Then his son Jeroboam II became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 14, 'When Elisha was in his last illness, King Jehoash of Israel visited him and wept over him. "My father! My father! The chariots and charioteers of Israel!" he cried.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 15, 'Elisha told him, "Get a bow and some arrows." And the king did as he was told.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 16, 'Then Elisha told the king of Israel to put his hand on the bow, and Elisha laid his own hands on the king''s hands.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 17, 'Then he commanded, "Open that eastern window," and he opened it. Then he said, "Shoot!" So he did. Then Elisha proclaimed, "This is the LORD''s arrow, full of victory over Aram, for you will completely conquer the Arameans at Aphek.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 18, 'Now pick up the other arrows and strike them against the ground." So the king picked them up and struck the ground three times.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 19, 'But the man of God was angry with him. "You should have struck the ground five or six times!" he exclaimed. "Then you would have beaten Aram until they were entirely destroyed. Now you will be victorious only three times."', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 20, 'Then Elisha died and was buried. Groups of Moabite raiders used to invade the land each spring.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 21, 'Once when some Israelites were burying a man, they spied a band of these raiders. So they hastily threw the body they were burying into the tomb of Elisha. But as soon as the body touched Elisha''s bones, the dead man revived and jumped to his feet!', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 22, 'King Hazael of Aram had oppressed Israel during the entire reign of King Jehoahaz.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 23, 'But the LORD was gracious to the people of Israel, and they were not totally destroyed. He pitied them because of his covenant with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. And to this day he still has not completely destroyed them or banished them from his presence.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 24, 'King Hazael of Aram died, and his son Ben-hadad became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 13, 25, 'Then Jehoash son of Jehoahaz recaptured from Ben-hadad son of Hazael the towns that Hazael had taken from Jehoash''s father, Jehoahaz. Jehoash defeated Ben-hadad on three occasions, and so recovered the Israelite towns.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 1, 'Amaziah son of Joash began to rule over Judah in the second year of the reign of King Jehoash of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 2, 'Amaziah was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem twenty-nine years. His mother was Jehoaddin, from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 3, 'Amaziah did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight, but not like his ancestor David. Instead, he followed the example of his father, Joash.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 4, 'Amaziah did not destroy the pagan shrines, where the people offered sacrifices and burned incense.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 5, 'When Amaziah was well established as king, he executed the men who had assassinated his father.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 6, 'However, he did not kill the children of the assassins, for he obeyed the command of the LORD written in the Book of the Law of Moses: "Parents must not be put to death for the sins of their children, nor the children for the sins of their parents. Those worthy of death must be executed for their own crimes."', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 7, 'It was Amaziah who killed ten thousand Edomites in the Valley of Salt. He also conquered Sela and changed its name to Joktheel, as it is called to this day.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 8, 'One day Amaziah sent this challenge to Israel''s king Jehoash, the son of Jehoahaz and grandson of Jehu: "Come and meet me in battle!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 9, 'But King Jehoash of Israel replied to King Amaziah of Judah with this story: "Out in the Lebanon mountains a thistle sent a message to a mighty cedar tree: `Give your daughter in marriage to my son.'' But just then a wild animal came by and stepped on the thistle, crushing it!', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 10, 'You have indeed destroyed Edom and are very proud about it. Be content with your victory and stay at home! Why stir up trouble that will bring disaster on you and the people of Judah?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 11, 'But Amaziah refused to listen, so King Jehoash of Israel mobilized his army against King Amaziah of Judah. The two armies drew up their battle lines at Beth-shemesh in Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 12, 'Judah was routed by the army of Israel, and its army scattered and fled for home.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 13, 'King Jehoash of Israel captured King Amaziah of Judah at Beth-shemesh and marched on to Jerusalem. Then Jehoash ordered his army to demolish six hundred feet of Jerusalem''s wall, from the Ephraim Gate to the Corner Gate.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 14, 'He carried off all the gold and silver and all the utensils from the Temple of the LORD, as well as from the palace treasury. He also took hostages and returned to Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 15, 'The rest of the events in Jehoash''s reign, including the extent of his power and his war with King Amaziah of Judah, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 16, 'When Jehoash died, he was buried with his ancestors in Samaria. Then his son Jeroboam II became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 17, 'King Amaziah of Judah lived on for fifteen years after the death of King Jehoash of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 18, 'The rest of the events in Amaziah''s reign are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 19, 'There was a conspiracy against Amaziah''s life in Jerusalem, and he fled to Lachish. But his enemies sent assassins after him, and they killed him there.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 20, 'They brought him back to Jerusalem on a horse, and he was buried with his ancestors in the City of David.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 21, 'The people of Judah then crowned Amaziah''s sixteen-year-old son, Uzziah, as their next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 22, 'After his father''s death, Uzziah rebuilt the town of Elath and restored it to Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 23, 'Jeroboam II, the son of Jehoash, began to rule over Israel in the fifteenth year of King Amaziah''s reign in Judah. Jeroboam reigned in Samaria forty-one years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 24, 'He did what was evil in the LORD''s sight. He refused to turn from the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 25, 'Jeroboam II recovered the territories of Israel between Lebo-hamath and the Dead Sea, just as the LORD, the God of Israel, had promised through Jonah son of Amittai, the prophet from Gath-hepher.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 26, 'For the LORD saw the bitter suffering of everyone in Israel, and how they had absolutely no one to help them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 27, 'And because the LORD had not said he would blot out the name of Israel completely, he used Jeroboam II, the son of Jehoash, to save them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 28, 'The rest of the events in the reign of Jeroboam II and all his deeds, including the extent of his power, his wars, and how he recovered for Israel both Damascus and Hamath, which had belonged to Judah, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 14, 29, 'When Jeroboam II died, he was buried with his ancestors, the kings of Israel. Then his son Zechariah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 1, 'Uzziah son of Amaziah began to rule over Judah in the twenty-seventh year of the reign of King Jeroboam II of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 2, 'He was sixteen years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem fifty-two years. His mother was Jecoliah, from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 3, 'He did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight, just as his father, Amaziah, had done.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 4, 'But he did not destroy the pagan shrines, where the people offered sacrifices and burned incense.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 5, 'The LORD struck the king with leprosy, which lasted until the day of his death; he lived in a house by himself. The king''s son Jotham was put in charge of the royal palace, and he governed the people of the land.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 6, 'The rest of the events in Uzziah''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 7, 'When Uzziah died, he was buried near his ancestors in the City of David. Then his son Jotham became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 8, 'Zechariah son of Jeroboam II began to rule over Israel in the thirty-eighth year of King Uzziah''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria six months.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 9, 'Zechariah did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, as his ancestors had done. He refused to turn from the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 10, 'Then Shallum son of Jabesh conspired against Zechariah, assassinated him in public, and became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 11, 'The rest of the events in Zechariah''s reign are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 12, 'So the LORD''s message to Jehu came true: "Your descendants will be kings of Israel down to the fourth generation."', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 13, 'Shallum son of Jabesh began to rule over Israel in the thirty-ninth year of King Uzziah''s reign in Judah. Shallum reigned in Samaria only one month.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 14, 'Then Menahem son of Gadi went to Samaria from Tirzah and assassinated him, and he became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 15, 'The rest of the events in Shallum''s reign, including his conspiracy, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel. Menahem Rules in Israel', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 16, 'At that time Menahem destroyed the town of Tappuah and all the surrounding countryside as far as Tirzah, because its citizens refused to surrender the town. He killed the entire population and ripped open the pregnant women.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 17, 'Menahem son of Gadi began to rule over Israel in the thirty-ninth year of King Uzziah''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria ten years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 18, 'But Menahem did what was evil in the LORD''s sight. During his entire reign, he refused to turn from the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 19, 'Then King Tiglath-pileser of Assyria invaded the land. But Menahem paid him thirty-seven tons of silver to gain his support in tightening his grip on royal power.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 20, 'Menahem extorted the money from the rich of Israel, demanding that each of them pay twenty ounces of silver in the form of a special tax. So the king of Assyria turned from attacking Israel and did not stay in the land.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 21, 'The rest of the events in Menahem''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 22, 'When Menahem died, his son Pekahiah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 23, 'Pekahiah son of Menahem began to rule over Israel in the fiftieth year of King Uzziah''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria two years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 24, 'But Pekahiah did what was evil in the LORD''s sight. He refused to turn from the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 25, 'Then Pekah son of Remaliah, the commander of Pekahiah''s army, conspired against him. With fifty men from Gilead, Pekah assassinated the king, along with Argob and Arieh, in the citadel of the palace at Samaria. Pekah then became the next king of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 26, 'The rest of the events in Pekahiah''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel. Pekah Rules in Israel', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 27, 'Pekah son of Remaliah began to rule over Israel in the fifty-second year of King Uzziah''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria twenty years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 28, 'But Pekah did what was evil in the LORD''s sight. He refused to turn from the sins of idolatry that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led Israel to commit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 29, 'During his reign, King Tiglath-pileser of Assyria attacked Israel again, and he captured the towns of Ijon, Abel-beth-maacah, Janoah, Kedesh, and Hazor. He also conquered the regions of Gilead, Galilee, and Naphtali, and he took the people to Assyria as captives.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 30, 'Then Hoshea son of Elah conspired against Pekah and assassinated him. He began to rule over Israel in the twentieth year of Jotham son of Uzziah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 31, 'The rest of the events in Pekah''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel. Jotham Rules in Judah', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 32, 'Jotham son of Uzziah began to rule over Judah in the second year of King Pekah''s reign in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 33, 'He was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem sixteen years. His mother was Jerusha, the daughter of Zadok.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 34, 'Jotham did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight, just as his father Uzziah had done.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 35, 'But he did not destroy the pagan shrines, where the people offered sacrifices and burned incense. He was the one who rebuilt the upper gate of the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 36, 'The rest of the events in Jotham''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 37, 'In those days the LORD began to send King Rezin of Aram and King Pekah of Israel to attack Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 15, 38, 'When Jotham died, he was buried with his ancestors in the City of David. Then his son Ahaz became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 1, 'Ahaz son of Jotham began to rule over Judah in the seventeenth year of King Pekah''s reign in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 2, 'Ahaz was twenty years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem sixteen years. He did not do what was pleasing in the sight of the LORD his God, as his ancestor David had done.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 3, 'Instead, he followed the example of the kings of Israel, even sacrificing his own son in the fire. He imitated the detestable practices of the pagan nations the LORD had driven from the land ahead of the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 4, 'He offered sacrifices and burned incense at the pagan shrines and on the hills and under every green tree.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 5, 'Then King Rezin of Aram and King Pekah of Israel declared war on Ahaz. They besieged Jerusalem but did not conquer it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 6, 'At that time the king of Edom recovered the town of Elath for Edom. He drove out the people of Judah and sent Edomites to live there, as they do to this day.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 7, 'King Ahaz sent messengers to King Tiglath-pileser of Assyria with this message: "I am your servant and your vassal. Come up and rescue me from the attacking armies of Aram and Israel."', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 8, 'Then Ahaz took the silver and gold from the Temple of the LORD and the palace treasury and sent it as a gift to the Assyrian king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 9, 'So the Assyrians attacked the Aramean capital of Damascus and led its population away as captives, resettling them in Kir. They also killed King Rezin.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 10, 'King Ahaz then went to Damascus to meet with King Tiglath-pileser of Assyria. While he was there, he noticed an unusual altar. So he sent a model of the altar to Uriah the priest, along with its design in full detail.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 11, 'Uriah built an altar just like it by following the king''s instructions, and it was ready for the king when he returned from Damascus.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 12, 'When the king returned, he inspected the altar and made offerings on it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 13, 'The king presented a burnt offering and a grain offering, poured a drink offering over it, and sprinkled the blood of peace offerings on it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 14, 'Then King Ahaz removed the old bronze altar from the front of the LORD''s Temple, which had stood between the entrance and the new altar, and placed it on the north side of the new altar.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 15, 'He said to Uriah the priest, "Use the new altar for the morning sacrifices of burnt offering, the evening grain offering, the king''s burnt offering and grain offering, and the offerings of the people, including their drink offerings. The blood from the burnt offerings and sacrifices should be sprinkled over the new altar. The old bronze altar will be only for my personal use."', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 16, 'Uriah the priest did just as King Ahaz instructed him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 17, 'Then the king removed the side panels and basins from the portable water carts. He also removed the Sea from the backs of the bronze oxen and placed it on the stone pavement.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 18, 'In deference to the king of Assyria, he also removed the canopy that had been constructed inside the palace for use on the Sabbath day, as well as the king''s outer entrance to the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 19, 'The rest of the events in Ahaz''s reign and his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 16, 20, 'When Ahaz died, he was buried with his ancestors in the City of David. Then his son Hezekiah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 1, 'Hoshea son of Elah began to rule over Israel in the twelfth year of King Ahaz''s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria nine years.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 2, 'He did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, but not as much as the kings of Israel who ruled before him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 3, 'King Shalmaneser of Assyria attacked and defeated King Hoshea, so Israel was forced to pay heavy annual tribute to Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 4, 'Then Hoshea conspired against the king of Assyria by asking King So of Egypt to help him shake free of Assyria''s power and by refusing to pay the annual tribute to Assyria. When the king of Assyria discovered this treachery, he arrested him and put him in prison for his rebellion.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 5, 'Then the king of Assyria invaded the entire land, and for three years he besieged Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 6, 'Finally, in the ninth year of King Hoshea''s reign, Samaria fell, and the people of Israel were exiled to Assyria. They were settled in colonies in Halah, along the banks of the Habor River in Gozan, and among the cities of the Medes.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 7, 'This disaster came upon the nation of Israel because the people worshiped other gods, sinning against the LORD their God, who had brought them safely out of their slavery in Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 8, 'They had imitated the practices of the pagan nations the LORD had driven from the land before them, as well as the practices the kings of Israel had introduced.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 9, 'The people of Israel had also secretly done many things that were not pleasing to the LORD their God. They built pagan shrines for themselves in all their towns, from the smallest outpost to the largest walled city.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 10, 'They set up sacred pillars and Asherah poles at the top of every hill and under every green tree.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 11, 'They burned incense at the shrines, just like the nations the LORD had driven from the land ahead of them. So the people of Israel had done many evil things, arousing the LORD''s anger.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 12, 'Yes, they worshiped idols, despite the LORD''s specific and repeated warnings.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 13, 'Again and again the LORD had sent his prophets and seers to warn both Israel and Judah: "Turn from all your evil ways. Obey my commands and laws, which are contained in the whole law that I commanded your ancestors and which I gave you through my servants the prophets."', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 14, 'But the Israelites would not listen. They were as stubborn as their ancestors and refused to believe in the LORD their God.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 15, 'They rejected his laws and the covenant he had made with their ancestors, and they despised all his warnings. They worshiped worthless idols and became worthless themselves. They followed the example of the nations around them, disobeying the LORD''s command not to imitate them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 16, 'They defied all the commands of the LORD their God and made two calves from metal. They set up an Asherah pole and worshiped Baal and all the forces of heaven.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 17, 'They even sacrificed their own sons and daughters in the fire. They consulted fortune-tellers and used sorcery and sold themselves to evil, arousing the LORD''s anger.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 18, 'And because the LORD was angry, he swept them from his presence. Only the tribe of Judah remained in the land.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 19, 'But even the people of Judah refused to obey the commands of the LORD their God. They walked down the same evil paths that Israel had established.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 20, 'So the LORD rejected all the descendants of Israel. He punished them by handing them over to their attackers until they were destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 21, 'For when the LORD tore Israel away from the kingdom of David, they chose Jeroboam son of Nebat as their king. Then Jeroboam drew Israel away from following the LORD and made them commit a great sin.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 22, 'And the people of Israel persisted in all the evil ways of Jeroboam. They did not turn from these sins of idolatry', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 23, 'until the LORD finally swept them away, just as all his prophets had warned would happen. So Israel was carried off to the land of Assyria, where they remain to this day.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 24, 'And the king of Assyria transported groups of people from Babylon, Cuthah, Avva, Hamath, and Sepharvaim and resettled them in the towns of Samaria, replacing the people of Israel. So the Assyrians took over Samaria and the other towns of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 25, 'But since these foreign settlers did not worship the LORD when they first arrived, the LORD sent lions among them to kill some of them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 26, 'So a message was sent to the king of Assyria: "The people whom you have resettled in the towns of Israel do not know how to worship the God of the land. He has sent lions among them to destroy them because they have not worshiped him correctly."', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 27, 'The king of Assyria then commanded, "Send one of the exiled priests from Samaria back to Israel. Let him teach the new residents the religious customs of the God of the land."', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 28, 'So one of the priests who had been exiled from Samaria returned to Bethel and taught the new residents how to worship the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 29, 'But these various groups of foreigners also continued to worship their own gods. In town after town where they lived, they placed their idols at the pagan shrines that the people of Israel had built.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 30, 'Those from Babylon worshiped idols of their god Succoth-benoth. Those from Cuthah worshiped their god Nergal. And those from Hamath worshiped Ashima.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 31, 'The Avvites worshiped their gods Nibhaz and Tartak. And the people from Sepharvaim even burned their own children as sacrifices to Adrammelech and Anammelech.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 32, 'These new residents worshiped the LORD, but they appointed from among themselves priests to offer sacrifices at the pagan shrines.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 33, 'And though they worshiped the LORD, they continued to follow the religious customs of the nations from which they came.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 34, 'And this is still going on among them today. They follow their former practices instead of truly worshiping the LORD and obeying the laws, regulations, instructions, and commands he gave the descendants of Jacob, whose name he changed to Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 35, 'For the LORD had made a covenant with the descendants of Jacob and commanded them: "Do not worship any other gods or bow before them or serve them or offer sacrifices to them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 36, 'Worship only the LORD, who brought you out of Egypt with such mighty miracles and power. You must worship him and bow before him; offer sacrifices to him alone.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 37, 'Be careful to obey all the laws, regulations, instructions, and commands that he wrote for you. You must not worship any other gods.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 38, 'Do not forget the covenant I made with you, and do not worship other gods.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 39, 'You must worship only the LORD your God. He is the one who will rescue you from all your enemies."', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 40, 'But the people would not listen and continued to follow their old ways.', 'NLT'),
(16, 17, 41, 'So while these new residents worshiped the LORD, they also worshiped their idols. And to this day their descendants do the same.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 1, 'Hezekiah son of Ahaz began to rule over Judah in the third year of King Hoshea''s reign in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 2, 'He was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem twenty-nine years. His mother was Abijah, the daughter of Zechariah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 3, 'He did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight, just as his ancestor David had done.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 4, 'He removed the pagan shrines, smashed the sacred pillars, and knocked down the Asherah poles. He broke up the bronze serpent that Moses had made, because the people of Israel had begun to worship it by burning incense to it. The bronze serpent was called Nehushtan.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 5, 'Hezekiah trusted in the LORD, the God of Israel. There was never another king like him in the land of Judah, either before or after his time.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 6, 'He remained faithful to the LORD in everything, and he carefully obeyed all the commands the LORD had given Moses.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 7, 'So the LORD was with him, and Hezekiah was successful in everything he did. He revolted against the king of Assyria and refused to pay him tribute.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 8, 'He also conquered the Philistines as far distant as Gaza and its territory, from their smallest outpost to their largest walled city.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 9, 'During the fourth year of Hezekiah''s reign, which was the seventh year of King Hoshea''s reign in Israel, King Shalmaneser of Assyria attacked Israel and began a siege on the city of Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 10, 'Three years later, during the sixth year of King Hezekiah''s reign and the ninth year of King Hoshea''s reign in Israel, Samaria fell.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 11, 'At that time the king of Assyria deported the Israelites to Assyria and put them in colonies in Halah, along the banks of the Habor River in Gozan, and among the cities of the Medes.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 12, 'For they had refused to listen to the LORD their God. Instead, they had violated his covenant--all the laws the LORD had given through his servant Moses.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 13, 'In the fourteenth year of King Hezekiah''s reign, King Sennacherib of Assyria came to attack the fortified cities of Judah and conquered them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 14, 'King Hezekiah sent this message to the king of Assyria at Lachish: "I have done wrong. I will pay whatever tribute money you demand if you will only go away." The king of Assyria then demanded a settlement of more than eleven tons of silver and about one ton of gold.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 15, 'To gather this amount, King Hezekiah used all the silver stored in the Temple of the LORD and in the palace treasury.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 16, 'Hezekiah even stripped the gold from the doors of the LORD''s Temple and from the doorposts he had overlaid with gold, and he gave it all to the Assyrian king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 17, 'Nevertheless the king of Assyria sent his commander in chief, his field commander, and his personal representative from Lachish with a huge army to confront King Hezekiah in Jerusalem. The Assyrians stopped beside the aqueduct that feeds water into the upper pool, near the road leading to the field where cloth is bleached.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 18, 'They summoned King Hezekiah, but the king sent these officials to meet with them: Eliakim son of Hilkiah, the palace administrator, Shebna the court secretary, and Joah son of Asaph, the royal historian.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 19, 'Then the Assyrian king''s personal representative sent this message to King Hezekiah: "This is what the great king of Assyria says: What are you trusting in that makes you so confident?', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 20, 'Do you think that mere words can substitute for military skill and strength? Which of your allies will give you any military backing against Assyria?', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 21, 'Will Egypt? If you lean on Egypt, you will find it to be a stick that breaks beneath your weight and pierces your hand. The pharaoh of Egypt is completely unreliable!', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 22, '"But perhaps you will say, `We are trusting in the LORD our God!'' But isn''t he the one who was insulted by King Hezekiah? Didn''t Hezekiah tear down his shrines and altars and make everyone in Judah worship only at the altar here in Jerusalem?', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 23, '"I''ll tell you what! My master, the king of Assyria, will strike a bargain with you. If you can find two thousand horsemen in your entire army, he will give you two thousand horses for them to ride on!', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 24, 'With your tiny army, how can you think of challenging even the weakest contingent of my master''s troops, even with the help of Egypt''s chariots and horsemen?', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 25, 'What''s more, do you think we have invaded your land without the LORD''s direction? The LORD himself told us, `Go and destroy it!''"', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 26, 'Then Eliakim son of Hilkiah, Shebna, and Joah said to the king''s representative, "Please speak to us in Aramaic, for we understand it well. Don''t speak in Hebrew, for the people on the wall will hear."', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 27, 'But Sennacherib''s representative replied, "My master wants everyone in Jerusalem to hear this, not just you. He wants them to know that if you do not surrender, this city will be put under siege. The people will become so hungry and thirsty that they will eat their own dung and drink their own urine."', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 28, 'Then he stood and shouted in Hebrew to the people on the wall, "Listen to this message from the great king of Assyria!', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 29, 'This is what the king says: Don''t let King Hezekiah deceive you. He will never be able to rescue you from my power.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 30, 'Don''t let him fool you into trusting in the LORD by saying, `The LORD will rescue us! This city will never be handed over to the Assyrian king.''', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 31, '"Don''t listen to Hezekiah! These are the terms the king of Assyria is offering: Make peace with me--open the gates and come out. Then I will allow each of you to continue eating from your own garden and drinking from your own well.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 32, 'Then I will arrange to take you to another land like this one--a country with bountiful harvests of grain and wine, bread and vineyards, olive trees and honey--a land of plenty. Choose life instead of death! "Don''t listen to Hezekiah when he tries to mislead you by saying, `The LORD will rescue us!''', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 33, 'Have the gods of any other nations ever saved their people from the king of Assyria?', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 34, 'What happened to the gods of Hamath and Arpad? And what about the gods of Sepharvaim, Hena, and Ivvah? Did they rescue Samaria from my power?', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 35, 'What god of any nation has ever been able to save its people from my power? Name just one! So what makes you think that the LORD can rescue Jerusalem?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 36, 'But the people were silent and did not answer because Hezekiah had told them not to speak.', 'NLT'),
(16, 18, 37, 'Then Eliakim son of Hilkiah, the palace administrator, Shebna the court secretary, and Joah son of Asaph, the royal historian, went back to Hezekiah. They tore their clothes in despair, and they went in to see the king and told him what the Assyrian representative had said.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 1, 'When King Hezekiah heard their report, he tore his clothes and put on sackcloth and went into the Temple of the LORD to pray.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 2, 'And he sent Eliakim the palace administrator, Shebna the court secretary, and the leading priests, all dressed in sackcloth, to the prophet Isaiah son of Amoz.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 3, 'They told him, "This is what King Hezekiah says: This is a day of trouble, insult, and disgrace. It is like when a child is ready to be born, but the mother has no strength to deliver it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 4, 'But perhaps the LORD your God has heard the Assyrian representative defying the living God and will punish him for his words. Oh, pray for those of us who are left!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 5, 'After King Hezekiah''s officials delivered the king''s message to Isaiah,', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 6, 'the prophet replied, "Say to your master, `This is what the LORD says: Do not be disturbed by this blasphemous speech against me from the Assyrian king''s messengers.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 7, 'Listen! I myself will move against him, and the king will receive a report from Assyria telling him that he is needed at home. Then I will make him want to return to his land, where I will have him killed with a sword.''"', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 8, 'Meanwhile, the Assyrian representative left Jerusalem and went to consult his king, who had left Lachish and was attacking Libnah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 9, 'Soon afterward King Sennacherib received word that King Tirhakah of Ethiopia was leading an army to fight against him. Before leaving to meet the attack, he sent this message back to Hezekiah in Jerusalem:', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 10, '"This message is for King Hezekiah of Judah. Don''t let this God you trust deceive you with promises that Jerusalem will not be captured by the king of Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 11, 'You know perfectly well what the kings of Assyria have done wherever they have gone. They have crushed everyone who stood in their way! Why should you be any different?', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 12, 'Have the gods of other nations rescued them--such nations as Gozan, Haran, Rezeph, and the people of Eden who were in Tel-assar? The former kings of Assyria destroyed them all!', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 13, 'What happened to the king of Hamath and the king of Arpad? What happened to the kings of Sepharvaim, Hena, and Ivvah?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 14, 'After Hezekiah received the letter and read it, he went up to the LORD''s Temple and spread it out before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 15, 'And Hezekiah prayed this prayer before the LORD: "O LORD, God of Israel, you are enthroned between the mighty cherubim! You alone are God of all the kingdoms of the earth. You alone created the heavens and the earth.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 16, 'Listen to me, O LORD, and hear! Open your eyes, O LORD, and see! Listen to Sennacherib''s words of defiance against the living God.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 17, '"It is true, LORD, that the kings of Assyria have destroyed all these nations, just as the message says.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 18, 'And they have thrown the gods of these nations into the fire and burned them. But of course the Assyrians could destroy them! They were not gods at all--only idols of wood and stone shaped by human hands.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 19, 'Now, O LORD our God, rescue us from his power; then all the kingdoms of the earth will know that you alone, O LORD, are God."', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 20, 'Then Isaiah son of Amoz sent this message to Hezekiah: "This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: I have heard your prayer about King Sennacherib of Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 21, 'This is the message that the LORD has spoken against him: `The virgin daughter of Zion despises you and laughs at you. The daughter of Jerusalem scoffs and shakes her head as you flee.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 22, '`Whom do you think you have been insulting and ridiculing? Against whom did you raise your voice? At whom did you look in such proud condescension? It was the Holy One of Israel!', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 23, 'By your messengers you have mocked the Lord. You have said, "With my many chariots I have conquered the highest mountains--yes, the remotest peaks of Lebanon. I have cut down its tallest cedars and its choicest cypress trees. I have reached its farthest corners and explored its deepest forests.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 24, 'I have dug wells in many a foreign land and refreshed myself with their water. I even stopped up the rivers of Egypt so that my armies could go across!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 25, '`But have you not heard? It was I, the LORD, who decided this long ago. Long ago I planned what I am now causing to happen, that you should crush fortified cities into heaps of rubble.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 26, 'That is why their people have so little power and are such easy prey for you. They are as helpless as the grass, as easily trampled as tender green shoots. They are like grass sprouting on a housetop, easily scorched by the sun.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 27, '`But I know you well--your comings and goings and all you do. I know the way you have raged against me.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 28, 'And because of your arrogance against me, which I have heard for myself, I will put my hook in your nose and my bridle in your mouth. I will make you return by the road on which you came.''"', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 29, 'Then Isaiah said to Hezekiah, "Here is the proof that the LORD will protect this city from Assyria''s king. This year you will eat only what grows up by itself, and next year you will eat what springs up from that. But in the third year you will plant crops and harvest them; you will tend vineyards and eat their fruit.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 30, 'And you who are left in Judah, who have escaped the ravages of the siege, will take root again in your own soil, and you will flourish and multiply.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 31, 'For a remnant of my people will spread out from Jerusalem, a group of survivors from Mount Zion. The passion of the LORD Almighty will make this happen!', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 32, '"And this is what the LORD says about the king of Assyria: His armies will not enter Jerusalem to shoot their arrows. They will not march outside its gates with their shields and build banks of earth against its walls.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 33, 'The king will return to his own country by the road on which he came. He will not enter this city, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 34, 'For my own honor and for the sake of my servant David, I will defend it."', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 35, 'That night the angel of the LORD went out to the Assyrian camp and killed 185,000 Assyrian troops. When the surviving Assyrians woke up the next morning, they found corpses everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 36, 'Then King Sennacherib of Assyria broke camp and returned to his own land. He went home to his capital of Nineveh and stayed there.', 'NLT'),
(16, 19, 37, 'One day while he was worshiping in the temple of his god Nisroch, his sons Adrammelech and Sharezer killed him with their swords. They then escaped to the land of Ararat, and another son, Esarhaddon, became the next king of Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 1, 'About that time Hezekiah became deathly ill, and the prophet Isaiah son of Amoz went to visit him. He gave the king this message: "This is what the LORD says: Set your affairs in order, for you are going to die. You will not recover from this illness."', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 2, 'When Hezekiah heard this, he turned his face to the wall and prayed to the LORD,', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 3, '"Remember, O LORD, how I have always tried to be faithful to you and do what is pleasing in your sight." Then he broke down and wept bitterly.', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 4, 'But before Isaiah had left the middle courtyard, this message came to him from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 5, '"Go back to Hezekiah, the leader of my people. Tell him, `This is what the LORD, the God of your ancestor David, says: I have heard your prayer and seen your tears. I will heal you, and three days from now you will get out of bed and go to the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 6, 'I will add fifteen years to your life, and I will rescue you and this city from the king of Assyria. I will do this to defend my honor and for the sake of my servant David.''"', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 7, 'Then Isaiah said to Hezekiah''s servants, "Make an ointment from figs and spread it over the boil." They did this, and Hezekiah recovered!', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 8, 'Meanwhile, Hezekiah had said to Isaiah, "What sign will the LORD give to prove that he will heal me and that I will go to the Temple of the LORD three days from now?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 9, 'Isaiah replied, "This is the sign that the LORD will give you to prove he will do as he promised. Would you like the shadow on the sundial to go forward ten steps or backward ten steps?"', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 10, '"The shadow always moves forward," Hezekiah replied. "Make it go backward instead."', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 11, 'So Isaiah asked the LORD to do this, and he caused the shadow to move ten steps backward on the sundial of Ahaz!', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 12, 'Soon after this, Merodach-baladan son of Baladan, king of Babylon, sent Hezekiah his best wishes and a gift, for he had heard that Hezekiah had been very sick.', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 13, 'Hezekiah welcomed the Babylonian envoys and showed them everything in his treasure-houses--the silver, the gold, the spices, and the aromatic oils. He also took them to see his armory and showed them all his other treasures--everything! There was nothing in his palace or kingdom that Hezekiah did not show them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 14, 'Then Isaiah the prophet went to King Hezekiah and asked him, "What did those men want? Where were they from?" Hezekiah replied, "They came from the distant land of Babylon."', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 15, '"What did they see in your palace?" Isaiah asked. "They saw everything," Hezekiah replied. "I showed them everything I own--all my treasures."', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 16, 'Then Isaiah said to Hezekiah, "Listen to this message from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 17, 'The time is coming when everything you have--all the treasures stored up by your ancestors--will be carried off to Babylon. Nothing will be left, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 18, 'Some of your own descendants will be taken away into exile. They will become eunuchs who will serve in the palace of Babylon''s king."', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 19, 'Then Hezekiah said to Isaiah, "This message you have given me from the LORD is good." But the king was thinking, "At least there will be peace and security during my lifetime."', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 20, 'The rest of the events in Hezekiah''s reign, including the extent of his power and how he built a pool and dug a tunnel to bring water into the city, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 20, 21, 'When Hezekiah died, his son Manasseh became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 1, 'Manasseh was twelve years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem fifty-five years. His mother was Hephzibah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 2, 'He did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, imitating the detestable practices of the pagan nations whom the LORD had driven from the land ahead of the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 3, 'He rebuilt the pagan shrines his father, Hezekiah, had destroyed. He constructed altars for Baal and set up an Asherah pole, just as King Ahab of Israel had done. He also bowed before all the forces of heaven and worshiped them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 4, 'He even built pagan altars in the Temple of the LORD, the place where the LORD had said his name should be honored.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 5, 'He built these altars for all the forces of heaven in both courtyards of the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 6, 'Manasseh even sacrificed his own son in the fire. He practiced sorcery and divination, and he consulted with mediums and psychics. He did much that was evil in the LORD''s sight, arousing his anger.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 7, 'Manasseh even took an Asherah pole he had made and set it up in the Temple, the very place where the LORD had told David and his son Solomon: "My name will be honored here forever in this Temple and in Jerusalem--the city I have chosen from among all the other tribes of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 8, 'If the Israelites will obey my commands--the whole law that was given through my servant Moses--I will not send them into exile from this land that I gave their ancestors."', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 9, 'But the people refused to listen, and Manasseh led them to do even more evil than the pagan nations whom the LORD had destroyed when the Israelites entered the land.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 10, 'Then the LORD said through his servants the prophets:', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 11, '"King Manasseh of Judah has done many detestable things. He is even more wicked than the Amorites, who lived in this land before Israel. He has led the people of Judah into idolatry.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 12, 'So this is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: I will bring such disaster on Jerusalem and Judah that the ears of those who hear about it will tingle with horror.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 13, 'I will judge Jerusalem by the same standard I used for Samaria and by the same measure I used for the family of Ahab. I will wipe away the people of Jerusalem as one wipes a dish and turns it upside down.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 14, 'Then I will reject even those few of my people who are left, and I will hand them over as plunder for their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 15, 'For they have done great evil in my sight and have angered me ever since their ancestors came out of Egypt."', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 16, 'Manasseh also murdered many innocent people until Jerusalem was filled from one end to the other with innocent blood. This was in addition to the sin that he caused the people of Judah to commit, leading them to do evil in the LORD''s sight.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 17, 'The rest of the events in Manasseh''s reign and all his deeds, including the sins he committed, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 18, 'When Manasseh died, he was buried in the palace garden, the garden of Uzza. Then his son Amon became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 19, 'Amon was twenty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem two years. His mother was Meshullemeth, the daughter of Haruz from Jotbah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 20, 'He did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, just as his father, Manasseh, had done.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 21, 'He followed the example of his father, worshiping the same idols that his father had worshiped.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 22, 'He abandoned the LORD, the God of his ancestors, and he refused to follow the LORD''s ways.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 23, 'Then Amon''s own servants plotted against him and assassinated him in his palace.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 24, 'But the people of the land killed all those who had conspired against King Amon, and they made his son Josiah the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 25, 'The rest of the events in Amon''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 21, 26, 'He was buried in his tomb in the garden of Uzza. Then his son Josiah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 1, 'Josiah was eight years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem thirty-one years. His mother was Jedidah, the daughter of Adaiah from Bozkath.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 2, 'He did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight and followed the example of his ancestor David. He did not turn aside from doing what was right.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 3, 'In the eighteenth year of his reign, King Josiah sent Shaphan son of Azaliah and grandson of Meshullam, the court secretary, to the Temple of the LORD. He told him,', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 4, '"Go up to Hilkiah the high priest and have him count the money the gatekeepers have collected from the people at the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 5, 'Entrust this money to the men assigned to supervise the Temple''s restoration. Then they can use it to pay workers to repair the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 6, 'They will need to hire carpenters, builders, and masons. Also have them buy the timber and the cut stone needed to repair the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 7, 'But there will be no need for the construction supervisors to keep account of the money they receive, for they are honest people."', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 8, 'Hilkiah the high priest said to Shaphan the court secretary, "I have found the Book of the Law in the LORD''s Temple!" Then Hilkiah gave the scroll to Shaphan, and he read it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 9, 'Shaphan returned to the king and reported, "Your officials have given the money collected at the Temple of the LORD to the workers and supervisors at the Temple."', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 10, 'Shaphan also said to the king, "Hilkiah the priest has given me a scroll." So Shaphan read it to the king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 11, 'When the king heard what was written in the Book of the Law, he tore his clothes in despair.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 12, 'Then he gave these orders to Hilkiah the priest, Ahikam son of Shaphan, Acbor son of Micaiah, Shaphan the court secretary, and Asaiah the king''s personal adviser:', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 13, '"Go to the Temple and speak to the LORD for me and for the people and for all Judah. Ask him about the words written in this scroll that has been found. The LORD''s anger is burning against us because our ancestors have not obeyed the words in this scroll. We have not been doing what this scroll says we must do."', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 14, 'So Hilkiah the priest, Ahikam, Acbor, Shaphan, and Asaiah went to the newer Mishneh section of Jerusalem to consult with the prophet Huldah. She was the wife of Shallum son of Tikvah and grandson of Harhas, the keeper of the Temple wardrobe.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 15, 'She said to them, "The LORD, the God of Israel, has spoken! Go and tell the man who sent you,', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 16, '`This is what the LORD says: I will destroy this city and its people, just as I stated in the scroll you read.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 17, 'For my people have abandoned me and worshiped pagan gods, and I am very angry with them for everything they have done. My anger is burning against this place, and it will not be quenched.''', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 18, '"But go to the king of Judah who sent you to seek the LORD and tell him: `This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says concerning the message you have just heard:', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 19, 'You were sorry and humbled yourself before the LORD when you heard what I said against this city and its people, that this land would be cursed and become desolate. You tore your clothing in despair and wept before me in repentance. So I have indeed heard you, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(16, 22, 20, 'I will not send the promised disaster against this city until after you have died and been buried in peace. You will not see the disaster I am going to bring on this place.''" So they took her message back to the king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 1, 'Then the king summoned all the leaders of Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 2, 'And the king went up to the Temple of the LORD with all the people of Judah and Jerusalem, and the priests, and the prophets--all the people from the least to the greatest. There the king read to them the entire Book of the Covenant that had been found in the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 3, 'The king took his place of authority beside the pillar and renewed the covenant in the LORD''s presence. He pledged to obey the LORD by keeping all his commands, regulations, and laws with all his heart and soul. In this way, he confirmed all the terms of the covenant that were written in the scroll, and all the people pledged themselves to the covenant.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 4, 'Then the king instructed Hilkiah the high priest and the leading priests and the Temple gatekeepers to remove from the LORD''s Temple all the utensils that were used to worship Baal, Asherah, and all the forces of heaven. The king had all these things burned outside Jerusalem on the terraces of the Kidron Valley, and he carried the ashes away to Bethel.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 5, 'He did away with the pagan priests, who had been appointed by the previous kings of Judah, for they had burned incense at the pagan shrines throughout Judah and even in the vicinity of Jerusalem. They had also offered incense to Baal, and to the sun, the moon, the constellations, and to all the forces of heaven.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 6, 'The king removed the Asherah pole from the LORD''s Temple and took it outside Jerusalem to the Kidron Valley, where he burned it. Then he ground the pole to dust and threw the dust in the public cemetery.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 7, 'He also tore down the houses of the shrine prostitutes that were inside the Temple of the LORD, where the women wove coverings for the Asherah pole.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 8, 'Josiah brought back to Jerusalem all the priests of the LORD, who were living in other towns of Judah. He also defiled all the pagan shrines, where they had burned incense, from Geba to Beersheba. He destroyed the shrines at the entrance to the gate of Joshua, the governor of Jerusalem. This gate was located to the left of the city gate as one enters the city.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 9, 'The priests who had served at the pagan shrines were not allowed to serve at the LORD''s altar in Jerusalem, but they were allowed to eat unleavened bread with the other priests.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 10, 'Then the king defiled the altar of Topheth in the valley of Ben-hinnom, so no one could ever again use it to sacrifice a son or daughter in the fire as an offering to Molech.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 11, 'He removed from the entrance of the LORD''s Temple the horse statues that the former kings of Judah had dedicated to the sun. They were near the quarters of Nathan-melech the eunuch, an officer of the court. The king also burned the chariots dedicated to the sun.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 12, 'Josiah tore down the altars that the kings of Judah had built on the palace roof above the upper room of Ahaz. The king destroyed the altars that Manasseh had built in the two courtyards of the LORD''s Temple. He smashed them to bits and scattered the pieces in the Kidron Valley.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 13, 'The king also desecrated the pagan shrines east of Jerusalem and south of the Mount of Corruption, where King Solomon of Israel had built shrines for Ashtoreth, the detestable goddess of the Sidonians; and for Chemosh, the detestable god of the Moabites; and for Molech, the detestable god of the Ammonites.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 14, 'He smashed the sacred pillars and cut down the Asherah poles. Then he desecrated these places by scattering human bones over them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 15, 'The king also tore down the altar at Bethel, the pagan shrine that Jeroboam son of Nebat had made when he led Israel into sin. Josiah crushed the stones to dust and burned the Asherah pole.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 16, 'Then as Josiah was looking around, he noticed several tombs in the side of the hill. He ordered that the bones be brought out, and he burned them on the altar at Bethel to desecrate it. This happened just as the LORD had promised through the man of God as Jeroboam stood beside the altar at the festival. Then Josiah turned and looked up at the tomb of the man of God who had predicted these things.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 17, '"What is that monument over there?" Josiah asked. And the people of the town told him, "It is the tomb of the man of God who came from Judah and predicted the very things that you have just done to the altar at Bethel!"', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 18, 'Josiah replied, "Leave it alone. Don''t disturb his bones." So they did not burn his bones or those of the old prophet from Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 19, 'Then Josiah demolished all the buildings at the pagan shrines in the towns of Samaria, just as he had done at Bethel. They had been built by the various kings of Israel and had made the LORD very angry.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 20, 'He executed the priests of the pagan shrines on their own altars, and he burned human bones on the altars to desecrate them. Finally, he returned to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 21, 'King Josiah then issued this order to all the people: "You must celebrate the Passover to the LORD your God, as it is written in the Book of the Covenant."', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 22, 'There had not been a Passover celebration like that since the time when the judges ruled in Israel, throughout all the years of the kings of Israel and Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 23, 'This Passover was celebrated to the LORD in Jerusalem during the eighteenth year of King Josiah''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 24, 'Josiah also exterminated the mediums and psychics, the household gods, and every other kind of idol worship, both in Jerusalem and throughout the land of Judah. He did this in obedience to all the laws written in the scroll that Hilkiah the priest had found in the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 25, 'Never before had there been a king like Josiah, who turned to the LORD with all his heart and soul and strength, obeying all the laws of Moses. And there has never been a king like him since.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 26, 'Even so, the LORD''s anger burned against Judah because of all the great evils of King Manasseh, and he did not hold back his fierce anger from them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 27, 'For the LORD had said, "I will destroy Judah just as I have destroyed Israel. I will banish the people from my presence and reject my chosen city of Jerusalem and the Temple where my name was to be honored."', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 28, 'The rest of the events in Josiah''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 29, 'While Josiah was king, Pharaoh Neco, king of Egypt, went to the Euphrates River to help the king of Assyria. King Josiah marched out with his army to fight him, but King Neco killed him when they met at Megiddo.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 30, 'Josiah''s officers took his body back in a chariot from Megiddo to Jerusalem and buried him in his own tomb. Then the people anointed his son Jehoahaz and made him the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 31, 'Jehoahaz was twenty-three years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem three months. His mother was Hamutal, the daughter of Jeremiah from Libnah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 32, 'He did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, just as his ancestors had done.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 33, 'Pharaoh Neco put Jehoahaz in prison at Riblah in the land of Hamath to prevent him from ruling from Jerusalem. He also demanded that Judah pay 7,500 pounds of silver and 75 pounds of gold as tribute.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 34, 'Pharaoh Neco then installed Eliakim, another of Josiah''s sons, to reign in place of his father, and he changed Eliakim''s name to Jehoiakim. Jehoahaz was taken to Egypt as a prisoner, where he died.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 35, 'In order to get the silver and gold demanded as tribute by Pharaoh Neco, Jehoiakim collected a tax from the people of Judah, requiring them to pay in proportion to their wealth.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 36, 'Jehoiakim was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem eleven years. His mother was Zebidah, the daughter of Pedaiah from Rumah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 23, 37, 'He did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, just as his ancestors had done.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 1, 'During Jehoiakim''s reign, King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon invaded the land of Judah. Jehoiakim surrendered and paid him tribute for three years but then rebelled.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 2, 'Then the LORD sent bands of Babylonian, Aramean, Moabite, and Ammonite raiders against Judah to destroy it, just as the LORD had promised through his prophets.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 3, 'These disasters happened to Judah according to the LORD''s command. He had decided to remove Judah from his presence because of the many sins of Manasseh.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 4, 'He had filled Jerusalem with innocent blood, and the LORD would not forgive this.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 5, 'The rest of the events in Jehoiakim''s reign and all his deeds are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 6, 'When Jehoiakim died, his son Jehoiachin became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 7, 'The king of Egypt never returned after that, for the king of Babylon occupied the entire area formerly claimed by Egypt--from the brook of Egypt to the Euphrates River.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 8, 'Jehoiachin was eighteen years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem three months. His mother was Nehushta, the daughter of Elnathan from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 9, 'Jehoiachin did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, just as his father had done.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 10, 'During Jehoiachin''s reign, the officers of King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon came up against Jerusalem and besieged it.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 11, 'Nebuchadnezzar himself arrived at the city during the siege.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 12, 'Then King Jehoiachin, along with his advisers, nobles, and officials, and the queen mother, surrendered to the Babylonians. In the eighth year of Nebuchadnezzar''s reign, he took Jehoiachin prisoner.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 13, 'As the LORD had said beforehand, Nebuchadnezzar carried away all the treasures from the LORD''s Temple and the royal palace. They cut apart all the gold vessels that King Solomon of Israel had placed in the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 14, 'King Nebuchadnezzar took ten thousand captives from Jerusalem, including all the princes and the best of the soldiers, craftsmen, and smiths. So only the poorest people were left in the land.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 15, 'Nebuchadnezzar led King Jehoiachin away as a captive to Babylon, along with his wives and officials, the queen mother, and all Jerusalem''s elite.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 16, 'He also took seven thousand of the best troops and one thousand craftsmen and smiths, all of whom were strong and fit for war.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 17, 'Then the king of Babylon installed Mattaniah, Jehoiachin''s uncle, as the next king, and he changed Mattaniah''s name to Zedekiah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 18, 'Zedekiah was twenty-one years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem eleven years. His mother was Hamutal, the daughter of Jeremiah from Libnah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 19, 'But Zedekiah did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, just as Jehoiakim had done.', 'NLT'),
(16, 24, 20, 'So the LORD, in his anger, finally banished the people of Jerusalem and Judah from his presence and sent them into exile. Then Zedekiah rebelled against the king of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 1, 'So on January 15, during the ninth year of Zedekiah''s reign, King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon led his entire army against Jerusalem. They surrounded the city and built siege ramps against its walls.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 2, 'Jerusalem was kept under siege until the eleventh year of King Zedekiah''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 3, 'By July 18 of Zedekiah''s eleventh year, the famine in the city had become very severe, with the last of the food entirely gone.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 4, 'Then a section of the city wall was broken down, and all the soldiers made plans to escape from the city. But since the city was surrounded by the Babylonians, they waited for nightfall and fled through the gate between the two walls behind the king''s gardens. They made a dash across the fields, in the direction of the Jordan Valley.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 5, 'But the Babylonians chased after them and caught the king on the plains of Jericho, for by then his men had all abandoned him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 6, 'They brought him to the king of Babylon at Riblah, where sentence was passed against him.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 7, 'The king of Babylon made Zedekiah watch as all his sons were killed. Then they gouged out Zedekiah''s eyes, bound him in bronze chains, and led him away to Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 8, 'On August 14 of that year, which was the nineteenth year of Nebuchadnezzar''s reign, Nebuzaradan, captain of the guard, an official of the Babylonian king, arrived in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 9, 'He burned down the Temple of the LORD, the royal palace, and all the houses of Jerusalem. He destroyed all the important buildings in the city.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 10, 'Then the captain of the guard supervised the entire Babylonian army as they tore down the walls of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 11, 'Nebuzaradan, captain of the guard, then took as exiles those who remained in the city, along with the rest of the people and the troops who had declared their allegiance to the king of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 12, 'But the captain of the guard allowed some of the poorest people to stay behind in Judah to care for the vineyards and fields.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 13, 'The Babylonians broke up the bronze pillars, the bronze water carts, and the bronze Sea that were at the LORD''s Temple, and they carried all the bronze away to Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 14, 'They also took all the pots, shovels, lamp snuffers, dishes, and all the other bronze utensils used for making sacrifices at the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 15, 'Nebuzaradan, captain of the guard, also took the firepans and basins, and all the other utensils made of pure gold or silver.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 16, 'The bronze from the two pillars, the water carts, and the Sea was too great to be weighed. These things had been made for the LORD''s Temple in the days of King Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 17, 'Each of the pillars was 27 feet tall. The bronze capital on top of each pillar was 7 1/2 feet high and was decorated with a network of bronze pomegranates all the way around.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 18, 'The captain of the guard took with him as prisoners Seraiah the chief priest, his assistant Zephaniah, and the three chief gatekeepers.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 19, 'And of the people still hiding in the city, he took an officer of the Judean army, five of the king''s personal advisers, the army commander''s chief secretary, who was in charge of recruitment, and sixty other citizens.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 20, 'Nebuzaradan the commander took them all to the king of Babylon at Riblah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 21, 'And there at Riblah, in the land of Hamath, the king of Babylon had them all put to death. So the people of Judah were sent into exile from their land.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 22, 'Then King Nebuchadnezzar appointed Gedaliah son of Ahikam and grandson of Shaphan as governor over the people left in Judah.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 23, 'When all the army commanders and their men learned that the king of Babylon had appointed Gedaliah as governor, they joined him at Mizpah. These included Ishmael son of Nethaniah, Johanan son of Kareah, Seraiah son of Tanhumeth the Netophathite, and Jaazaniah son of the Maacathite, and all their men.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 24, 'Gedaliah vowed to them that the Babylonian officials meant them no harm. "Live in the land and serve the king of Babylon, and all will go well for you," he promised.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 25, 'But in midautumn of that year, Ishmael son of Nethaniah and grandson of Elishama, who was of the royal family, went to Mizpah with ten men and assassinated Gedaliah and everyone with him, both Judeans and Babylonians.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 26, 'Then all the people of Judah, from the least to the greatest, as well as the army commanders, fled in panic to Egypt, for they were afraid of what the Babylonians would do to them.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 27, 'In the thirty-seventh year of King Jehoiachin''s exile in Babylon, Evil-merodach ascended to the Babylonian throne. He was kind to Jehoiachin and released him from prison on April 2 of that year.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 28, 'He spoke pleasantly to Jehoiachin and gave him preferential treatment over all the other exiled kings in Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 29, 'He supplied Jehoiachin with new clothes to replace his prison garb and allowed him to dine at the king''s table for the rest of his life.', 'NLT'),
(16, 25, 30, 'The Babylonian king also gave him a regular allowance to cover his living expenses until the day of his death.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 1, 'The descendants of Adam were Seth, Enosh,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 2, 'Kenan, Mahalalel, Jared,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 3, 'Enoch, Methuselah, Lamech,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 4, 'and Noah. The sons of Noah were Shem, Ham, and Japheth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 5, 'The descendants of Japheth were Gomer, Magog, Madai, Javan, Tubal, Meshech, and Tiras.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 6, 'The descendants of Gomer were Ashkenaz, Riphath, and Togarmah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 7, 'The descendants of Javan were Elishah, Tarshish, Kittim, and Rodanim.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 8, 'The descendants of Ham were Cush, Mizraim, Put, and Canaan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 9, 'The descendants of Cush were Seba, Havilah, Sabtah, Raamah, and Sabteca. The descendants of Raamah were Sheba and Dedan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 10, 'Cush was also the ancestor of Nimrod, who was known across the earth as a heroic warrior.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 11, 'Mizraim was the ancestor of the Ludites, Anamites, Lehabites, Naphtuhites,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 12, 'Pathrusites, Casluhites, and the Caphtorites, from whom the Philistines came.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 13, 'Canaan''s oldest son was Sidon, the ancestor of the Sidonians. Canaan was also the ancestor of the Hittites,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 14, 'Jebusites, Amorites, Girgashites,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 15, 'Hivites, Arkites, Sinites,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 16, 'Arvadites, Zemarites, and Hamathites.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 17, 'The descendants of Shem were Elam, Asshur, Arphaxad, Lud, and Aram. The descendants of Aram were Uz, Hul, Gether, and Mash.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 18, 'Arphaxad was the father of Shelah. Shelah was the father of Eber.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 19, 'Eber had two sons. The first was named Peleg--"division"--for during his lifetime the people of the world were divided into different language groups and dispersed. His brother''s name was Joktan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 20, 'Joktan was the ancestor of Almodad, Sheleph, Hazarmaveth, Jerah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 21, 'Hadoram, Uzal, Diklah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 22, 'Obal, Abimael, Sheba,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 23, 'Ophir, Havilah, and Jobab. All these were descendants of Joktan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 24, 'So this is the family line descended from Shem: Arphaxad, Shelah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 25, 'Eber, Peleg, Reu,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 26, 'Serug, Nahor, Terah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 27, 'and Abram, later known as Abraham.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 28, 'The sons of Abraham were Isaac and Ishmael.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 29, 'The sons of Ishmael were Nebaioth (the oldest), Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 30, 'Mishma, Dumah, Massa, Hadad, Tema,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 31, 'Jetur, Naphish, and Kedemah. These were the sons of Ishmael.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 32, 'The sons of Keturah, Abraham''s concubine, were Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak, and Shuah. The sons of Jokshan were Sheba and Dedan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 33, 'The sons of Midian were Ephah, Epher, Hanoch, Abida, and Eldaah. All these were sons of Abraham by his concubine Keturah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 34, 'Abraham was the father of Isaac. The sons of Isaac were Esau and Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 35, 'The sons of Esau were Eliphaz, Reuel, Jeush, Jalam, and Korah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 36, 'The sons of Eliphaz were Teman, Omar, Zepho, Gatam, Kenaz, and Amalek, who was born to Timna.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 37, 'The sons of Reuel were Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 38, 'The sons of Seir were Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah, Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 39, 'The sons of Lotan were Hori and Heman. Lotan''s sister was named Timna.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 40, 'The sons of Shobal were Alvan, Manahath, Ebal, Shepho, and Onam. The sons of Zibeon were Aiah and Anah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 41, 'The son of Anah was Dishon. The sons of Dishon were Hemdan, Eshban, Ithran, and Keran.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 42, 'The sons of Ezer were Bilhan, Zaavan, and Akan. The sons of Dishan were Uz and Aran.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 43, 'These are the kings who ruled in Edom before there were kings in Israel: Bela son of Beor, who ruled from his city of Dinhabah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 44, 'When Bela died, Jobab son of Zerah from Bozrah became king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 45, 'When Jobab died, Husham from the land of the Temanites became king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 46, 'When Husham died, Hadad son of Bedad became king and ruled from the city of Avith. He was the one who destroyed the Midianite army in the land of Moab.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 47, 'When Hadad died, Samlah from the city of Masrekah became king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 48, 'When Samlah died, Shaul from the city of Rehoboth on the Euphrates River became king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 49, 'When Shaul died, Baal-hanan son of Acbor became king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 50, 'When Baal-hanan died, Hadad became king and ruled from the city of Pau. His wife was Mehetabel, the daughter of Matred and granddaughter of Me-zahab.', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 51, 'Then Hadad died. The clan leaders of Edom were Timna, Alvah, Jetheth,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 52, 'Oholibamah, Elah, Pinon,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 53, 'Kenaz, Teman, Mibzar,', 'NLT'),
(17, 1, 54, 'Magdiel, and Iram. These were the clan leaders of Edom.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 1, 'The sons of Israel were Reuben, Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, Zebulun,', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 2, 'Dan, Joseph, Benjamin, Naphtali, Gad, and Asher.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 3, 'Judah had three sons through Bathshua, a Canaanite woman. Their names were Er, Onan, and Shelah. But the oldest son, Er, was a wicked man, so the LORD killed him.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 4, 'Later Judah had twin sons through Tamar, his widowed daughter-in-law. Their names were Perez and Zerah. So Judah had five sons in all.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 5, 'The sons of Perez were Hezron and Hamul.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 6, 'The sons of Zerah were Zimri, Ethan, Heman, Calcol, and Darda--five in all.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 7, 'Achan son of Carmi, one of Zerah''s descendants, brought disaster on Israel by taking plunder that had been set apart for the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 8, 'The son of Ethan was Azariah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 9, 'The sons of Hezron were Jerahmeel, Ram, and Caleb.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 10, 'Ram was the father of Amminadab. Amminadab was the father of Nahshon, a leader of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 11, 'Nahshon was the father of Salmon. Salmon was the father of Boaz.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 12, 'Boaz was the father of Obed. Obed was the father of Jesse.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 13, 'Jesse''s first son was Eliab, his second was Abinadab, his third was Shimea,', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 14, 'his fourth was Nethanel, his fifth was Raddai,', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 15, 'his sixth was Ozem, and his seventh was David.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 16, 'Their sisters were named Zeruiah and Abigail. Zeruiah had three sons named Abishai, Joab, and Asahel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 17, 'Abigail married a man named Jether, an Ishmaelite, and they had a son named Amasa.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 18, 'Hezron''s son Caleb had two wives named Azubah and Jerioth. Azubah''s sons were named Jesher, Shobab, and Ardon.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 19, 'After Azubah died, Caleb married Ephrathah, and they had a son named Hur.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 20, 'Hur was the father of Uri. Uri was the father of Bezalel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 21, 'When Hezron was sixty years old, he married Gilead''s sister, the daughter of Makir. They had a son named Segub.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 22, 'Segub was the father of Jair, who ruled twenty-three towns in the land of Gilead.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 23, '(Later Geshur and Aram captured the Towns of Jair and also took Kenath and its sixty surrounding villages.) All these were descendants of Makir, the father of Gilead.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 24, 'Soon after Hezron died in the town of Caleb-ephrathah, his wife Abijah gave birth to a son named Ashhur (the father of Tekoa).', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 25, 'The sons of Jerahmeel, the oldest son of Hezron, were Ram (the oldest), Bunah, Oren, Ozem, and Ahijah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 26, 'Jerahmeel had a second wife named Atarah. She was the mother of Onam.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 27, 'The sons of Ram, the oldest son of Jerahmeel, were Maaz, Jamin, and Eker.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 28, 'The sons of Onam were Shammai and Jada. The sons of Shammai were Nadab and Abishur.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 29, 'The sons of Abishur and his wife Abihail were Ahban and Molid.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 30, 'The sons of Nadab were Seled and Appaim. Seled died without children,', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 31, 'but Appaim had a son named Ishi. The son of Ishi was Sheshan. Sheshan had a descendant named Ahlai.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 32, 'Shammai''s brother, Jada, had two sons named Jether and Jonathan. Jether died without children,', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 33, 'but Jonathan had two sons named Peleth and Zaza. These were all descendants of Jerahmeel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 34, 'Sheshan had no sons, though he did have daughters. He also had an Egyptian servant named Jarha.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 35, 'Sheshan gave one of his daughters to be the wife of Jarha, and they had a son named Attai.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 36, 'Attai was the father of Nathan. Nathan was the father of Zabad.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 37, 'Zabad was the father of Ephlal. Ephlal was the father of Obed.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 38, 'Obed was the father of Jehu. Jehu was the father of Azariah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 39, 'Azariah was the father of Helez. Helez was the father of Eleasah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 40, 'Eleasah was the father of Sismai. Sismai was the father of Shallum.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 41, 'Shallum was the father of Jekamiah. Jekamiah was the father of Elishama.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 42, 'The oldest son of Caleb, the brother of Jerahmeel, was Mesha, the father of Ziph. Caleb''s second son was Mareshah, the father of Hebron.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 43, 'The sons of Hebron were Korah, Tappuah, Rekem, and Shema.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 44, 'Shema was the father of Raham. Raham was the father of Jorkeam. Rekem was the father of Shammai.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 45, 'The son of Shammai was Maon. Maon was the father of Beth-zur.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 46, 'Caleb''s concubine Ephah gave birth to Haran, Moza, and Gazez. Haran was the father of Gazez.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 47, 'The sons of Jahdai were Regem, Jotham, Geshan, Pelet, Ephah, and Shaaph.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 48, 'Another of Caleb''s concubines, Maacah, gave birth to Sheber and Tirhanah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 49, 'She also gave birth to Shaaph (the father of Madmannah) and Sheva (the father of Macbenah and Gibea). Caleb also had a daughter named Acsah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 50, 'These were all descendants of Caleb. The sons of Hur, the oldest son of Caleb''s wife Ephrathah, were Shobal (the father of Kiriath-jearim),', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 51, 'Salma (the father of Bethlehem), and Hareph (the father of Beth-gader).', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 52, 'The descendants of Shobal (the father of Kiriath-jearim) were Haroeh, half the Manahathites,', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 53, 'and the families of Kiriath-jearim--the Ithrites, Puthites, Shumathites, and Mishraites, from whom came the people of Zorah and Eshtaol.', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 54, 'The descendants of Salma were Bethlehem, the Netophathites, Atroth-beth-joab, the other half of the Manahathites, the Zorites,', 'NLT'),
(17, 2, 55, 'and the families of scribes living at Jabez--the Tirathites, Shimeathites, and Sucathites. All these were Kenites who descended from Hammath, the father of the family of Recab.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 1, 'These were the sons who were born to David in Hebron: The oldest was Amnon, whose mother was Ahinoam of Jezreel. The second was Kileab, whose mother was Abigail from Carmel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 2, 'The third was Absalom, whose mother was Maacah, the daughter of Talmai, king of Geshur. The fourth was Adonijah, whose mother was Haggith.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 3, 'The fifth was Shephatiah, whose mother was Abital. The sixth was Ithream, whose mother was Eglah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 4, 'These six sons were born to David in Hebron, where he reigned seven and a half years. Then David moved the capital to Jerusalem, where he reigned another thirty-three years.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 5, 'The sons born to David in Jerusalem included Shimea, Shobab, Nathan, and Solomon. Bathsheba, the daughter of Ammiel, was the mother of these sons.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 6, 'David also had nine other sons: Ibhar, Elishua, Elpelet,', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 7, 'Nogah, Nepheg, Japhia,', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 8, 'Elishama, Eliada, and Eliphelet.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 9, 'These were the sons of David, not including the sons of his concubines. David also had a daughter named Tamar.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 10, 'The descendants of Solomon were Rehoboam, Abijah, Asa, Jehoshaphat,', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 11, 'Jehoram, Ahaziah, Joash,', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 12, 'Amaziah, Uzziah, Jotham,', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 13, 'Ahaz, Hezekiah, Manasseh,', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 14, 'Amon, and Josiah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 15, 'The sons of Josiah were Johanan (the oldest), Jehoiakim (the second), Zedekiah (the third), and Jehoahaz (the fourth).', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 16, 'Jehoiakim was succeeded by his son Jehoiachin; he, in turn, was succeeded by his uncle Zedekiah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 17, 'The sons of Jehoiachin, who was taken prisoner by the Babylonians, were Shealtiel,', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 18, 'Malkiram, Pedaiah, Shenazzar, Jekamiah, Hoshama, and Nedabiah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 19, 'The sons of Pedaiah were Zerubbabel and Shimei. The sons of Zerubbabel were Meshullam and Hananiah. He also had a daughter named Shelomith.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 20, 'His five other sons were Hashubah, Ohel, Berekiah, Hasadiah, and Jushab-hesed.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 21, 'The sons of Hananiah were Pelatiah and Jeshaiah. Jeshaiah''s son was Rephaiah. Rephaiah''s son was Arnan. Arnan''s son was Obadiah. Obadiah''s son was Shecaniah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 22, 'Shecaniah''s descendants were Shemaiah and his sons, Hattush, Igal, Bariah, Neariah, and Shaphat--six in all.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 23, 'The sons of Neariah were Elioenai, Hizkiah, and Azrikam--three in all.', 'NLT'),
(17, 3, 24, 'The sons of Elioenai were Hodaviah, Eliashib, Pelaiah, Akkub, Johanan, Delaiah, and Anani--seven in all.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 1, 'Some of the descendants of Judah were Perez, Hezron, Carmi, Hur, and Shobal.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 2, 'Shobal''s son Reaiah was the father of Jahath. Jahath was the father of Ahumai and Lahad. These were the families of the Zorathites.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 3, 'The descendants of Etam were Jezreel, Ishma, Idbash, Hazzelelponi (his daughter),', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 4, 'Penuel (the father of Gedor), and Ezer (the father of Hushah). These were the descendants of Hur (the firstborn of Ephrathah), the ancestor of Bethlehem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 5, 'Ashhur (the father of Tekoa) had two wives, named Helah and Naarah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 6, 'Naarah gave birth to Ahuzzam, Hepher, Temeni, and Haahashtari.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 7, 'Helah gave birth to Zereth, Izhar, Ethnan,', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 8, 'and Koz, who became the ancestor of Anub, Zobebah, and all the families of Aharhel son of Harum.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 9, 'There was a man named Jabez who was more distinguished than any of his brothers. His mother named him Jabez because his birth had been so painful.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 10, 'He was the one who prayed to the God of Israel, "Oh, that you would bless me and extend my lands! Please be with me in all that I do, and keep me from all trouble and pain!" And God granted him his request.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 11, 'Kelub (the brother of Shuhah) was the father of Mehir. Mehir was the father of Eshton.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 12, 'Eshton was the father of Beth-rapha, Paseah, and Tehinnah. Tehinnah was the father of Ir-nahash. These were the descendants of Recah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 13, 'The sons of Kenaz were Othniel and Seraiah. Othniel''s sons were Hathath and Meonothai.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 14, 'Meonothai was the father of Ophrah. Seraiah was the father of Joab, the founder of the Valley of Craftsmen, so called because many craftsmen lived there.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 15, 'The sons of Caleb son of Jephunneh were Iru, Elah, and Naam. The son of Elah was Kenaz.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 16, 'The sons of Jehallelel were Ziph, Ziphah, Tiria, and Asarel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 17, 'The sons of Ezrah were Jether, Mered, Epher, and Jalon. Mered married an Egyptian woman, who became the mother of Miriam, Shammai, and Ishbah (the father of Eshtemoa).', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 18, 'Mered also married a woman of Judah, who became the mother of Jered (the father of Gedor), Heber (the father of Soco), and Jekuthiel (the father of Zanoah). Mered''s Egyptian wife was named Bithiah, and she was an Egyptian princess.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 19, 'Hodiah''s wife was the sister of Naham. One of her sons was the father of Keilah the Garmite, and another was the father of Eshtemoa the Maacathite.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 20, 'The sons of Shimon were Amnon, Rinnah, Ben-hanan, and Tilon. The descendants of Ishi were Zoheth and Ben-zoheth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 21, 'Shelah was one of Judah''s sons. The descendants of Shelah were Er (the father of Lecah), Laadah (the father of Mareshah), the families of linen workers at Beth-ashbea,', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 22, 'Jokim, the people of Cozeba, Joash, and Saraph, who ruled over Moab and Jashubi-lehem. These names all come from ancient records.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 23, 'They were the potters who lived in Netaim and Gederah. They all worked for the king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 24, 'The sons of Simeon were Nemuel, Jamin, Jarib, Zerah, and Shaul.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 25, 'The descendants of Shaul were Shallum, Mibsam, and Mishma.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 26, 'The descendants of Mishma were Hammuel, Zaccur, and Shimei.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 27, 'Shimei had sixteen sons and six daughters, but none of his brothers had large families. So Simeon''s tribe never became as large as the tribe of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 28, 'They lived in Beersheba, Moladah, Hazar-shual,', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 29, 'Bilhah, Ezem, Tolad,', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 30, 'Bethuel, Hormah, Ziklag,', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 31, 'Beth-marcaboth, Hazar-susim, Beth-biri, and Shaaraim. These towns were under their control until the time of King David.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 32, 'Their descendants also lived in Etam, Ain, Rimmon, Token, and Ashan--five towns', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 33, 'and their surrounding villages as far away as Baalath. This was their territory, and these names are recorded in their family genealogy.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 34, 'Other descendants of Simeon included Meshobab, Jamlech, Joshah son of Amaziah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 35, 'Joel, Jehu son of Joshibiah, son of Seraiah, son of Asiel,', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 36, 'Elioenai, Jaakobah, Jeshohaiah, Asaiah, Adiel, Jesimiel, Benaiah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 37, 'and Ziza son of Shiphi, son of Allon, son of Jedaiah, son of Shimri, son of Shemaiah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 38, 'These were the names of some of the leaders of Simeon''s wealthy clans,', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 39, 'who traveled to the region of Gedor, in the east part of the valley, seeking pastureland for their flocks.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 40, 'They found lush pastures there, and the land was quiet and peaceful. Some of Ham''s descendants had been living in the region of Gedor.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 41, 'But during the reign of King Hezekiah of Judah, the leaders of Simeon invaded it and completely destroyed the homes of the descendants of Ham and of the Meunites. They killed everyone who lived there and took the land for themselves, because they wanted its good pastureland for their flocks.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 42, 'Five hundred of these invaders from the tribe of Simeon went to Mount Seir, led by Pelatiah, Neariah, Rephaiah, and Uzziel--all sons of Ishi.', 'NLT'),
(17, 4, 43, 'They destroyed the few Amalekites who had survived, and they have lived there ever since.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 1, 'The oldest son of Israel was Reuben. But since he dishonored his father by sleeping with one of his father''s concubines, his birthright was given to the sons of his brother Joseph. For this reason, Reuben is not listed in the genealogy as the firstborn son.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 2, 'It was the descendants of Judah that became the most powerful tribe and provided a ruler for the nation, but the birthright belonged to Joseph.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 3, 'The sons of Reuben, the oldest son of Israel, were Hanoch, Pallu, Hezron, and Carmi.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 4, 'The descendants of Joel were Shemaiah, Gog, Shimei,', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 5, 'Micah, Reaiah, Baal,', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 6, 'and Beerah. Beerah was the leader of the Reubenites when they were taken into captivity by King Tiglath-pileser of Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 7, 'Beerah''s relatives are listed in their genealogy by their clans: Jeiel (the leader), Zechariah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 8, 'and Bela son of Azaz, son of Shema, son of Joel. These Reubenites lived in the area that stretches from Aroer to Nebo and Baal-meon.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 9, 'And since they had so many cattle in the land of Gilead, they spread eastward toward the edge of the desert that stretches to the Euphrates River.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 10, 'During the reign of Saul, the Reubenites defeated the Hagrites in battle. Then they moved into the Hagrite settlements all along the eastern edge of Gilead.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 11, 'Across from the Reubenites in the land of Bashan lived the descendants of Gad, who were spread as far east as Salecah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 12, 'Joel was the leader in the land of Bashan, and Shapham was second-in-command, along with Janai and Shaphat.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 13, 'Their relatives, the leaders of seven other clans, were Michael, Meshullam, Sheba, Jorai, Jacan, Zia, and Eber.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 14, 'These were all descendants of Abihail son of Huri, son of Jaroah, son of Gilead, son of Michael, son of Jeshishai, son of Jahdo, son of Buz.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 15, 'Ahi son of Abdiel, son of Guni, was the leader of their clans.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 16, 'The Gadites lived in the land of Gilead, in Bashan and its villages, and throughout the Sharon Plain.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 17, 'All of these were listed in the genealogical records during the days of King Jotham of Judah and King Jeroboam of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 18, 'There were 44,760 skilled warriors in the armies of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of Manasseh. They were all skilled in combat and armed with shields, swords, and bows.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 19, 'They waged war against the Hagrites, the Jeturites, the Naphishites, and the Nodabites.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 20, 'They cried out to God during the battle, and he answered their prayer because they trusted in him. So the Hagrites and all their allies were defeated.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 21, 'The plunder taken from the Hagrites included 50,000 camels, 250,000 sheep, 2,000 donkeys, and 100,000 captives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 22, 'Many of the Hagrites were killed in the battle because God was fighting against them. So they lived in their land until they were taken away into exile.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 23, 'The half-tribe of Manasseh spread through the land from Bashan to Baal-hermon, Senir, and Mount Hermon. They were very numerous.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 24, 'These were the leaders of their clans: Epher, Ishi, Eliel, Azriel, Jeremiah, Hodaviah, and Jahdiel. Each of these men had a great reputation as a warrior and leader.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 25, 'But they were unfaithful and violated their covenant with the God of their ancestors. They worshiped the gods of the nations that God had destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(17, 5, 26, 'So the God of Israel caused King Pul of Assyria (also known as Tiglath-pileser) to invade the land and lead away the people of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of Manasseh as captives. The Assyrians exiled them to Halah, Habor, Hara, and the Gozan River, where they remain to this day.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 1, 'The sons of Levi were Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 2, 'The descendants of Kohath included Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 3, 'The children of Amram were Aaron, Moses, and Miriam. The sons of Aaron were Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 4, 'Eleazar was the father of Phinehas. Phinehas was the father of Abishua.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 5, 'Abishua was the father of Bukki. Bukki was the father of Uzzi.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 6, 'Uzzi was the father of Zerahiah. Zerahiah was the father of Meraioth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 7, 'Meraioth was the father of Amariah. Amariah was the father of Ahitub.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 8, 'Ahitub was the father of Zadok. Zadok was the father of Ahimaaz.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 9, 'Ahimaaz was the father of Azariah. Azariah was the father of Johanan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 10, 'Johanan was the father of Azariah, the high priest at the Temple built by Solomon in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 11, 'Azariah was the father of Amariah. Amariah was the father of Ahitub.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 12, 'Ahitub was the father of Zadok. Zadok was the father of Shallum.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 13, 'Shallum was the father of Hilkiah. Hilkiah was the father of Azariah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 14, 'Azariah was the father of Seraiah. Seraiah was the father of Jehozadak,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 15, 'who went into exile when the LORD sent the people of Judah and Jerusalem into captivity under Nebuchadnezzar.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 16, 'The sons of Levi were Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 17, 'The descendants of Gershon included Libni and Shimei.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 18, 'The descendants of Kohath included Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 19, 'The descendants of Merari included Mahli and Mushi. The following were the Levite clans, listed according to their ancestral descent:', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 20, 'The descendants of Gershon included Libni, Jahath, Zimmah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 21, 'Joah, Iddo, Zerah, and Jeatherai.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 22, 'The descendants of Kohath included Amminadab, Korah, Assir,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 23, 'Elkanah, Abiasaph, Assir,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 24, 'Tahath, Uriel, Uzziah, and Shaul.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 25, 'The descendants of Elkanah included Amasai, Ahimoth,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 26, 'Elkanah, Zophai, Nahath,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 27, 'Eliab, Jeroham, Elkanah, and Samuel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 28, 'The sons of Samuel were Joel (the older) and Abijah (the second).', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 29, 'The descendants of Merari included Mahli, Libni, Shimei, Uzzah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 30, 'Shimea, Haggiah, and Asaiah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 31, 'David assigned the following men to lead the music at the house of the LORD after he put the Ark there.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 32, 'They ministered with music there at the Tabernacle until Solomon built the Temple of the LORD in Jerusalem. Then they carried on their work there, following all the regulations handed down to them.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 33, 'These are the men who served, along with their sons: Heman the musician was from the clan of Kohath. His genealogy was traced back through Joel, Samuel,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 34, 'Elkanah, Jeroham, Eliel, Toah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 35, 'Zuph, Elkanah, Mahath, Amasai,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 36, 'Elkanah, Joel, Azariah, Zephaniah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 37, 'Tahath, Assir, Abiasaph, Korah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 38, 'Izhar, Kohath, Levi, and Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 39, 'Heman''s first assistant was Asaph from the clan of Gershon. Asaph''s genealogy was traced back through Berekiah, Shimea,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 40, 'Michael, Baaseiah, Malkijah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 41, 'Ethni, Zerah, Adaiah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 42, 'Ethan, Zimmah, Shimei,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 43, 'Jahath, Gershon, and Levi.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 44, 'Heman''s second assistant was Ethan from the clan of Merari. Ethan''s genealogy was traced back through Kishi, Abdi, Malluch,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 45, 'Hashabiah, Amaziah, Hilkiah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 46, 'Amzi, Bani, Shemer,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 47, 'Mahli, Mushi, Merari, and Levi.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 48, 'Their relatives, also Levites, were appointed to various other tasks in the Tabernacle, the house of God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 49, 'Only Aaron and his descendants served as priests. They presented the offerings on the altar of burnt offering and the altar of incense, and they performed all the other duties related to the Most Holy Place. They made atonement for Israel by following all the commands that Moses, the servant of God, had given them.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 50, 'The descendants of Aaron were Eleazar, Phinehas, Abishua,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 51, 'Bukki, Uzzi, Zerahiah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 52, 'Meraioth, Amariah, Ahitub,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 53, 'Zadok, and Ahimaaz.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 54, 'This is a record of the towns and territory assigned by means of sacred lots to the descendants of Aaron who were from the clan of Kohath.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 55, 'This included Hebron and its surrounding pasturelands in Judah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 56, 'but the fields and outlying areas were given to Caleb son of Jephunneh.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 57, 'So the descendants of Aaron were given the following towns, each with its surrounding pasturelands: Hebron (a city of refuge), Libnah, Jattir, Eshtemoa,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 58, 'Holon, Debir,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 59, 'Ain, Juttah, and Beth-shemesh.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 60, 'And from the territory of Benjamin they were given Gibeon, Geba, Alemeth, and Anathoth, each with its pasturelands. So a total of thirteen towns was given to the descendants of Aaron.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 61, 'The remaining descendants of Kohath received ten towns from the territory of the half-tribe of Manasseh by means of sacred lots.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 62, 'The descendants of Gershon received by sacred lots thirteen towns from the territories of Issachar, Asher, Naphtali, and from the Bashan area of Manasseh, east of the Jordan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 63, 'The descendants of Merari received by sacred lots twelve towns from the territories of Reuben, Gad, and Zebulun.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 64, 'So the people of Israel assigned all these towns and pasturelands to the Levites.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 65, 'The towns in the territories of Judah, Simeon, and Benjamin, mentioned above, were also assigned by means of sacred lots.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 66, 'The descendants of Kohath received from the territory of Ephraim these towns, each with its surrounding pasturelands:', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 67, 'Shechem (a city of refuge in the hill country of Ephraim), Gezer,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 68, 'Jokmeam, Beth-horon,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 69, 'Aijalon, and Gath-rimmon.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 70, 'The remaining descendants of Kohath were assigned these towns from the territory of the half-tribe of Manasseh: Aner and Bileam, each with its pasturelands.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 71, 'The descendants of Gershon received from the territory of the half-tribe of Manasseh the town of Golan in Bashan with its pasturelands and Ashtaroth with its pasturelands.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 72, 'From the territory of Issachar, they were given Kedesh, Daberath,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 73, 'Ramoth, and Anem, with their pasturelands.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 74, 'From the territory of Asher, they received Mashal, Abdon,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 75, 'Hukok, and Rehob, each with its pasturelands.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 76, 'From the territory of Naphtali, they were given Kedesh in Galilee, Hammon, and Kiriathaim, each with its pasturelands.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 77, 'The remaining descendants of Merari received from the territory of Zebulun the towns of Jokneam, Kartah, Rimmono, and Tabor, each with its pasturelands.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 78, 'From the territory of Reuben, east of the Jordan River opposite Jericho, they received Bezer (a desert town), Jahaz,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 79, 'Kedemoth, and Mephaath, each with its pasturelands.', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 80, 'And from the territory of Gad, they received Ramoth in Gilead, Mahanaim,', 'NLT'),
(17, 6, 81, 'Heshbon, and Jazer, each with its pasturelands.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 1, 'The four sons of Issachar were Tola, Puah, Jashub, and Shimron.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 2, 'The sons of Tola were Uzzi, Rephaiah, Jeriel, Jahmai, Ibsam, and Shemuel. Each of them was the leader of an ancestral clan. At the time of King David, the total number of men available for military service from these families was 22,600.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 3, 'The son of Uzzi was Izrahiah. The sons of Izrahiah were Michael, Obadiah, Joel, and Isshiah. These five became the leaders of clans.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 4, 'The total number of men available for military service among their descendants was 36,000, for all five of them had many wives and many sons.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 5, 'The total number of men available for military service from all the clans of the tribe of Issachar was 87,000. All of them were listed in their tribal genealogy.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 6, 'Three of Benjamin''s sons were Bela, Beker, and Jediael.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 7, 'The sons of Bela were Ezbon, Uzzi, Uzziel, Jerimoth, and Iri. These five warriors were the leaders of clans. The total number of men available for military service among their descendants was 22,034. All of them were listed in their family genealogy.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 8, 'The sons of Beker were Zemirah, Joash, Eliezer, Elioenai, Omri, Jeremoth, Abijah, Anathoth, and Alemeth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 9, 'According to their family genealogy, there were 20,200 men available for military service among their descendants, in addition to their clan leaders.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 10, 'The son of Jediael was Bilhan. The sons of Bilhan were Jeush, Benjamin, Ehud, Kenaanah, Zethan, Tarshish, and Ahishahar.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 11, 'They were the leaders of the clans of Jediael, and their descendants included 17,200 men available for military service.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 12, 'The sons of Ir were Shuppim and Huppim. Hushim was the son of Aher.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 13, 'The sons of Naphtali were Jahzeel, Guni, Jezer, and Shillem. They were all descendants of Jacob''s wife Bilhah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 14, 'The sons of Manasseh, born to his Aramean concubine, were Asriel and Makir. Makir was the father of Gilead.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 15, 'Makir found wives for Huppim and Shuppim. Makir''s sister was named Maacah. One of his descendants was Zelophehad, who had only daughters.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 16, 'Makir''s wife, Maacah, gave birth to a son whom she named Peresh. His brother''s name was Sheresh. The sons of Peresh were Ulam and Rakem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 17, 'The son of Ulam was Bedan. All these were considered Gileadites, descendants of Makir son of Manasseh.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 18, 'Makir''s sister Hammoleketh gave birth to Ishhod, Abiezer, and Mahlah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 19, 'The sons of Shemida were Ahian, Shechem, Likhi, and Aniam.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 20, 'The descendants of Ephraim were Shuthelah, Bered, Tahath, Eleadah, Tahath,', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 21, 'Zabad, and Shuthelah. Ephraim''s sons Ezer and Elead were killed trying to steal livestock from the local farmers near Gath.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 22, 'Their father, Ephraim, mourned for them a long time, and his relatives came to comfort him.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 23, 'Afterward Ephraim slept with his wife, and she became pregnant and gave birth to a son. Ephraim named him Beriah because of the tragedy his family had suffered.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 24, 'Ephraim had a daughter named Sheerah. She built the towns of Lower and Upper Beth-horon and Uzzen-sheerah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 25, 'Ephraim''s line of descent was Rephah, Resheph, Telah, Tahan,', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 26, 'Ladan, Ammihud, Elishama,', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 27, 'Nun, and Joshua.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 28, 'The descendants of Ephraim lived in the territory that included Bethel and its surrounding towns to the south, Naaran to the east, Gezer and its villages to the west, and Shechem and its surrounding villages to the north as far as Ayyah and its towns.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 29, 'Along the border of Manasseh were the towns of Beth-shan, Taanach, Megiddo, Dor, and their surrounding villages. The descendants of Joseph son of Israel lived in these towns.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 30, 'The sons of Asher were Imnah, Ishvah, Ishvi, and Beriah. They had a sister named Serah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 31, 'The sons of Beriah were Heber and Malkiel (the father of Birzaith).', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 32, 'The sons of Heber were Japhlet, Shomer, and Hotham. They had a sister named Shua.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 33, 'The sons of Japhlet were Pasach, Bimhal, and Ashvath.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 34, 'The sons of Shomer were Ahi, Rohgah, Hubbah, and Aram.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 35, 'The sons of his brother Helem were Zophah, Imna, Shelesh, and Amal.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 36, 'The sons of Zophah were Suah, Harnepher, Shual, Beri, Imrah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 37, 'Bezer, Hod, Shamma, Shilshah, Ithran, and Beera.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 38, 'The sons of Jether were Jephunneh, Pispah, and Ara.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 39, 'The sons of Ulla were Arah, Hanniel, and Rizia.', 'NLT'),
(17, 7, 40, 'Each of these descendants of Asher was the head of an ancestral clan. They were all skilled warriors and prominent leaders. There were 26,000 men available for military service among the descendants listed in their tribal genealogy.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 1, 'The sons of Benjamin, in order of age, included Bela (the oldest), Ashbel, Aharah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 2, 'Nohah, and Rapha.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 3, 'The sons of Bela were Addar, Gera, Abihud,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 4, 'Abishua, Naaman, Ahoah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 5, 'Gera, Shephuphan, and Huram.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 6, 'The sons of Ehud, leaders of the clans living at Geba, were driven out and moved to Manahath.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 7, 'Ehud''s sons were Naaman, Ahijah, and Gera. Gera, the father of Uzza and Ahihud, led them when they moved.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 8, 'After Shaharaim divorced his wives Hushim and Baara, he had children in the land of Moab.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 9, 'Hodesh, his new wife, gave birth to Jobab, Zibia, Mesha, Malcam,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 10, 'Jeuz, Sakia, and Mirmah. These sons all became the leaders of clans.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 11, 'Shaharaim''s wife Hushim had already given birth to Abitub and Elpaal.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 12, 'The sons of Elpaal were Eber, Misham, Shemed (who built Ono and Lod and their villages),', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 13, 'Beriah, and Shema. They were the leaders of the clans living in Aijalon, and they drove out the inhabitants of Gath.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 14, 'Ahio, Shashak, Jeremoth,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 15, 'Zebadiah, Arad, Eder,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 16, 'Michael, Ishpah, and Joha were the sons of Beriah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 17, 'Zebadiah, Meshullam, Hizki, Heber,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 18, 'Ishmerai, Izliah, and Jobab were the sons of Elpaal.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 19, 'Jakim, Zicri, Zabdi,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 20, 'Elienai, Zillethai, Eliel,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 21, 'Adaiah, Beraiah, and Shimrath were the sons of Shimei.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 22, 'Ishpan, Eber, Eliel,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 23, 'Abdon, Zicri, Hanan,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 24, 'Hananiah, Elam, Anthothijah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 25, 'Iphdeiah, and Penuel were the sons of Shashak.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 26, 'Shamsherai, Shehariah, Athaliah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 27, 'Jaareshiah, Elijah, and Zicri were the sons of Jeroham.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 28, 'These were the leaders of the ancestral clans, and they were listed in their tribal genealogy. They all lived in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 29, 'Jeiel (the father of Gibeon) lived in Gibeon. His wife''s name was Maacah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 30, 'and his oldest son was named Abdon. Jeiel''s other sons were Zur, Kish, Baal, Ner, Nadab,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 31, 'Gedor, Ahio, Zechariah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 32, 'and Mikloth, who was the father of Shimeam. All these families lived near each other in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 33, 'Ner was the father of Kish. Kish was the father of Saul. Saul was the father of Jonathan, Malkishua, Abinadab, and Eshbaal.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 34, 'Jonathan was the father of Meribbaal. Meribbaal was the father of Micah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 35, 'Micah was the father of Pithon, Melech, Tahrea, and Ahaz.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 36, 'Ahaz was the father of Jadah. Jadah was the father of Alemeth, Azmaveth, and Zimri. Zimri was the father of Moza.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 37, 'Moza was the father of Binea. Binea was the father of Rephaiah. Rephaiah was the father of Eleasah. Eleasah was the father of Azel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 38, 'Azel had six sons: Azrikam, Bokeru, Ishmael, Sheariah, Obadiah, and Hanan. These were the sons of Azel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 39, 'Azel''s brother Eshek had three sons: Ulam (the oldest), Jeush (the second), and Eliphelet (the third).', 'NLT'),
(17, 8, 40, 'The sons of Ulam were all skilled warriors and expert archers. They had many sons and grandsons--150 in all. All these were descendants of Benjamin.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 1, 'All Israel was listed in the genealogical record in The Book of the Kings of Israel. The Returning Exiles The people of Judah were exiled to Babylon because they were unfaithful to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 2, 'The first to return to their property in their former towns were common people. With them came some of the priests, Levites, and Temple assistants.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 3, 'People from the tribes of Judah, Benjamin, Ephraim, and Manasseh came and settled in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 4, 'One family that returned was that of Uthai son of Ammihud, son of Omri, son of Imri, son of Bani, a descendant of Perez son of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 5, 'Others returned from the Shilonite clan, including Asaiah (the oldest) and his sons.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 6, 'From the Zerahite clan, Jeuel returned with his relatives. In all, 690 families from the tribe of Judah returned.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 7, 'From the tribe of Benjamin came Sallu son of Meshullam, son of Hodaviah, son of Hassenuah;', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 8, 'Ibneiah son of Jeroham; Elah son of Uzzi, son of Micri; Meshullam son of Shephatiah, son of Reuel, son of Ibnijah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 9, 'These men were all leaders of clans, and they were listed in their tribal genealogy. In all, 956 families from the tribe of Benjamin returned.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 10, 'Among the priests who returned were Jedaiah, Jehoiarib, Jakin,', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 11, 'Azariah son of Hilkiah, son of Meshullam, son of Zadok, son of Meraioth, son of Ahitub. Azariah was the chief officer of the house of God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 12, 'Other returning priests were Adaiah son of Jeroham, son of Pashhur, son of Malkijah, and Maasai son of Adiel, son of Jahzerah, son of Meshullam, son of Meshillemith, son of Immer.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 13, 'In all, 1,760 priests returned. They were heads of clans and very able men. They were responsible for ministering at the house of God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 14, 'The Levites who returned were Shemaiah son of Hasshub, son of Azrikam, son of Hashabiah, a descendant of Merari;', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 15, 'Bakbakkar; Heresh; Galal; Mattaniah son of Mica, son of Zicri, son of Asaph;', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 16, 'Obadiah son of Shemaiah, son of Galal, son of Jeduthun; and Berekiah son of Asa, son of Elkanah, who lived in the area of Netophah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 17, 'The gatekeepers who returned were Shallum, Akkub, Talmon, Ahiman, and their relatives. Shallum was the chief gatekeeper.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 18, 'Prior to this time, they were responsible for the King''s Gate on the east side. These men served as gatekeepers for the camps of the Levites.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 19, 'Shallum was the son of Kore, a descendant of Abiasaph, from the clan of Korah. He and his relatives, the Korahites, were responsible for guarding the entrance to the sanctuary, just as their ancestors had guarded the Tabernacle in the camp of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 20, 'Phinehas son of Eleazar had been in charge of the gatekeepers in earlier times, and the LORD had been with him.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 21, 'And later Zechariah son of Meshelemiah had been responsible for guarding the entrance to the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 22, 'In all, there were 212 gatekeepers in those days, and they were listed by genealogies in their villages. David and Samuel the seer had appointed their ancestors because they were reliable men.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 23, 'These gatekeepers and their descendants, by their divisions, were responsible for guarding the entrance to the house of the LORD, the house that was formerly a tent.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 24, 'The gatekeepers were stationed on all four sides--east, west, north, and south.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 25, 'From time to time, their relatives in the villages came to share their duties for seven-day periods.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 26, 'The four chief gatekeepers, all Levites, were in an office of great trust, for they were responsible for the rooms and treasuries at the house of God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 27, 'They would spend the night around the house of God, since it was their duty to guard it. It was also their job to open the gates every morning.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 28, 'Some of the gatekeepers were assigned to care for the various utensils used in worship. They checked them in and out to avoid any loss.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 29, 'Others were responsible for the furnishings, the items in the sanctuary, and the supplies such as choice flour, wine, olive oil, incense, and spices.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 30, 'But it was the priests who prepared the spices and incense.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 31, 'Mattithiah, a Levite and the oldest son of Shallum the Korahite, was entrusted with baking the bread used in the offerings.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 32, 'And some members of the clan of Kohath were in charge of preparing the bread to be set on the table each Sabbath day.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 33, 'The musicians, all prominent Levites, lived at the Temple. They were exempt from other responsibilities there since they were on duty at all hours.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 34, 'All these men lived in Jerusalem. They were the heads of Levite families and were listed as prominent leaders in their tribal genealogy.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 35, 'Jeiel (the father of Gibeon) lived in Gibeon. His wife''s name was Maacah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 36, 'and his oldest son was named Abdon. Jeiel''s other sons were Zur, Kish, Baal, Ner, Nadab,', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 37, 'Gedor, Ahio, Zechariah, and Mikloth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 38, 'Mikloth was the father of Shimeam. All these families lived near each other in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 39, 'Ner was the father of Kish. Kish was the father of Saul. Saul was the father of Jonathan, Malkishua, Abinadab, and Eshbaal.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 40, 'Jonathan was the father of Meribbaal. Meribbaal was the father of Micah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 41, 'The sons of Micah were Pithon, Melech, Tahrea, and Ahaz.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 42, 'Ahaz was the father of Jadah. Jadah was the father of Alemeth, Azmaveth, and Zimri. Zimri was the father of Moza.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 43, 'Moza was the father of Binea. Binea''s son was Rephaiah. Rephaiah''s son was Eleasah. Eleasah''s son was Azel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 9, 44, 'Azel had six sons, and their names were Azrikam, Bokeru, Ishmael, Sheariah, Obadiah, and Hanan. These were the sons of Azel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 1, 'Now the Philistines attacked Israel, forcing the Israelites to flee. Many were slaughtered on the slopes of Mount Gilboa.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 2, 'The Philistines closed in on Saul and his sons, and they killed three of his sons--Jonathan, Abinadab, and Malkishua.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 3, 'The fighting grew very fierce around Saul, and the Philistine archers caught up with him and wounded him severely.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 4, 'Saul groaned to his armor bearer, "Take your sword and run me through before these pagan Philistines come and humiliate me." But his armor bearer was afraid and would not do it. So Saul took his own sword and fell on it.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 5, 'When his armor bearer realized that Saul was dead, he fell on his own sword and died.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 6, 'So Saul and his three sons died there together, bringing his dynasty to an end.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 7, 'When the Israelites in the Jezreel Valley saw that their army had been routed and that Saul and his sons were dead, they abandoned their towns and fled. So the Philistines moved in and occupied their towns.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 8, 'The next day when the Philistines went out to strip the dead, they found the bodies of Saul and his sons on Mount Gilboa.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 9, 'So they stripped off Saul''s armor and cut off his head. Then they proclaimed the news of Saul''s death before their idols and to the people throughout the land of Philistia.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 10, 'They placed his armor in the temple of their gods, and they fastened his head to the wall in the temple of Dagon.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 11, 'But when the people of Jabesh-gilead heard what the Philistines had done to Saul,', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 12, 'their warriors went out and brought the bodies of Saul and his three sons back to Jabesh. Then they buried their remains beneath the oak tree at Jabesh, and they fasted for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 13, 'So Saul died because he was unfaithful to the LORD. He failed to obey the LORD''s command, and he even consulted a medium', 'NLT'),
(17, 10, 14, 'instead of asking the LORD for guidance. So the LORD killed him and turned his kingdom over to David son of Jesse.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 1, 'Then all Israel went to David at Hebron and told him, "We are all members of your family.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 2, 'For a long time, even while Saul was our king, you were the one who really led Israel. And the LORD your God has told you, `You will be the shepherd of my people Israel. You will be their leader.''"', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 3, 'So there at Hebron David made a covenant with the leaders of Israel before the LORD. They anointed him king of Israel, just as the LORD had promised through Samuel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 4, 'Then David and all Israel went to Jerusalem (or Jebus, as it used to be called), where the Jebusites, original inhabitants of the land, lived.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 5, 'The people of Jebus said to David, "You will never get in here!" But David captured the fortress of Zion, now called the City of David.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 6, 'David had said to his troops, "Whoever leads the attack against the Jebusites will become the commander of my armies!" And Joab, the son of David''s sister Zeruiah, led the attack, so he became the commander of David''s armies.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 7, 'David made the fortress his home, and that is why it is called the City of David.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 8, 'He extended the city from the Millo to the surrounding area, while Joab rebuilt the rest of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 9, 'And David became more and more powerful, because the LORD Almighty was with him.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 10, 'These are the leaders of David''s mighty men. Together with all Israel, they determined to make David their king, just as the LORD had promised concerning Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 11, 'Here is the record of David''s mightiest men: The first was Jashobeam the Hacmonite, who was commander of the Three--the three greatest warriors among David''s men. He once used his spear to kill three hundred enemy warriors in a single battle.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 12, 'Next in rank among the Three was Eleazar son of Dodai, a descendant of Ahoah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 13, 'He was with David in the battle against the Philistines at Pas-dammim. The battle took place in a field full of barley, and the Israelite army fled.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 14, 'But Eleazar and David held their ground in the middle of the field and beat back the Philistines. So the LORD saved them by giving them a great victory.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 15, 'Once when David was at the rock near the cave of Adullam, the Philistine army was camped in the valley of Rephaim. The Three (who were among the Thirty--an elite group among David''s fighting men) went down to meet him there.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 16, 'David was staying in the stronghold at the time, and a Philistine detachment had occupied the town of Bethlehem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 17, 'David remarked longingly to his men, "Oh, how I would love some of that good water from the well in Bethlehem, the one by the gate."', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 18, 'So the Three broke through the Philistine lines, drew some water from the well, and brought it back to David. But David refused to drink it. Instead, he poured it out before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 19, '"God forbid that I should drink this!" he exclaimed. "This water is as precious as the blood of these men who risked their lives to bring it to me." So David did not drink it. This is an example of the exploits of the Three.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 20, 'Abishai, the brother of Joab, was the leader of the Thirty. He once used his spear to kill three hundred enemy warriors in a single battle. It was by such feats that he became as famous as the Three.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 21, 'Abishai was the most famous of the Thirty and was their commander, though he was not one of the Three.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 22, 'There was also Benaiah son of Jehoiada, a valiant warrior from Kabzeel. He did many heroic deeds, which included killing two of Moab''s mightiest warriors. Another time he chased a lion down into a pit. Then, despite the snow and slippery ground, he caught the lion and killed it.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 23, 'Another time, armed with only a club, he killed an Egyptian warrior who was seven and a half feet tall and whose spear was as thick as a weaver''s beam. Benaiah wrenched the spear from the Egyptian''s hand and killed him with it.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 24, 'These are some of the deeds that made Benaiah as famous as the Three.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 25, 'He was more honored than the other members of the Thirty, though he was not one of the Three. And David made him commander of his bodyguard.', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 26, 'These were also included among David''s mighty men: Asahel, Joab''s brother; Elhanan son of Dodo from Bethlehem;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 27, 'Shammah from Harod; Helez from Pelon;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 28, 'Ira son of Ikkesh from Tekoa; Abiezer from Anathoth;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 29, 'Sibbecai from Hushah; Zalmon from Ahoah;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 30, 'Maharai from Netophah; Heled son of Baanah from Netophah;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 31, 'Ithai son of Ribai from Gibeah (from the tribe of Benjamin); Benaiah from Pirathon;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 32, 'Hurai from near Nahale-gaash; Abi-albon the Arbathite;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 33, 'Azmaveth from Bahurim; Eliahba from Shaalbon;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 34, 'the sons of Jashen from Gizon; Jonathan son of Shagee from Harar;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 35, 'Ahiam son of Sharar from Harar; Eliphal son of Ur;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 36, 'Hepher from Mekerah; Ahijah from Pelon;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 37, 'Hezro from Carmel; Paarai son of Ezbai;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 38, 'Joel, the brother of Nathan; Mibhar son of Hagri;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 39, 'Zelek from Ammon; Naharai from Beeroth (Joab''s armor bearer);', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 40, 'Ira from Jattir; Gareb from Jattir;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 41, 'Uriah the Hittite; Zabad son of Ahlai;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 42, 'Adina son of Shiza, the Reubenite leader who had thirty men with him;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 43, 'Hanan son of Maacah; Joshaphat from Mithna;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 44, 'Uzzia from Ashtaroth; Shama and Jeiel, the sons of Hotham, from Aroer;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 45, 'Jediael son of Shimri; Joha, his brother, from Tiz;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 46, 'Eliel from Mahavah; Jeribai and Joshaviah, the sons of Elnaam; Ithmah from Moab;', 'NLT'),
(17, 11, 47, 'Eliel and Obed; Jaasiel from Zobah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 1, 'The following men joined David at Ziklag while he was hiding from Saul son of Kish. They were among the warriors who fought beside David in battle.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 2, 'All of them were expert archers, and they could shoot arrows or sling stones with their left hand as well as their right. They were all relatives of Saul from the tribe of Benjamin.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 3, 'Their leader was Ahiezer son of Shemaah from Gibeah; his brother Joash was second-in-command. These were the other warriors: Jeziel and Pelet, sons of Azmaveth; Beracah and Jehu from Anathoth;', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 4, 'Ishmaiah from Gibeon, a famous warrior and leader among the Thirty; Jeremiah, Jahaziel, Johanan, and Jozabad from Gederah;', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 5, 'Eluzai, Jerimoth, Bealiah, Shemariah, and Shephatiah from Haruph;', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 6, 'Elkanah, Isshiah, Azarel, Joezer, and Jashobeam, who were Korahites;', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 7, 'Joelah and Zebadiah, sons of Jeroham from Gedor.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 8, 'Some brave and experienced warriors from the tribe of Gad also defected to David while he was at the stronghold in the wilderness. They were expert with both shield and spear, as fierce as lions and as swift as deer on the mountains.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 9, 'Ezer was their leader. Obadiah was second. Eliab was third.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 10, 'Mishmannah was fourth. Jeremiah was fifth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 11, 'Attai was sixth. Eliel was seventh.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 12, 'Johanan was eighth. Elzabad was ninth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 13, 'Jeremiah was tenth. Macbannai was eleventh.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 14, 'These warriors from Gad were army commanders. The weakest among them could take on a hundred regular troops, and the strongest could take on a thousand!', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 15, 'They crossed the Jordan River during its seasonal flooding at the beginning of the year and drove out all the people living in the lowlands on both the east and west banks.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 16, 'Others from Benjamin and Judah came to David at the stronghold.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 17, 'David went out to meet them and said, "If you have come in peace to help me, we are friends. But if you have come to betray me to my enemies when I am innocent, then may the God of our ancestors see and judge you."', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 18, 'Then the Spirit came upon Amasai, who later became a leader among the Thirty, and he said, "We are yours, David! We are on your side, son of Jesse. Peace and prosperity be with you, and success to all who help you, for your God is the one who helps you." So David let them join him, and he made them officers over his troops.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 19, 'Some men from Manasseh defected from the Israelite army and joined David when he went with the Philistines to fight against Saul. But as it turned out, the Philistine leaders refused to let David and his men go with them. After much discussion, they sent them back, for they said, "It will cost us our lives if David switches loyalties to Saul and turns against us."', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 20, 'Here is a list of the men from Manasseh who defected to David as he was returning to Ziklag: Adnah, Jozabad, Jediael, Michael, Jozabad, Elihu, and Zillethai. Each commanded a thousand troops from the tribe of Manasseh.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 21, 'They helped David chase down bands of raiders, for they were all brave and able warriors who became commanders in his army.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 22, 'Day after day more men joined David until he had a great army, like the army of God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 23, 'These are the numbers of armed warriors who joined David at Hebron. They were all eager to see David become king instead of Saul, just as the LORD had promised.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 24, 'From the tribe of Judah, there were 6,800 warriors armed with shields and spears.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 25, 'From the tribe of Simeon, there were 7,100 warriors.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 26, 'From the tribe of Levi, there were 4,600 troops.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 27, 'This included Jehoiada, leader of the family of Aaron, who had 3,700 under his command.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 28, 'This also included Zadok, a young warrior, with twenty-two members of his family who were all officers.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 29, 'From the tribe of Benjamin, Saul''s relatives, there were 3,000 warriors. Most of the men from Benjamin had remained loyal to Saul until this time.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 30, 'From the tribe of Ephraim, there were 20,800 warriors, each famous in his own clan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 31, 'From the half-tribe of Manasseh west of the Jordan, 18,000 men were sent for the express purpose of helping David become king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 32, 'From the tribe of Issachar, there were 200 leaders of the tribe with their relatives. All these men understood the temper of the times and knew the best course for Israel to take.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 33, 'From the tribe of Zebulun, there were 50,000 skilled warriors. They were fully armed and prepared for battle and completely loyal to David.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 34, 'From the tribe of Naphtali, there were 1,000 officers and 37,000 warriors armed with shields and spears.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 35, 'From the tribe of Dan, there were 28,600 warriors, all prepared for battle.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 36, 'From the tribe of Asher, there were 40,000 trained warriors, all prepared for battle.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 37, 'From the east side of the Jordan River--where the tribes of Reuben and Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh lived--there were 120,000 troops armed with every kind of weapon.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 38, 'All these men came in battle array to Hebron with the single purpose of making David the king of Israel. In fact, all Israel agreed that David should be their king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 39, 'They feasted and drank with David for three days, for preparations had been made by their relatives for their arrival.', 'NLT'),
(17, 12, 40, 'And people from as far away as Issachar, Zebulun, and Naphtali brought food on donkeys, camels, mules, and oxen. Vast supplies of flour, fig cakes, raisins, wine, olive oil, cattle, and sheep were brought to the celebration. There was great joy throughout the land of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 1, 'David consulted with all his officials, including the generals and captains of his army.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 2, 'Then he addressed the entire assembly of Israel as follows: "If you approve and if it is the will of the LORD our God, let us send messages to all the Israelites throughout the land, including the priests and Levites in their towns and pasturelands. Let us invite them to come and join us.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 3, 'It is time to bring back the Ark of our God, for we neglected it during the reign of Saul."', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 4, 'The whole assembly agreed to this, for the people could see it was the right thing to do.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 5, 'So David summoned all the people of Israel, from one end of the country to the other, to join in bringing the Ark of God from Kiriath-jearim.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 6, 'Then David and all Israel went to Baalah of Judah (also called Kiriath-jearim) to bring back the Ark of God, which bears the name of the LORD who is enthroned between the cherubim.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 7, 'They transported the Ark of God from the house of Abinadab on a new cart, with Uzzah and Ahio guiding it.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 8, 'David and all Israel were celebrating before God with all their might, singing and playing all kinds of musical instruments--lyres, harps, tambourines, cymbals, and trumpets.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 9, 'But when they arrived at the threshing floor of Nacon, the oxen stumbled, and Uzzah put out his hand to steady the Ark.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 10, 'Then the LORD''s anger blazed out against Uzzah, and he struck him dead because he had laid his hand on the Ark. So Uzzah died there in the presence of God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 11, 'David was angry because the LORD''s anger had blazed out against Uzzah. He named that place Perez-uzzah (which means "outbreak against Uzzah"). It is still called that today.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 12, 'David was now afraid of God and asked, "How can I ever bring the Ark of God back into my care?"', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 13, 'So David decided not to move the Ark into the City of David. He took it instead to the home of Obed-edom of Gath.', 'NLT'),
(17, 13, 14, 'The Ark of God remained there with the family of Obed-edom for three months, and the LORD blessed him and his entire household.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 1, 'Now King Hiram of Tyre sent messengers to David, along with stonemasons and carpenters to build him a palace. Hiram also sent many cedar logs for lumber.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 2, 'And David realized that the LORD had made him king over Israel and had made his kingdom very great for the sake of his people Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 3, 'Then David married more wives in Jerusalem, and they had many sons and daughters.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 4, 'These are the names of David''s sons who were born in Jerusalem: Shimea, Shobab, Nathan, Solomon,', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 5, 'Ibhar, Elishua, Elpelet,', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 6, 'Nogah, Nepheg, Japhia,', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 7, 'Elishama, Eliada, and Eliphelet.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 8, 'When the Philistines heard that David had been anointed king over all Israel, they mobilized all their forces to capture him. But David was told they were coming, so he and his men marched out to meet them.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 9, 'The Philistines had arrived in the valley of Rephaim and raided it.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 10, 'So David asked God, "Should I go out to fight the Philistines? Will you hand them over to me?" The LORD replied, "Yes, go ahead. I will give you the victory."', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 11, 'So David and his troops went to Baal-perazim and defeated the Philistines there. "God has done it!" David exclaimed. "He used me to burst through my enemies like a raging flood!" So that place was named Baal-perazim (which means "the Lord who bursts through").', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 12, 'The Philistines had abandoned their idols there, so David gave orders to burn them up.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 13, 'But after a while, the Philistines returned and raided the valley again.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 14, 'And once again David asked God what to do. "Do not attack them straight on," God replied. "Instead, circle around behind them and attack them near the balsam trees.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 15, 'When you hear a sound like marching feet in the tops of the balsam trees, attack! That will be the signal that God is moving ahead of you to strike down the Philistines."', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 16, 'So David did what God commanded, and he struck down the Philistine army all the way from Gibeon to Gezer.', 'NLT'),
(17, 14, 17, 'So David''s fame spread everywhere, and the LORD caused all the nations to fear David.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 1, 'David now built several buildings for himself in the City of David. He also prepared a place for the Ark of God and set up a special tent there to shelter it.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 2, 'Then he issued these instructions: "When we transport the Ark of God this time, no one except the Levites may carry it. The LORD has chosen them to carry the Ark of the LORD and to minister before him forever."', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 3, 'Then David summoned all the Israelites to Jerusalem to bring the Ark of the LORD to the place he had prepared for it.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 4, 'These are the priests and Levites who were called together:', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 5, 'There were 120 from the clan of Kohath, with Uriel as their leader.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 6, 'There were 220 from the clan of Merari, with Asaiah as their leader.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 7, 'There were 130 from the clan of Gershon, with Joel as their leader.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 8, 'There were 200 descendants of Elizaphan, with Shemaiah as their leader.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 9, 'There were 80 descendants of Hebron, with Eliel as their leader.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 10, 'There were 112 descendants of Uzziel, with Amminadab as their leader.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 11, 'Then David summoned the priests, Zadok and Abiathar, and these Levite leaders: Uriel, Asaiah, Joel, Shemaiah, Eliel, and Amminadab.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 12, 'He said to them, "You are the leaders of the Levite families. You must purify yourselves and all your fellow Levites, so you can bring the Ark of the LORD, the God of Israel, to the place I have prepared for it.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 13, 'Because you Levites did not carry the Ark the first time, the anger of the LORD our God burst out against us. We failed to ask God how to move it in the proper way."', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 14, 'So the priests and the Levites purified themselves in order to bring the Ark of the LORD, the God of Israel, to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 15, 'Then the Levites carried the Ark of God on their shoulders with its carrying poles, just as the LORD had instructed Moses.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 16, 'David also ordered the Levite leaders to appoint a choir of Levites who were singers and musicians to sing joyful songs to the accompaniment of lyres, harps, and cymbals.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 17, 'So the Levites appointed Heman son of Joel, Asaph son of Berekiah, and Ethan son of Kushaiah from the clan of Merari to direct the musicians.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 18, 'The following men were chosen as their assistants: Zechariah, Jaaziel, Shemiramoth, Jehiel, Unni, Eliab, Benaiah, Maaseiah, Mattithiah, Eliphelehu, Mikneiah, and the gatekeepers, Obed-edom and Jeiel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 19, 'Heman, Asaph, and Ethan were chosen to sound the bronze cymbals.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 20, 'Zechariah, Aziel, Shemiramoth, Jehiel, Unni, Eliab, Maaseiah, and Benaiah were chosen to play the lyres.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 21, 'Mattithiah, Eliphelehu, Mikneiah, Obed-edom, Jeiel, and Azaziah were chosen to play the harps.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 22, 'Kenaniah, the head Levite, was chosen as the choir leader because of his skill.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 23, 'Berekiah and Elkanah were chosen to guard the Ark.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 24, 'Shebaniah, Joshaphat, Nethanel, Amasai, Zechariah, Benaiah, and Eliezer--all of whom were priests--were chosen to blow the trumpets as they marched in front of the Ark of God. Obed-edom and Jehiah were chosen to guard the Ark.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 25, 'Then David and the leaders of Israel and the generals of the army went to the home of Obed-edom to bring the Ark of the LORD''s covenant up to Jerusalem with a great celebration.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 26, 'And because God was clearly helping the Levites as they carried the Ark of the LORD''s covenant, they sacrificed seven bulls and seven lambs.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 27, 'David was dressed in a robe of fine linen, as were the Levites who carried the Ark, the singers, and Kenaniah the song leader. David was also wearing a priestly tunic.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 28, 'So all Israel brought up the Ark of the LORD''s covenant to Jerusalem with shouts of joy, the blowing of horns and trumpets, the crashing of cymbals, and loud playing on harps and lyres.', 'NLT'),
(17, 15, 29, 'But as the Ark of the LORD''s covenant entered the City of David, Michal, the daughter of Saul, looked down from her window. When she saw King David dancing and leaping for joy, she was filled with contempt for him.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 1, 'So they brought the Ark of God into the special tent David had prepared for it, and they sacrificed burnt offerings and peace offerings before God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 2, 'When he had finished, David blessed the people in the name of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 3, 'Then he gave a gift of food to every man and woman in Israel: a loaf of bread, a cake of dates, and a cake of raisins.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 4, 'David appointed the following Levites to lead the people in worship before the Ark of the LORD by asking for his blessings and giving thanks and praise to the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 5, 'Asaph, the leader of this group, sounded the cymbals. His assistants were Zechariah (the second), then Jeiel, Shemiramoth, Jehiel, Mattithiah, Eliab, Benaiah, Obed-edom, and Jeiel. They played the harps and lyres.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 6, 'The priests, Benaiah and Jahaziel, played the trumpets regularly before the Ark of God''s covenant.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 7, 'That day David gave to Asaph and his fellow Levites this song of thanksgiving to the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 8, 'Give thanks to the LORD and proclaim his greatness. Let the whole world know what he has done.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 9, 'Sing to him; yes, sing his praises. Tell everyone about his miracles.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 10, 'Exult in his holy name; O worshipers of the LORD, rejoice!', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 11, 'Search for the LORD and for his strength, and keep on searching.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 12, 'Think of the wonderful works he has done, the miracles, and the judgments he handed down,', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 13, 'O children of Israel, God''s servant, O descendants of Jacob, God''s chosen one.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 14, 'He is the LORD our God. His rule is seen throughout the land.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 15, 'He always stands by his covenant--the commitment he made to a thousand generations.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 16, 'This is the covenant he made with Abraham and the oath he swore to Isaac.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 17, 'He confirmed it to Jacob as a decree, to the people of Israel as a never-ending treaty:', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 18, '"I will give you the land of Canaan as your special possession."', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 19, 'He said this when they were few in number, a tiny group of strangers in Canaan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 20, 'They wandered back and forth between nations, from one kingdom to another.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 21, 'Yet he did not let anyone oppress them. He warned kings on their behalf:', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 22, '"Do not touch these people I have chosen, and do not hurt my prophets."', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 23, 'Let the whole earth sing to the LORD! Each day proclaim the good news that he saves.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 24, 'Publish his glorious deeds among the nations. Tell everyone about the amazing things he does.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 25, 'Great is the LORD! He is most worthy of praise! He is to be revered above all gods.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 26, 'The gods of other nations are merely idols, but the LORD made the heavens!', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 27, 'Honor and majesty surround him; strength and beauty are in his dwelling.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 28, 'O nations of the world, recognize the LORD, recognize that the LORD is glorious and strong.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 29, 'Give to the LORD the glory he deserves! Bring your offering and come to worship him. Worship the LORD in all his holy splendor.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 30, 'Let all the earth tremble before him. The world is firmly established and cannot be shaken.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 31, 'Let the heavens be glad, and let the earth rejoice! Tell all the nations that the LORD is king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 32, 'Let the sea and everything in it shout his praise! Let the fields and their crops burst forth with joy!', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 33, 'Let the trees of the forest rustle with praise before the LORD! For he is coming to judge the earth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 34, 'Give thanks to the LORD, for he is good! His faithful love endures forever.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 35, 'Cry out, "Save us, O God of our salvation! Gather and rescue us from among the nations, so we can thank your holy name and rejoice and praise you."', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 36, 'Blessed be the LORD, the God of Israel, from everlasting to everlasting! And all the people shouted "Amen!" and praised the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 37, 'David arranged for Asaph and his fellow Levites to minister regularly before the Ark of the LORD''s covenant, doing whatever needed to be done each day.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 38, 'This group included Obed-edom (son of Jeduthun), Hosah, and sixty-eight other Levites as gatekeepers.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 39, 'Meanwhile, David stationed Zadok the priest and his fellow priests at the Tabernacle of the LORD on the hill of Gibeon, where they continued to minister before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 40, 'They sacrificed the regular burnt offerings to the LORD each morning and evening on the altar set aside for that purpose, obeying everything written in the law of the LORD, which he had given to Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 41, 'David also appointed Heman, Jeduthun, and the others chosen by name to give thanks to the LORD, "for his faithful love endures forever."', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 42, 'They used their trumpets, cymbals, and other instruments to accompany the songs of praise to God. And the sons of Jeduthun were appointed as gatekeepers.', 'NLT'),
(17, 16, 43, 'Then all the people returned to their homes, and David returned home to bless his family.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 1, 'Now when David was settled in his palace, he said to Nathan the prophet, "Here I am living in this beautiful cedar palace, but the Ark of the LORD''s covenant is out in a tent!"', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 2, 'Nathan replied, "Go ahead with what you have in mind, for God is with you."', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 3, 'But that same night God said to Nathan,', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 4, '"Go and tell my servant David, `This is what the LORD says: You are not the one to build me a temple to live in.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 5, 'I have never lived in a temple, from the day I brought the Israelites out of Egypt until now. My home has always been a tent, moving from one place to another.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 6, 'And I never once complained to Israel''s leaders, the shepherds of my people. I have never asked them, "Why haven''t you built me a beautiful cedar temple?"''', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 7, '"Now go and say to my servant David, `This is what the LORD Almighty says: I chose you to lead my people Israel when you were just a shepherd boy, tending your sheep out in the pasture.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 8, 'I have been with you wherever you have gone, and I have destroyed all your enemies. Now I will make your name famous throughout the earth!', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 9, 'And I have provided a permanent homeland for my people Israel, a secure place where they will never be disturbed. It will be their own land where wicked nations won''t oppress them as they did in the past,', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 10, 'from the time I appointed judges to rule my people. And I will subdue all your enemies. "`And now I declare that the LORD will build a house for you--a dynasty of kings!', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 11, 'For when you die, I will raise up one of your sons, and I will make his kingdom strong.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 12, 'He is the one who will build a house--a temple--for me. And I will establish his throne forever.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 13, 'I will be his father, and he will be my son. I will not take my unfailing love from him as I took it from Saul, who ruled before you.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 14, 'I will establish him over my dynasty and my kingdom for all time, and his throne will be secure forever.''"', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 15, 'So Nathan went back to David and told him everything the LORD had said.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 16, 'Then King David went in and sat before the LORD and prayed, "Who am I, O LORD God, and what is my family, that you have brought me this far?', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 17, 'And now, O God, in addition to everything else, you speak of giving me a lasting dynasty! You speak as though I were someone very great, O LORD God!', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 18, 'What more can I say about the way you have honored me? You know what I am really like.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 19, 'For my sake, O LORD, and according to your will, you have done all these great things and have made them known.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 20, '"O LORD, there is no one like you--there is no other God. We have never even heard of another god like you!', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 21, 'What other nation on earth is like Israel? What other nation, O God, have you redeemed from slavery to be your own people? You made a great name for yourself when you rescued your people from Egypt. You performed awesome miracles and drove out the nations that stood in their way.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 22, 'You chose Israel to be your people forever, and you, O LORD, have become their God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 23, '"And now, O LORD, do as you have promised concerning me and my family. May it be a promise that will last forever.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 24, 'And may your name be established and honored forever so that all the world will say, `The LORD Almighty is God over Israel!'' And may the dynasty of your servant David be established in your presence.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 25, '"O my God, I have been bold enough to pray this prayer because you have revealed that you will build a house for me--an eternal dynasty!', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 26, 'For you are God, O LORD. And you have promised these good things to me, your servant.', 'NLT'),
(17, 17, 27, 'And now, it has pleased you to bless me and my family so that our dynasty will continue forever before you. For when you grant a blessing, O LORD, it is an eternal blessing!"', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 1, 'After this, David subdued and humbled the Philistines by conquering Gath and its surrounding towns.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 2, 'David also conquered the land of Moab, and the Moabites became David''s subjects and brought him tribute money.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 3, 'Then David destroyed the forces of King Hadadezer of Zobah, as far as Hamath, when Hadadezer marched out to strengthen his control along the Euphrates River.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 4, 'David captured one thousand chariots, seven thousand charioteers, and twenty thousand foot soldiers. Then he crippled all but one hundred of the chariot horses.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 5, 'When Arameans from Damascus arrived to help Hadadezer, David killed twenty-two thousand of them.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 6, 'Then he placed several army garrisons in Damascus, the Aramean capital, and the Arameans became David''s subjects and brought him tribute money. So the LORD gave David victory wherever he went.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 7, 'David brought the gold shields of Hadadezer''s officers to Jerusalem,', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 8, 'along with a large amount of bronze from Hadadezer''s cities of Tebah and Cun. Later Solomon melted the bronze and used it for the Temple. He molded it into the bronze Sea, the pillars, and the various bronze utensils used at the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 9, 'When King Toi of Hamath heard that David had destroyed the army of King Hadadezer of Zobah,', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 10, 'he sent his son Joram to congratulate David on his success. Hadadezer and Toi had long been enemies, and there had been many wars between them. Joram presented David with many gifts of gold, silver, and bronze.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 11, 'King David dedicated all these gifts to the LORD, along with the silver and gold he had taken from the other nations he had subdued--Edom, Moab, Ammon, Philistia, and Amalek.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 12, 'Abishai son of Zeruiah destroyed eighteen thousand Edomites in the Valley of Salt.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 13, 'He placed army garrisons throughout Edom, and all the Edomites became David''s subjects. This was another example of how the LORD made David victorious wherever he went.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 14, 'David reigned over all Israel and was fair to everyone.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 15, 'Joab son of Zeruiah was commander of the army. Jehoshaphat son of Ahilud was the royal historian.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 16, 'Zadok son of Ahitub and Ahimelech son of Abiathar were the priests. Seraiah was the court secretary.', 'NLT'),
(17, 18, 17, 'Benaiah son of Jehoiada was captain of the king''s bodyguard. David''s sons served as the king''s chief assistants.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 1, 'Some time after this, King Nahash of the Ammonites died, and his son Hanun became king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 2, 'David said, "I am going to show complete loyalty to Hanun because his father, Nahash, was always completely loyal to me." So David sent ambassadors to express sympathy to Hanun about his father''s death. But when David''s ambassadors arrived in the land of Ammon,', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 3, 'Hanun''s advisers said to him, "Do you really think these men are coming here to honor your father? No! David has sent them to spy out the land so that they can come in and conquer it!"', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 4, 'So Hanun seized David''s ambassadors and shaved their beards, cut off their robes at the buttocks, and sent them back to David in shame.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 5, 'When David heard what had happened, he sent messengers to tell the men to stay at Jericho until their beards grew out, for they were very embarrassed by their appearance.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 6, 'Now the people of Ammon realized how seriously they had angered David, so Hanun and the Ammonites sent thirty-eight tons of silver to hire chariots and troops from Aram-naharaim, Aram-maacah, and Zobah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 7, 'They also hired thirty-two thousand chariots and secured the support of the king of Maacah and his army. These forces camped at Medeba, where they were joined by the Ammonite troops that Hanun had recruited from his own towns.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 8, 'When David heard about this, he sent Joab and all his warriors to fight them.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 9, 'The Ammonite troops drew up their battle lines at the gate of the city, while the other kings positioned themselves to fight in the open fields.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 10, 'When Joab saw that he would have to fight on two fronts, he chose the best troops in his army. He placed them under his personal command and led them out to fight the Arameans in the fields.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 11, 'He left the rest of the army under the command of his brother Abishai, who was to attack the Ammonites.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 12, '"If the Arameans are too strong for me, then come over and help me," Joab told his brother. "And if the Ammonites are too strong for you, I will help you.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 13, 'Be courageous! Let us fight bravely to save our people and the cities of our God. May the LORD''s will be done."', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 14, 'When Joab and his troops attacked, the Arameans began to run away.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 15, 'And when the Ammonites saw the Arameans running, they ran from Abishai and retreated into the city. Then Joab returned to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 16, 'The Arameans now realized that they were no match for Israel, so they summoned additional Aramean troops from the other side of the Euphrates River. These troops arrived under the command of Shobach, the commander of all Hadadezer''s forces.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 17, 'When David heard what was happening, he mobilized all Israel, crossed the Jordan River, and positioned his troops in battle formation. Then he engaged the enemy troops in battle, and they fought against him.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 18, 'But again the Arameans fled from the Israelites. This time David''s forces killed seven thousand charioteers and forty thousand foot soldiers, including Shobach, the commander of their army.', 'NLT'),
(17, 19, 19, 'When the servants of Hadadezer realized they had been defeated by Israel, they surrendered to David and became his subjects. After that, the Arameans were no longer willing to help the Ammonites.', 'NLT'),
(17, 20, 1, 'The following spring, the time of year when kings go to war, Joab led the Israelite army in successful attacks against the towns and villages of the Ammonites. In the process they laid siege to the city of Rabbah and destroyed it. But David had stayed behind in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 20, 2, 'When David arrived at Rabbah, he removed the crown from the king''s head, and it was placed on David''s own head. The crown was made of gold and set with gems, and it weighed about seventy-five pounds. David took a vast amount of plunder from the city.', 'NLT'),
(17, 20, 3, 'He also made slaves of the people of Rabbah and forced them to labor with saws, picks, and axes. That is how he dealt with the people of all the Ammonite cities. Then David and his army returned to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 20, 4, 'After this, war broke out with the Philistines at Gezer. As they fought, Sibbecai from Hushah killed Saph, a descendant of the giants, and so the Philistines were subdued.', 'NLT'),
(17, 20, 5, 'During another battle with the Philistines, Elhanan son of Jair killed Lahmi, the brother of Goliath of Gath. The handle of Lahmi''s spear was as thick as a weaver''s beam!', 'NLT'),
(17, 20, 6, 'In another battle with the Philistines at Gath, a huge man with six fingers on each hand and six toes on each foot--a descendant of the giants--', 'NLT'),
(17, 20, 7, 'defied and taunted Israel. But he was killed by Jonathan, the son of David''s brother Shimea.', 'NLT'),
(17, 20, 8, 'These Philistines were descendants of the giants of Gath, but they were killed by David and his warriors.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 1, 'Satan rose up against Israel and caused David to take a census of the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 2, 'David gave these orders to Joab and his commanders: "Take a census of all the people in the land--from Beersheba in the south to Dan in the north--and bring me the totals so I may know how many there are."', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 3, 'But Joab replied, "May the LORD increase the number of his people a hundred times over! But why, my lord, do you want to do this? Are they not all your servants? Why must you cause Israel to sin?"', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 4, 'But the king insisted that Joab take the census, so Joab traveled throughout Israel to count the people. Then he returned to Jerusalem', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 5, 'and reported the number of people to David. There were 1,100,000 men of military age in Israel, and 470,000 in Judah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 6, 'But Joab did not include the tribes of Levi and Benjamin in the census because he was so distressed at what the king had made him do.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 7, 'God was very displeased with the census, and he punished Israel for it.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 8, 'Then David said to God, "I have sinned greatly and shouldn''t have taken the census. Please forgive me for doing this foolish thing."', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 9, 'Then the LORD spoke to Gad, David''s seer. This was the message:', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 10, '"Go and say to David, `This is what the LORD says: I will give you three choices. Choose one of these punishments, and I will do it.''"', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 11, 'So Gad came to David and said, "These are the choices the LORD has given you.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 12, 'You may choose three years of famine, three months of destruction by your enemies, or three days of severe plague as the angel of the LORD brings devastation throughout the land of Israel. Think this over and let me know what answer to give the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 13, '"This is a desperate situation!" David replied to Gad. "But let me fall into the hands of the LORD, for his mercy is very great. Do not let me fall into human hands."', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 14, 'So the LORD sent a plague upon Israel, and seventy thousand people died as a result.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 15, 'And God sent an angel to destroy Jerusalem. But just as the angel was preparing to destroy it, the LORD relented and said to the death angel, "Stop! That is enough!" At that moment the angel of the LORD was standing by the threshing floor of Araunah the Jebusite.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 16, 'David looked up and saw the angel of the LORD standing between heaven and earth with his sword drawn, stretched out over Jerusalem. So David and the leaders of Israel put on sackcloth to show their distress and fell down with their faces to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 17, 'And David said to God, "I am the one who called for the census! I am the one who has sinned and done wrong! But these people are innocent--what have they done? O LORD my God, let your anger fall against me and my family, but do not destroy your people."', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 18, 'Then the angel of the LORD told Gad to instruct David to build an altar to the LORD at the threshing floor of Araunah the Jebusite.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 19, 'So David obeyed the instructions the LORD had given him through Gad.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 20, 'Araunah, who was busy threshing wheat at the time, turned and saw the angel there. His four sons, who were with him, ran away and hid.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 21, 'When Araunah saw the king approaching, he left his threshing floor and bowed to the ground before David.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 22, 'David said to Araunah, "Let me buy this threshing floor from you at its full price. Then I will build an altar to the LORD there, so that he will stop the plague."', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 23, '"Take it, my lord, and use it as you wish," Araunah said to David. "Here are oxen for the burnt offerings, and you can use the threshing tools for wood to build a fire on the altar. And take the wheat for the grain offering. I will give it all to you."', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 24, 'But the king replied to Araunah, "No, I insist on paying what it is worth. I cannot take what is yours and give it to the LORD. I will not offer a burnt offering that has cost me nothing!"', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 25, 'So David gave Araunah six hundred pieces of gold in payment for the threshing floor.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 26, 'David built an altar there to the LORD and sacrificed burnt offerings and peace offerings. And when David prayed, the LORD answered him by sending fire from heaven to burn up the offering on the altar.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 27, 'Then the LORD spoke to the angel, who put the sword back into its sheath.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 28, 'When David saw that the LORD had answered his prayer, he offered sacrifices there at Araunah''s threshing floor.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 29, 'At that time, the Tabernacle of the LORD and the altar that Moses made in the wilderness were located at the hill of Gibeon.', 'NLT'),
(17, 21, 30, 'But David was not able to go there to inquire of God, because he was terrified by the drawn sword of the angel of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 1, 'Then David said, "This will be the location for the Temple of the LORD God and the place of the altar for Israel''s burnt offerings!"', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 2, 'So David gave orders to call together the foreigners living in Israel, and he assigned them the task of preparing blocks of stone for building the Temple of God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 3, 'David provided large amounts of iron for the nails that would be needed for the doors in the gates and for the clamps, and more bronze than they could ever weigh.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 4, 'He also provided innumerable cedar logs, for the men of Tyre and Sidon had brought vast amounts of cedar to David.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 5, 'David said, "My son Solomon is still young and inexperienced, and the Temple of the LORD must be a magnificent structure, famous and glorious throughout the world. So I will begin making preparations for it now." So David collected vast amounts of building materials before his death.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 6, 'Then David sent for his son Solomon and instructed him to build a Temple for the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 7, '"I wanted to build a Temple to honor the name of the LORD my God," David told him.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 8, '"But the LORD said to me, `You have killed many men in the great battles you have fought. And since you have shed so much blood before me, you will not be the one to build a Temple to honor my name.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 9, 'But you will have a son who will experience peace and rest. I will give him peace with his enemies in all the surrounding lands. His name will be Solomon, and I will give peace and quiet to Israel during his reign.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 10, 'He is the one who will build a Temple to honor my name. He will be my son, and I will be his father. And I will establish the throne of his kingdom over Israel forever.''', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 11, '"Now, my son, may the LORD be with you and give you success as you follow his instructions in building the Temple of the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 12, 'And may the LORD give you wisdom and understanding, that you may obey the law of the LORD your God as you rule over Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 13, 'For if you carefully obey the laws and regulations that the LORD gave to Israel through Moses, you will be successful. Be strong and courageous; do not be afraid or lose heart!', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 14, '"I have worked hard to provide materials for building the Temple of the LORD--nearly four thousand tons of gold, nearly forty thousand tons of silver, and so much iron and bronze that it cannot be weighed. I have also gathered lumber and stone for the walls, though you may need to add more.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 15, 'You have many skilled stonemasons and carpenters and craftsmen of every kind available to you.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 16, 'They are expert goldsmiths and silversmiths and workers of bronze and iron. Now begin the work, and may the LORD be with you!"', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 17, 'Then David ordered all the leaders of Israel to assist Solomon in this project.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 18, '"The LORD your God is with you," he declared. "He has given you peace with the surrounding nations. He has handed them over to me, and they are now subject to the LORD and his people.', 'NLT'),
(17, 22, 19, 'Now seek the LORD your God with all your heart. Build the sanctuary of the LORD God so that you can bring the Ark of the LORD''s covenant and the holy vessels of God into the Temple built to honor the LORD''s name."', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 1, 'When David was an old man, he appointed his son Solomon to be king over Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 2, 'David summoned all the political leaders of Israel, together with the priests and Levites, for the coronation ceremony.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 3, 'All the Levites who were thirty years old or older were counted, and the total came to thirty-eight thousand.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 4, 'Then David said, "Twenty-four thousand of them will supervise the work at the Temple of the LORD. Six thousand are to serve as officials and judges.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 5, 'Four thousand will work as gatekeepers, and another four thousand will praise the LORD with the musical instruments I have made."', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 6, 'Then David divided the Levites into divisions named after the clans descended from the three sons of Levi--Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 7, 'The Gershonite family units were defined by their lines of descent from Libni and Shimei, the sons of Gershon.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 8, 'Three of the descendants of Libni were Jehiel (the family leader), Zetham, and Joel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 9, 'These were the leaders of the family of Libni. Three of the descendants of Shimei were Shelomoth, Haziel, and Haran.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 10, 'Four other descendants of Shimei were Jahath, Ziza, Jeush, and Beriah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 11, 'Jahath was the family leader, and Ziza was next. Jeush and Beriah were counted as a single family because neither had many sons.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 12, 'The descendants of Kohath included Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 13, 'The sons of Amram were Aaron and Moses. Aaron and his descendants were set apart to dedicate the most holy things, to offer sacrifices in the LORD''s presence, to serve the LORD, and to pronounce blessings in his name forever.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 14, 'As for Moses, the man of God, his sons were included with the tribe of Levi.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 15, 'The sons of Moses were Gershom and Eliezer.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 16, 'The descendants of Gershom included Shebuel, the family leader.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 17, 'Eliezer had only one son, Rehabiah, the family leader. Rehabiah had numerous descendants.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 18, 'The descendants of Izhar included Shelomith, the family leader.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 19, 'The descendants of Hebron included Jeriah (the family leader), Amariah (the second), Jahaziel (the third), and Jekameam (the fourth).', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 20, 'The descendants of Uzziel included Micah (the family leader) and Isshiah (the second).', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 21, 'The descendants of Merari included Mahli and Mushi. The sons of Mahli were Eleazar and Kish.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 22, 'Eleazar died with no sons, only daughters. His daughters married their cousins, the sons of Kish.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 23, 'The three sons of Mushi were Mahli, Eder, and Jerimoth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 24, 'These were the descendants of Levi by clans, the leaders of their family groups, registered carefully by name. Each had to be twenty years old or older to qualify for service in the house of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 25, 'For David said, "The LORD, the God of Israel, has given us peace, and he will always live in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 26, 'Now the Levites will no longer need to carry the Tabernacle and its utensils from place to place."', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 27, 'It was according to David''s final instructions that all the Levites twenty years old or older were registered for service.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 28, 'The work of the Levites was to assist the priests, the descendants of Aaron, as they served at the house of the LORD. They also took care of the courtyards and side rooms, helped perform the ceremonies of purification, and served in many other ways in the house of God.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 29, 'They were in charge of the sacred bread that was set out on the table, the choice flour for the grain offerings, the wafers made without yeast, the cakes cooked in olive oil, and the other mixed breads. They were also responsible to check all the weights and measures.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 30, 'And each morning and evening they stood before the LORD to sing songs of thanks and praise to him.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 31, 'They assisted with the burnt offerings that were presented to the LORD on Sabbath days, at new moon celebrations, and at all the appointed festivals. The proper number of Levites served in the LORD''s presence at all times, following all the procedures they had been given.', 'NLT'),
(17, 23, 32, 'And so, under the supervision of the priests, the Levites watched over the Tabernacle and the Temple and faithfully carried out their duties of service at the house of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 1, 'This is how Aaron''s descendants, the priests, were divided into groups for service. The sons of Aaron were Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 2, 'But Nadab and Abihu died before their father did, and they had no sons. So only Eleazar and Ithamar were left to carry on as priests.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 3, 'With the help of Zadok, who was a descendant of Eleazar, and of Ahimelech, who was a descendant of Ithamar, David divided Aaron''s descendants into groups according to their various duties.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 4, 'Eleazar''s descendants were divided into sixteen groups and Ithamar''s into eight, for there were more family leaders among the descendants of Eleazar.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 5, 'All tasks were assigned to the various groups by means of sacred lots so that no preference would be shown, for there were many qualified officials serving God in the sanctuary from among the descendants of both Eleazar and Ithamar.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 6, 'Shemaiah son of Nethanel, a Levite, acted as secretary and wrote down the names and assignments in the presence of the king, Zadok the priest, Ahimelech son of Abiathar, and the family leaders of the priests and Levites. The descendants of Eleazar and Ithamar took turns casting lots.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 7, 'The first lot fell to Jehoiarib. The second lot fell to Jedaiah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 8, 'The third lot fell to Harim. The fourth lot fell to Seorim.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 9, 'The fifth lot fell to Malkijah. The sixth lot fell to Mijamin.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 10, 'The seventh lot fell to Hakkoz. The eighth lot fell to Abijah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 11, 'The ninth lot fell to Jeshua. The tenth lot fell to Shecaniah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 12, 'The eleventh lot fell to Eliashib. The twelfth lot fell to Jakim.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 13, 'The thirteenth lot fell to Huppah. The fourteenth lot fell to Jeshebeab.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 14, 'The fifteenth lot fell to Bilgah. The sixteenth lot fell to Immer.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 15, 'The seventeenth lot fell to Hezir. The eighteenth lot fell to Happizzez.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 16, 'The nineteenth lot fell to Pethahiah. The twentieth lot fell to Jehezkel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 17, 'The twenty-first lot fell to Jakin. The twenty-second lot fell to Gamul.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 18, 'The twenty-third lot fell to Delaiah. The twenty-fourth lot fell to Maaziah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 19, 'Each group carried out its duties in the house of the LORD according to the procedures established by their ancestor Aaron in obedience to the commands of the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 20, 'These were the other family leaders descended from Levi: From the descendants of Amram, the leader was Shebuel. From the descendants of Shebuel, the leader was Jehdeiah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 21, 'From the descendants of Rehabiah, the leader was Isshiah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 22, 'From the descendants of Izhar, the leader was Shelomith. From the descendants of Shelomith, the leader was Jahath.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 23, 'From the descendants of Hebron, Jeriah was the leader, Amariah was second-in-command, Jahaziel was third, and Jekameam was fourth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 24, 'From the descendants of Uzziel, the leader was Micah. From the descendants of Micah, the leader was Shamir,', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 25, 'along with Isshiah, the brother of Micah. From the descendants of Isshiah, the leader was Zechariah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 26, 'From the descendants of Merari, the leaders were Mahli and Mushi. From the descendants of Jaaziah, the leader was Beno.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 27, 'From the descendants of Merari through Jaaziah, the leaders were Beno, Shoham, Zaccur, and Ibri.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 28, 'From the descendants of Mahli, the leader was Eleazar, though he had no sons.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 29, 'From the descendants of Kish, the leader was Jerahmeel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 30, 'From the descendants of Mushi, the leaders were Mahli, Eder, and Jerimoth. These were the descendants of Levi in their various families.', 'NLT'),
(17, 24, 31, 'Like the descendants of Aaron, they were assigned to their duties by means of sacred lots, without regard to age or rank. It was done in the presence of King David, Zadok, Ahimelech, and the family leaders of the priests and the Levites.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 1, 'David and the army commanders then appointed men from the families of Asaph, Heman, and Jeduthun to proclaim God''s messages to the accompaniment of harps, lyres, and cymbals. Here is a list of their names and their work:', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 2, 'From the sons of Asaph, there were Zaccur, Joseph, Nethaniah, and Asarelah. They worked under the direction of their father, Asaph, who proclaimed God''s messages by the king''s orders.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 3, 'Jeduthun had six sons: Gedaliah, Zeri, Jeshaiah, Shimei, Hashabiah, and Mattithiah. They worked under the direction of their father, Jeduthun, who proclaimed God''s messages to the accompaniment of the harp, offering thanks and praise to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 4, 'Heman''s sons were Bukkiah, Mattaniah, Uzziel, Shubael, Jerimoth, Hananiah, Hanani, Eliathah, Geddalti, Romamti-ezer, Joshbekashah, Mallothi, Hothir, and Mahazioth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 5, 'All these were the sons of Heman, the king''s seer, for God had honored him with fourteen sons and three daughters.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 6, 'All these men were under the direction of their fathers as they made music at the house of the LORD. Their responsibilities included the playing of cymbals, lyres, and harps at the house of God. Asaph, Jeduthun, and Heman reported directly to the king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 7, 'They and their families were all trained in making music before the LORD, and each of them--288 in all--was an accomplished musician.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 8, 'The musicians were appointed to their particular term of service by means of sacred lots, without regard to whether they were young or old, teacher or student.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 9, 'The first lot fell to Joseph of the Asaph clan and twelve of his sons and relatives. The second lot fell to Gedaliah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 10, 'The third lot fell to Zaccur and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 11, 'The fourth lot fell to Zeri and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 12, 'The fifth lot fell to Nethaniah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 13, 'The sixth lot fell to Bukkiah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 14, 'The seventh lot fell to Asarelah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 15, 'The eighth lot fell to Jeshaiah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 16, 'The ninth lot fell to Mattaniah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 17, 'The tenth lot fell to Shimei and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 18, 'The eleventh lot fell to Uzziel and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 19, 'The twelfth lot fell to Hashabiah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 20, 'The thirteenth lot fell to Shubael and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 21, 'The fourteenth lot fell to Mattithiah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 22, 'The fifteenth lot fell to Jerimoth and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 23, 'The sixteenth lot fell to Hananiah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 24, 'The seventeenth lot fell to Joshbekashah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 25, 'The eighteenth lot fell to Hanani and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 26, 'The nineteenth lot fell to Mallothi and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 27, 'The twentieth lot fell to Eliathah and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 28, 'The twenty-first lot fell to Hothir and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 29, 'The twenty-second lot fell to Geddalti and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 30, 'The twenty-third lot fell to Mahazioth and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 25, 31, 'The twenty-fourth lot fell to Romamti-ezer and twelve of his sons and relatives.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 1, 'These are the divisions of the gatekeepers: From the Korahites, there was Meshelemiah son of Kore, of the family of Asaph.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 2, 'The sons of Meshelemiah were Zechariah (the oldest), Jediael (the second), Zebadiah (the third), Jathniel (the fourth),', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 3, 'Elam (the fifth), Jehohanan (the sixth), and Eliehoenai (the seventh).', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 4, 'The sons of Obed-edom, also gatekeepers, were Shemaiah (the oldest), Jehozabad (the second), Joah (the third), Sacar (the fourth), Nethanel (the fifth),', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 5, 'Ammiel (the sixth), Issachar (the seventh), and Peullethai (the eighth). God had richly blessed Obed-edom.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 6, 'Obed-edom''s son Shemaiah had sons with great ability who earned positions of great authority in the clan.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 7, 'Their names were Othni, Rephael, Obed, and Elzabad. Their relatives, Elihu and Semakiah, were also very capable men.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 8, 'All of these descendants of Obed-edom, including their sons and grandsons--sixty-two of them in all--were very capable men, well qualified for their work.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 9, 'Meshelemiah''s eighteen sons and relatives were also very capable men.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 10, 'Hosah, of the Merari clan, appointed Shimri as the leader among his sons, though he was not the oldest.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 11, 'His other sons included Hilkiah (the second), Tebaliah (the third), and Zechariah (the fourth). Hosah''s sons and relatives, who served as gatekeepers, numbered thirteen in all.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 12, 'These divisions of the gatekeepers were named for their family leaders, and like the other Levites, they served at the house of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 13, 'They were assigned by families for guard duty at the various gates, without regard to age or training, for it was all decided by means of sacred lots.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 14, 'The responsibility for the east gate went to Meshelemiah and his group. The north gate was assigned to his son Zechariah, a man of unusual wisdom.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 15, 'The south gate went to Obed-edom, and his sons were put in charge of the storehouses.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 16, 'Shuppim and Hosah were assigned the west gate and the gateway leading up to the Temple. Guard duties were divided evenly.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 17, 'Six Levites were assigned each day to the east gate, four to the north gate, four to the south gate, and two to each of the storehouses.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 18, 'Six were assigned each day to the west gate, four to the gateway leading up to the Temple, and two to the courtyard.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 19, 'These were the divisions of the gatekeepers from the clans of Korah and Merari.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 20, 'Other Levites, led by Ahijah, were in charge of the treasuries of the house of God and the storerooms.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 21, 'From the family of Libni in the clan of Gershon, Jehiel was the leader.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 22, 'The sons of Jehiel, Zetham and his brother Joel, were in charge of the treasuries of the house of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 23, 'These are the leaders that descended from Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel:', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 24, 'From the clan of Amram, Shebuel was a descendant of Gershom son of Moses. He was the chief officer of the treasuries.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 25, 'His relatives through Eliezer were Rehabiah, Jeshaiah, Joram, Zicri, and Shelomoth.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 26, 'Shelomoth and his relatives were in charge of the treasuries that held all the things dedicated to the LORD by King David, the family leaders, and the generals and captains and other officers of the army.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 27, 'These men had dedicated some of the plunder they had gained in battle to maintain the house of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 28, 'Shelomoth and his relatives also cared for the items dedicated to the LORD by Samuel the seer, Saul son of Kish, Abner son of Ner, and Joab son of Zeruiah. All the other dedicated items were in their care, too.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 29, 'From the clan of Izhar came Kenaniah. He and his sons were appointed to serve as public administrators and judges throughout Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 30, 'From the clan of Hebron came Hashabiah. He and his relatives--seventeen hundred capable men--were put in charge of the Israelite lands west of the Jordan River. They were responsible for all matters related to the things of the LORD and the service of the king in that area.', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 31, 'Also from the clan of Hebron came Jeriah, who was the leader of the Hebronites according to the genealogical records. (In the fortieth year of David''s reign, a search was made in the records, and capable men from the clan of Hebron were found at Jazer in the land of Gilead.)', 'NLT'),
(17, 26, 32, 'There were twenty-seven hundred capable men among the relatives of Jeriah. King David sent them to the east side of the Jordan River and put them in charge of the tribes of Reuben and Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh. They were responsible for all matters related to the things of God and the service of the king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 1, 'This is the list of Israelite generals and captains, and their officers, who served the king by supervising the army divisions that were on duty each month of the year. Each division served for one month and had twenty-four thousand troops.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 2, 'Jashobeam son of Zabdiel was commander of the first division, which was on duty during the first month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 3, 'He was a descendant of Perez and was in charge of all the army officers for the first month.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 4, 'Dodai, a descendant of Ahoah, was commander of the second division, which was on duty during the second month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division, and Mikloth was his chief officer.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 5, 'Benaiah son of Jehoiada the priest was commander of the third division, which was on duty during the third month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 6, 'This was the Benaiah who commanded David''s elite military group known as the Thirty. His son Ammizabad was his chief officer.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 7, 'Asahel, the brother of Joab, was commander of the fourth division, which was on duty during the fourth month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division. Asahel was succeeded by his son Zebadiah.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 8, 'Shammah the Izrahite was commander of the fifth division, which was on duty during the fifth month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 9, 'Ira son of Ikkesh from Tekoa was commander of the sixth division, which was on duty during the sixth month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 10, 'Helez, a descendant of Ephraim from Pelon, was commander of the seventh division, which was on duty during the seventh month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 11, 'Sibbecai, a descendant of Zerah from Hushah, was commander of the eighth division, which was on duty during the eighth month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 12, 'Abiezer from Anathoth in the territory of Benjamin was commander of the ninth division, which was on duty during the ninth month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 13, 'Maharai, a descendant of Zerah from Netophah, was commander of the tenth division, which was on duty during the tenth month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 14, 'Benaiah from Pirathon in Ephraim was commander of the eleventh division, which was on duty during the eleventh month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 15, 'Heled, a descendant of Othniel from Netophah, was commander of the twelfth division, which was on duty during the twelfth month. There were twenty-four thousand troops in his division.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 16, 'The following were the tribes of Israel and their leaders: Reuben...............Eliezer son of Zicri Simeon......... Shephatiah son of Maacah', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 17, 'Levi............ Hashabiah son of Kemuel Aaron (the priests)................ Zadok', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 18, 'Judah........... Elihu (a brother of David) Issachar............. Omri son of Michael', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 19, 'Zebulun.......... Ishmaiah son of Obadiah Naphtali........... Jeremoth son of Azriel', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 20, 'Ephraim........... Hoshea son of Azaziah Manasseh (west)....... Joel son of Pedaiah', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 21, 'Manasseh (east ).... Iddo son of Zechariah Benjamin............ Jaasiel son of Abner', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 22, 'Dan............... Azarel son of Jeroham These were the leaders of the tribes of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 23, 'When David took his census, he did not count those who were younger than twenty years of age, because the LORD had promised to make the Israelites as numerous as the stars in heaven.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 24, 'Joab began the census but never finished it because the anger of God broke out against Israel. The final total was never recorded in King David''s official records.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 25, 'Azmaveth son of Adiel was in charge of the palace treasuries. Jonathan son of Uzziah was in charge of the regional treasuries throughout the towns, villages, and fortresses of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 26, 'Ezri son of Kelub was in charge of the field workers who farmed the king''s lands.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 27, 'Shimei from Ramah was in charge of the king''s vineyards. Zabdi from Shepham was responsible for the grapes and the supplies of wine.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 28, 'Baal-hanan from Geder was in charge of the king''s olive groves and sycamore-fig trees in the foothills of Judah. Joash was responsible for the supplies of olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 29, 'Shitrai from Sharon was in charge of the cattle on the Sharon Plain. Shaphat son of Adlai was responsible for the cattle in the valleys.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 30, 'Obil the Ishmaelite was in charge of the camels. Jehdeiah from Meronoth was in charge of the donkeys.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 31, 'Jaziz the Hagrite was in charge of the king''s sheep. All these officials were overseers of King David''s property.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 32, 'Jonathan, David''s uncle, was a wise counselor to the king, a man of great insight, and a scribe. Jehiel the Hacmonite was responsible to teach the king''s sons.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 33, 'Ahithophel was the royal adviser. Hushai the Arkite was the king''s friend.', 'NLT'),
(17, 27, 34, 'Ahithophel was succeeded by Jehoiada son of Benaiah and by Abiathar. Joab was commander of the Israelite army.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 1, 'David summoned all his officials to Jerusalem--the leaders of the tribes, the commanders of the twelve army divisions, the other generals and captains, the overseers of the royal property and livestock, the palace officials, the mighty men, and all the other warriors in the kingdom.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 2, 'David rose and stood before them and addressed them as follows: "My brothers and my people! It was my desire to build a temple where the Ark of the LORD''s covenant, God''s footstool, could rest permanently. I made the necessary preparations for building it,', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 3, 'but God said to me, `You must not build a temple to honor my name, for you are a warrior and have shed much blood.''', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 4, '"Yet the LORD, the God of Israel, has chosen me from among all my father''s family to be king over Israel forever. For he has chosen the tribe of Judah to rule, and from among the families of Judah, he chose my father''s family. And from among my father''s sons, the LORD was pleased to make me king over all Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 5, 'And from among my sons--for the LORD has given me many children--he chose Solomon to succeed me on the throne of his kingdom of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 6, 'He said to me, `Your son Solomon will build my Temple and its courtyards, for I have chosen him as my son, and I will be his father.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 7, 'And if he continues to obey my commands and regulations as he does now, I will make his kingdom last forever.''', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 8, 'So now, with God as our witness, I give you this charge for all Israel, the LORD''s assembly: Be careful to obey all the commands of the LORD your God, so that you may possess this good land and leave it to your children as a permanent inheritance.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 9, '"And Solomon, my son, get to know the God of your ancestors. Worship and serve him with your whole heart and with a willing mind. For the LORD sees every heart and understands and knows every plan and thought. If you seek him, you will find him. But if you forsake him, he will reject you forever.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 10, 'So take this seriously. The LORD has chosen you to build a Temple as his sanctuary. Be strong, and do the work."', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 11, 'Then David gave Solomon the plans for the Temple and its surroundings, including the treasuries, the upstairs rooms, the inner rooms, and the inner sanctuary where the Ark''s cover--the place of atonement--would be kept.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 12, 'David also gave Solomon all the plans he had in mind for the courtyards of the LORD''s Temple, the outside rooms, the treasuries of God''s Temple, and the rooms for the dedicated gifts.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 13, 'The king also gave Solomon the instructions concerning the work of the various divisions of priests and Levites in the Temple of the LORD. And he gave specifications for the items in the LORD''s Temple which were to be used for worship and sacrifice.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 14, 'David gave instructions regarding how much gold and silver should be used to make the necessary items.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 15, 'He told Solomon the amount of gold needed for the gold lampstands and lamps, and the amount of silver for the silver lampstands and lamps, depending on how each would be used.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 16, 'He designated the amount of gold for the table on which the Bread of the Presence would be placed and the amount of silver for other tables.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 17, 'David also designated the amount of gold for the solid gold meat hooks used to handle the sacrificial meat and for the basins, pitchers, and dishes, as well as the amount of silver for every dish.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 18, 'Finally, he designated the amount of refined gold for the altar of incense and for the gold cherubim, whose wings were stretched out over the Ark of the LORD''s covenant.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 19, '"Every part of this plan," David told Solomon, "was given to me in writing from the hand of the LORD. "', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 20, 'Then David continued, "Be strong and courageous, and do the work. Don''t be afraid or discouraged by the size of the task, for the LORD God, my God, is with you. He will not fail you or forsake you. He will see to it that all the work related to the Temple of the LORD is finished correctly.', 'NLT'),
(17, 28, 21, 'The various divisions of priests and Levites will serve in the Temple of God. Others with skills of every kind will volunteer, and the leaders and the entire nation are at your command."', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 1, 'Then King David turned to the entire assembly and said, "My son Solomon, whom God has chosen to be the next king of Israel, is still young and inexperienced. The work ahead of him is enormous, for the Temple he will build is not just another building--it is for the LORD God himself!', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 2, 'Using every resource at my command, I have gathered as much as I could for building the Temple of my God. Now there is enough gold, silver, bronze, iron, and wood, as well as great quantities of onyx, other precious stones, costly jewels, and all kinds of fine stone and marble.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 3, 'And now because of my devotion to the Temple of my God, I am giving all of my own private treasures of gold and silver to help in the construction. This is in addition to the building materials I have already collected for his holy Temple.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 4, 'I am donating more than 112 tons of gold from Ophir and over 262 tons of refined silver to be used for overlaying the walls of the buildings', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 5, 'and for the other gold and silver work to be done by the craftsmen. Now then, who will follow my example? Who is willing to give offerings to the LORD today?"', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 6, 'Then the family leaders, the leaders of the tribes of Israel, the generals and captains of the army, and the king''s administrative officers all gave willingly.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 7, 'For the construction of the Temple of God, they gave almost 188 tons of gold, 10,000 gold coins, about 375 tons of silver, about 675 tons of bronze, and about 3,750 tons of iron.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 8, 'They also contributed numerous precious stones, which were deposited in the treasury of the house of the LORD under the care of Jehiel, a descendant of Gershon.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 9, 'The people rejoiced over the offerings, for they had given freely and wholeheartedly to the LORD, and King David was filled with joy.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 10, 'Then David praised the LORD in the presence of the whole assembly: "O LORD, the God of our ancestor Israel, may you be praised forever and ever!', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 11, 'Yours, O LORD, is the greatness, the power, the glory, the victory, and the majesty. Everything in the heavens and on earth is yours, O LORD, and this is your kingdom. We adore you as the one who is over all things.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 12, 'Riches and honor come from you alone, for you rule over everything. Power and might are in your hand, and it is at your discretion that people are made great and given strength.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 13, '"O our God, we thank you and praise your glorious name!', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 14, 'But who am I, and who are my people, that we could give anything to you? Everything we have has come from you, and we give you only what you have already given us!', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 15, 'We are here for only a moment, visitors and strangers in the land as our ancestors were before us. Our days on earth are like a shadow, gone so soon without a trace.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 16, '"O LORD our God, even these materials that we have gathered to build a Temple to honor your holy name come from you! It all belongs to you!', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 17, 'I know, my God, that you examine our hearts and rejoice when you find integrity there. You know I have done all this with good motives, and I have watched your people offer their gifts willingly and joyously.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 18, '"O LORD, the God of our ancestors Abraham, Isaac, and Israel, make your people always want to obey you. See to it that their love for you never changes.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 19, 'Give my son Solomon the wholehearted desire to obey all your commands, decrees, and principles, and to build this Temple, for which I have made all these preparations."', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 20, 'Then David said to the whole assembly, "Give praise to the LORD your God!" And the entire assembly praised the LORD, the God of their ancestors, and they bowed low and knelt before the LORD and the king.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 21, 'The next day they brought a thousand bulls, a thousand rams, and a thousand male lambs as burnt offerings to the LORD. They also brought drink offerings and many other sacrifices on behalf of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 22, 'They feasted and drank in the LORD''s presence with great joy that day. And again they crowned David''s son Solomon as their new king. They anointed him before the LORD as their leader, and they anointed Zadok as their priest.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 23, 'So Solomon took the throne of the LORD in place of his father, David, and he prospered greatly, and all Israel obeyed him.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 24, 'All the royal officials, the army commanders, and the sons of King David pledged their loyalty to King Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 25, 'And the LORD exalted Solomon so the entire nation of Israel stood in awe of him, and he gave Solomon even greater wealth and honor than his father.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 26, 'So David son of Jesse reigned over all Israel.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 27, 'He ruled Israel for forty years in all, seven years from Hebron and thirty-three years from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 28, 'He died at a ripe old age, having enjoyed long life, wealth, and honor. Then his son Solomon ruled in his place.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 29, 'All the events of King David''s reign, from beginning to end, are written in The Record of Samuel the Seer, The Record of Nathan the Prophet, and The Record of Gad the Seer.', 'NLT'),
(17, 29, 30, 'These accounts include the mighty deeds of his reign and everything that happened to him and to Israel and to all the surrounding kingdoms.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 1, 'Solomon, the son of King David, now took firm control of the kingdom, for the LORD his God was with him and made him very powerful.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 2, 'He called together all Israel--the generals and captains of the army, the judges, and all the political and clan leaders.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 3, 'Then Solomon led the entire assembly to the hill at Gibeon where God''s Tabernacle was located. This was the Tabernacle that Moses, the LORD''s servant, had constructed in the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 4, 'David had already moved the Ark of God from Kiriath-jearim to the special tent he had prepared for it in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 5, 'But the bronze altar made by Bezalel son of Uri and grandson of Hur was still at Gibeon in front of the Tabernacle of the LORD. So Solomon and the people gathered in front of it to consult the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 6, 'There in front of the Tabernacle, Solomon went up to the bronze altar in the LORD''s presence and sacrificed a thousand burnt offerings on it.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 7, 'That night God appeared to Solomon in a dream and said, "What do you want? Ask, and I will give it to you!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 8, 'Solomon replied to God, "You have been so faithful and kind to my father, David, and now you have made me king in his place.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 9, 'Now, LORD God, please keep your promise to David my father, for you have made me king over a people as numerous as the dust of the earth!', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 10, 'Give me wisdom and knowledge to rule them properly, for who is able to govern this great nation of yours?"', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 11, 'God said to Solomon, "Because your greatest desire is to help your people, and you did not ask for personal wealth and honor or the death of your enemies or even a long life, but rather you asked for wisdom and knowledge to properly govern my people,', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 12, 'I will certainly give you the wisdom and knowledge you requested. And I will also give you riches, wealth, and honor such as no other king has ever had before you or will ever have again!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 13, 'Then Solomon returned to Jerusalem from the Tabernacle at the hill of Gibeon, and he reigned over Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 14, 'Solomon built up a huge military force, which included fourteen hundred chariots and twelve thousand horses. He stationed many of them in the chariot cities, and some near him in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 15, 'During Solomon''s reign, silver and gold were as plentiful in Jerusalem as stones. And valuable cedarwood was as common as the sycamore wood that grows in the foothills of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 16, 'Solomon''s horses were imported from Egypt and from Cilicia; the king''s traders acquired them from Cilicia at the standard price.', 'NLT'),
(18, 1, 17, 'At that time, Egyptian chariots delivered to Jerusalem could be purchased for 600 pieces of silver, and horses could be bought for 150 pieces of silver. Many of these were then resold to the kings of the Hittites and the kings of Aram.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 1, 'Solomon now decided that the time had come to build a Temple for the LORD and a royal palace for himself.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 2, 'He enlisted a force of 70,000 common laborers, 80,000 stonecutters in the hill country, and 3,600 foremen.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 3, 'Solomon also sent this message to King Hiram at Tyre: "Send me cedar logs like the ones that were supplied to my father, David, when he was building his palace.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 4, 'I am about to build a Temple to honor the name of the LORD my God. It will be a place set apart to burn incense and sweet spices before him, to display the special sacrificial bread, and to sacrifice burnt offerings each morning and evening, on the Sabbaths, at new moon celebrations, and at the other appointed festivals of the LORD our God. He has commanded Israel to do these things forever.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 5, '"This will be a magnificent Temple because our God is an awesome God, greater than any other.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 6, 'But who can really build him a worthy home? Not even the highest heavens can contain him! So who am I to consider building a Temple for him, except as a place to burn sacrifices to him?', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 7, '"So send me a master craftsman who can work with gold, silver, bronze, and iron; someone who is expert at dyeing purple, scarlet, and blue cloth; and a skilled engraver who can work with the craftsmen of Judah and Jerusalem who were selected by my father, David.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 8, 'Also send me cedar, cypress, and almug logs from Lebanon, for I know that your men are without equal at cutting timber. I will send my men to help them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 9, 'An immense amount of timber will be needed, for the Temple I am going to build will be very large and magnificent.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 10, 'I will pay your men 100,000 bushels of crushed wheat, 100,000 bushels of barley, 110,000 gallons of wine, and 110,000 gallons of olive oil. "', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 11, 'King Hiram sent this letter of reply to Solomon: "It is because the LORD loves his people that he has made you their king!', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 12, 'Blessed be the LORD, the God of Israel, who made the heavens and the earth! He has given David a wise son, gifted with skill and understanding, who will build a Temple for the LORD and a royal palace for himself.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 13, '"I am sending you a master craftsman named Huram-abi. He is a brilliant man,', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 14, 'the son of a woman from Dan in Israel; his father is from Tyre. He is skillful at making things from gold, silver, bronze, and iron. He also knows all about stonework, carpentry, and weaving. He is an expert in dyeing purple, blue, and scarlet cloth and in working with linen. He is also an engraver and can follow any design given to him. He will work with your craftsmen and those appointed by my lord David, your father.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 15, '"Send along the wheat, barley, olive oil, and wine that you mentioned.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 16, 'We will cut whatever timber you need from the Lebanon mountains and will float the logs in rafts down the coast of the Mediterranean Sea to Joppa. From there you can transport the logs up to Jerusalem."', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 17, 'Solomon took a census of all foreigners in the land of Israel, like the census his father had taken, and he counted 153,600.', 'NLT'),
(18, 2, 18, 'He enlisted 70,000 of them as common laborers, 80,000 as stonecutters in the hill country, and 3,600 as foremen.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 1, 'So Solomon began to build the Temple of the LORD in Jerusalem on Mount Moriah, where the LORD had appeared to Solomon''s father, King David. The Temple was built on the threshing floor of Araunah the Jebusite, the site that David had selected.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 2, 'The construction began in midspring, during the fourth year of Solomon''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 3, 'The foundation for the Temple of God was ninety feet long and thirty feet wide.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 4, 'The foyer at the front of the Temple was thirty feet wide, running across the entire width of the Temple. The inner walls of the foyer and the ceiling were overlaid with pure gold. The roof of the foyer was thirty feet high.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 5, 'The main room of the Temple was paneled with cypress wood, overlaid with pure gold, and decorated with carvings of palm trees and chains.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 6, 'The walls of the Temple were decorated with beautiful jewels and with pure gold from the land of Parvaim.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 7, 'All the walls, beams, doors, and thresholds throughout the Temple were overlaid with gold, and figures of cherubim were carved on the walls.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 8, 'The Most Holy Place was thirty feet wide, corresponding to the width of the Temple, and it was also thirty feet deep. Its interior was overlaid with about twenty-three tons of pure gold.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 9, 'They used gold nails that weighed about twenty ounces each. The walls of the upper rooms were also overlaid with pure gold.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 10, 'Solomon made two figures shaped like cherubim and overlaid them with gold. These were placed in the Most Holy Place.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 11, 'The total wingspan of the two cherubim standing side by side was 30 feet. One wing of the first figure was 7 1/2 feet long, and it touched the Temple wall. The other wing, also 7 1/2 feet long, touched one of the wings of the second figure.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 12, 'In the same way, the second figure had one wing 7 1/2 feet long that touched the opposite wall. The other wing, also 7 1/2 feet long, touched the wing of the first figure.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 13, 'So the wingspan of both cherubim together was 30 feet. They both stood and faced out toward the main room of the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 14, 'Across the entrance of the Most Holy Place, Solomon hung a curtain made of fine linen and blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, with figures of cherubim embroidered on it.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 15, 'For the front of the Temple, Solomon made two pillars that were 27 feet tall, each topped by a capital extending upward another 7 1/2 feet.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 16, 'He made a network of interwoven chains and used them to decorate the tops of the pillars. He also made one hundred decorative pomegranates and attached them to the chains.', 'NLT'),
(18, 3, 17, 'Then he set up the two pillars at the entrance of the Temple, one to the south of the entrance and the other to the north. He named the one on the south Jakin, and the one on the north Boaz.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 1, 'Solomon also made a bronze altar 30 feet long, 30 feet wide, and 15 feet high.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 2, 'Then he cast a large round tank, 15 feet across from rim to rim; it was called the Sea. It was 7 1/2 feet deep and about 45 feet in circumference.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 3, 'The Sea was encircled just below its rim by two rows of figures that resembled oxen. There were about six oxen per foot all the way around, and they had been cast as part of the tank.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 4, 'The Sea rested on a base of twelve bronze oxen, all facing outward. Three faced north, three faced west, three faced south, and three faced east.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 5, 'The walls of the Sea were about three inches thick, and its rim flared out like a cup and resembled a lily blossom. It could hold about 16,500 gallons of water.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 6, 'He also made ten basins for water to wash the offerings, five to the south of the Sea and five to the north. The priests used the Sea itself, and not the basins, for their own washing.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 7, 'Solomon then cast ten gold lampstands according to the specifications that had been given and put them in the Temple. Five were placed against the south wall, and five were placed against the north wall.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 8, 'He also built ten tables and placed them in the Temple, five along the south wall and five along the north wall. Then he molded one hundred gold basins.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 9, 'Solomon also built a courtyard for the priests and the large outer courtyard. He made doors for the courtyard entrances and overlaid them with bronze.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 10, 'The Sea was placed near the southeast corner of the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 11, 'Huram-abi also made the necessary pots, shovels, and basins. So at last Huram-abi completed everything King Solomon had assigned him to make for the Temple of God:', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 12, 'two pillars, two bowl-shaped capitals on top of the pillars, two networks of chains that decorated the capitals,', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 13, 'four hundred pomegranates that hung from the chains on the capitals (two rows of pomegranates for each of the chain networks that were hung around the capitals on top of the pillars),', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 14, 'the water carts holding the basins,', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 15, 'the Sea and the twelve oxen under it,', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 16, 'the pots, the shovels, the meat hooks, and all the related utensils. Huram-abi made all these things out of burnished bronze for the Temple of the LORD, just as King Solomon had requested.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 17, 'The king had them cast in clay molds in the Jordan Valley between Succoth and Zarethan.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 18, 'Such great quantities of bronze were used that its weight could not be determined.', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 19, 'So Solomon made all the furnishings for the Temple of God: the gold altar; the tables for the Bread of the Presence;', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 20, 'the lampstands and their lamps of pure gold to burn in front of the Most Holy Place as prescribed;', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 21, 'the flower decorations, lamps, and tongs, all of pure gold;', 'NLT'),
(18, 4, 22, 'the lamp snuffers, basins, dishes, and firepans, all of pure gold; the doors for the entrances to the Most Holy Place and the main room of the Temple, overlaid with gold.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 1, 'When Solomon had finished all the work related to building the Temple of the LORD, he brought in the gifts dedicated by his father, King David, including all the silver and gold and all the utensils. These were stored in the treasuries of the Temple of God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 2, 'Solomon then summoned the leaders of all the tribes and families of Israel to assemble in Jerusalem. They were to bring the Ark of the LORD''s covenant from its location in the City of David, also known as Zion, to its new place in the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 3, 'They all assembled before the king at the annual Festival of Shelters in early autumn.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 4, 'When all the leaders of Israel arrived, the Levites moved the Ark,', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 5, 'along with the special tent and all its sacred utensils. The Levitical priests carried them all up to the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 6, 'King Solomon and the entire community of Israel sacrificed sheep and oxen before the Ark in such numbers that no one could keep count!', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 7, 'Then the priests carried the Ark of the LORD''s covenant into the inner sanctuary of the Temple--the Most Holy Place--and placed it beneath the wings of the cherubim.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 8, 'The cherubim spread their wings out over the Ark, forming a canopy over the Ark and its carrying poles.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 9, 'These poles were so long that their ends could be seen from the front entrance of the Temple''s main room--the Holy Place--but not from outside it. They are still there to this day.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 10, 'Nothing was in the Ark except the two stone tablets that Moses had placed there at Mount Sinai, when the LORD made a covenant with the people of Israel after they left Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 11, 'Then the priests left the Holy Place. All the priests who were present had purified themselves, whether or not they were on duty that day.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 12, 'And the Levites who were musicians--Asaph, Heman, Jeduthun, and all their sons and brothers--were dressed in fine linen robes and stood at the east side of the altar playing cymbals, harps, and lyres. They were joined by 120 priests who were playing trumpets.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 13, 'The trumpeters and singers performed together in unison to praise and give thanks to the LORD. Accompanied by trumpets, cymbals, and other instruments, they raised their voices and praised the LORD with these words: "He is so good! His faithful love endures forever!" At that moment a cloud filled the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 5, 14, 'The priests could not continue their work because the glorious presence of the LORD filled the Temple of God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 1, 'Then Solomon prayed, "O LORD, you have said that you would live in thick darkness.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 2, 'But I have built a glorious Temple for you, where you can live forever!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 3, 'Then the king turned around to the entire community of Israel standing before him and gave this blessing:', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 4, '"Blessed be the LORD, the God of Israel, who has kept the promise he made to my father, David. For he told my father,', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 5, '`From the day I brought my people out of Egypt, I have never chosen a city among the tribes of Israel as the place where a temple should be built to honor my name. Nor have I chosen a king to lead my people Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 6, 'But now I have chosen Jerusalem as that city, and David as that king.''"', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 7, 'Then Solomon said, "My father, David, wanted to build this Temple to honor the name of the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 8, 'But the LORD told him, `It is right for you to want to build the Temple to honor my name,', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 9, 'but you will not be the one to do it. One of your sons will build it instead.''', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 10, '"And now the LORD has done what he promised, for I have become king in my father''s place. I have built this Temple to honor the name of the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 11, 'There I have placed the Ark, and in the Ark is the covenant that the LORD made with the people of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 12, 'Then Solomon stood with his hands spread out before the altar of the LORD in front of the entire community of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 13, 'He had made a bronze platform 7 1/2 feet long, 7 1/2 feet wide, and 4 1/2 feet high and had placed it at the center of the Temple''s outer courtyard. He stood on the platform before the entire assembly, and then he knelt down and lifted his hands toward heaven.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 14, 'He prayed, "O LORD, God of Israel, there is no God like you in all of heaven and earth. You keep your promises and show unfailing love to all who obey you and are eager to do your will.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 15, 'You have kept your promise to your servant David, my father. You made that promise with your own mouth, and today you have fulfilled it with your own hands.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 16, 'And now, O LORD, God of Israel, carry out your further promise to your servant David, my father. For you said to him, `If your descendants guard their behavior and obey my law as you have done, they will always reign over Israel.''', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 17, 'Now, O LORD, God of Israel, fulfill this promise to your servant David.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 18, '"But will God really live on earth among people? Why, even the highest heavens cannot contain you. How much less this Temple I have built!', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 19, 'Listen to my prayer and my request, O LORD my God. Hear the cry and the prayer that your servant is making to you.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 20, 'May you watch over this Temple both day and night, this place where you have said you would put your name. May you always hear the prayers I make toward this place.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 21, 'May you hear the humble and earnest requests from me and your people Israel when we pray toward this place. Yes, hear us from heaven where you live, and when you hear, forgive.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 22, '"If someone wrongs another person and is required to take an oath of innocence in front of the altar at this Temple,', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 23, 'then hear from heaven and judge between your servants--the accuser and the accused. Punish the guilty party, and acquit the one who is innocent.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 24, '"If your people Israel are defeated by their enemies because they have sinned against you, and if they turn to you and call on your name and pray to you here in this Temple,', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 25, 'then hear from heaven and forgive their sins and return them to this land you gave their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 26, '"If the skies are shut up and there is no rain because your people have sinned against you, and then they pray toward this Temple and confess your name and turn from their sins because you have punished them,', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 27, 'then hear from heaven and forgive the sins of your servants, your people Israel. Teach them to do what is right, and send rain on your land that you have given to your people as their special possession.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 28, '"If there is a famine in the land, or plagues, or crop disease, or attacks of locusts or caterpillars, or if your people''s enemies are in the land besieging their towns--whatever the trouble is--', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 29, 'and if your people offer a prayer concerning their troubles or sorrow, raising their hands toward this Temple,', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 30, 'then hear from heaven where you live, and forgive. Give your people whatever they deserve, for you alone know the human heart.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 31, 'Then they will fear you and walk in your ways as long as they live in the land you gave to our ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 32, '"And when foreigners hear of you and your mighty miracles, and they come from distant lands to worship your great name and to pray toward this Temple,', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 33, 'then hear from heaven where you live, and grant what they ask of you. Then all the people of the earth will come to know and fear you, just as your own people Israel do. They, too, will know that this Temple I have built bears your name.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 34, '"If your people go out at your command to fight their enemies, and if they pray to you toward this city that you have chosen and toward this Temple that I have built for your name,', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 35, 'then hear their prayers from heaven and uphold their cause.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 36, '"If they sin against you--and who has never sinned?--you may become angry with them and let their enemies conquer them and take them captive to a foreign land far or near.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 37, 'But in that land of exile, they may turn to you again in repentance and pray, `We have sinned, done evil, and acted wickedly.''', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 38, 'Then if they turn to you with their whole heart and soul and pray toward the land you gave to their ancestors, toward this city you have chosen, and toward this Temple I have built to honor your name,', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 39, 'then hear their prayers from heaven where you live. Uphold their cause and forgive your people who have sinned against you.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 40, '"O my God, be attentive to all the prayers made to you in this place.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 41, 'And now, O LORD God, arise and enter this resting place of yours, where your magnificent Ark has been placed. May your priests, O LORD God, be clothed with salvation, and may your saints rejoice in your goodness.', 'NLT'),
(18, 6, 42, 'O LORD God, do not reject your anointed one. Remember your unfailing love for your servant David. "', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 1, 'When Solomon finished praying, fire flashed down from heaven and burned up the burnt offerings and sacrifices, and the glorious presence of the LORD filled the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 2, 'The priests could not even enter the Temple of the LORD because the glorious presence of the LORD filled it.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 3, 'When all the people of Israel saw the fire coming down and the glorious presence of the LORD filling the Temple, they fell face down on the ground and worshiped and praised the LORD, saying, "He is so good! His faithful love endures forever!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 4, 'Then the king and all the people offered sacrifices to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 5, 'King Solomon offered a sacrifice of 22,000 oxen and 120,000 sheep. And so the king and all the people dedicated the Temple of God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 6, 'The priests took their assigned positions, and so did the Levites who were singing, "His faithful love endures forever!" They accompanied the singing with music from the instruments King David had made for praising the LORD. On the other side of the Levites, the priests blew the trumpets, while all Israel stood.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 7, 'Solomon then dedicated the central area of the courtyard in front of the LORD''s Temple so they could present burnt offerings and the fat from peace offerings there. He did this because the bronze altar he had built could not handle all the burnt offerings, grain offerings, and sacrificial fat.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 8, 'For the next seven days they celebrated the Festival of Shelters with huge crowds gathered from all the tribes of Israel. They came from as far away as Lebo-hamath in the north, to the brook of Egypt in the south.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 9, 'On the eighth day they had a closing ceremony, for they had celebrated the dedication of the altar for seven days and the Festival of Shelters for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 10, 'Then at the end of the celebration, Solomon sent the people home. They were all joyful and happy because the LORD had been so good to David and Solomon and to his people Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 11, 'So Solomon finished building the Temple of the LORD, as well as the royal palace. He completed everything he had planned to do.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 12, 'Then one night the LORD appeared to Solomon and said, "I have heard your prayer and have chosen this Temple as the place for making sacrifices.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 13, 'At times I might shut up the heavens so that no rain falls, or I might command locusts to devour your crops, or I might send plagues among you.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 14, 'Then if my people who are called by my name will humble themselves and pray and seek my face and turn from their wicked ways, I will hear from heaven and will forgive their sins and heal their land.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 15, 'I will listen to every prayer made in this place,', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 16, 'for I have chosen this Temple and set it apart to be my home forever. My eyes and my heart will always be here.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 17, '"As for you, if you follow me as your father, David, did and obey all my commands, laws, and regulations,', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 18, 'then I will not let anyone take away your throne. This is the same promise I gave your father, David, when I said, `You will never fail to have a successor who rules over Israel.''', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 19, '"But if you abandon me and disobey the laws and commands I have given you, and if you go and worship other gods,', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 20, 'then I will uproot the people of Israel from this land of mine that I have given them. I will reject this Temple that I have set apart to honor my name. I will make it a spectacle of contempt among the nations.', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 21, 'And though this Temple is impressive now, it will become an appalling sight to all who pass by. They will ask, `Why has the LORD done such terrible things to his land and to his Temple?''', 'NLT'),
(18, 7, 22, 'And the answer will be, `Because his people abandoned the LORD, the God of their ancestors, who brought them out of Egypt, and they worshiped other gods instead. That is why he brought all these disasters upon them.''"', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 1, 'It was now twenty years since Solomon had become king, and the great building projects of the LORD''s Temple and his own royal palace were completed.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 2, 'Solomon now turned his attention to rebuilding the towns that King Hiram had given him, and he settled Israelites in them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 3, 'It was at this time, too, that Solomon fought against the city of Hamath-zobah and conquered it.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 4, 'He rebuilt Tadmor in the desert and built towns in the region of Hamath as supply centers.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 5, 'He fortified the cities of Upper Beth-horon and Lower Beth-horon, rebuilding their walls and installing barred gates.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 6, 'He also rebuilt Baalath and other supply centers at this time and constructed cities where his chariots and horses could be kept. He built to his heart''s content in Jerusalem and Lebanon and throughout the entire realm.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 7, 'There were still some people living in the land who were not Israelites, including Hittites, Amorites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 8, 'These were descendants of the nations that Israel had not completely destroyed. So Solomon conscripted them for his labor force, and they serve in the labor force to this day.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 9, 'But Solomon did not conscript any of the Israelites for forced labor. Instead, he assigned them to serve as fighting men, officers in his army, commanders of his chariots, and charioteers.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 10, 'King Solomon also appointed 250 of them to supervise the various projects.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 11, 'Solomon moved his wife, Pharaoh''s daughter, from the City of David to the new palace he had built for her. He said, "My wife must not live in King David''s palace, for the Ark of the LORD has been there, and it is holy ground."', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 12, 'Then Solomon sacrificed burnt offerings to the LORD on the altar he had built in front of the foyer of the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 13, 'The number of sacrifices varied from day to day according to the commands Moses had given. Extra sacrifices were offered on the Sabbaths, on new moon festivals, and at the three annual festivals--the Passover celebration, the Festival of Harvest, and the Festival of Shelters.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 14, 'In assigning the priests to their duties, Solomon followed the regulations of his father, David. He also assigned the Levites to lead the people in praise and to assist the priests in their daily duties. And he assigned the gatekeepers to their gates by their divisions, following the commands of David, the man of God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 15, 'Solomon did not deviate in any way from David''s commands concerning the priests and Levites and the treasuries.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 16, 'So Solomon made sure that all the work related to building the Temple of the LORD was carried out, from the day its foundation was laid to the day of its completion.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 17, 'Later Solomon went to Ezion-geber and Elath, ports in the land of Edom, along the shore of the Red Sea.', 'NLT'),
(18, 8, 18, 'Hiram sent him ships commanded by his own officers and manned by experienced crews of sailors. These ships sailed to the land of Ophir with Solomon''s men and brought back to Solomon almost seventeen tons of gold.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 1, 'When the queen of Sheba heard of Solomon''s reputation, she came to Jerusalem to test him with hard questions. She arrived with a large group of attendants and a great caravan of camels loaded with spices, huge quantities of gold, and precious jewels.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 2, 'When she met with Solomon, they talked about everything she had on her mind. Solomon answered all her questions; nothing was too hard for him to explain to her.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 3, 'When the queen of Sheba realized how wise Solomon was, and when she saw the palace he had built,', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 4, 'she was breathless. She was also amazed at the food on his tables, the organization of his officials and their splendid clothing, the cup-bearers and their robes, and the burnt offerings Solomon made at the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 5, 'She exclaimed to the king, "Everything I heard in my country about your achievements and wisdom is true!', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 6, 'I didn''t believe it until I arrived here and saw it with my own eyes. Truly I had not heard the half of it! Your wisdom is far greater than what I was told.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 7, 'How happy these people must be! What a privilege for your officials to stand here day after day, listening to your wisdom!', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 8, 'The LORD your God is great indeed! He delights in you and has placed you on the throne to rule for him. Because God loves Israel so much and desires this kingdom to last forever, he has made you king so you can rule with justice and righteousness."', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 9, 'Then she gave the king a gift of nine thousand pounds of gold, and great quantities of spices and precious jewels. Never before had there been spices as fine as those the queen of Sheba gave to Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 10, '(When the crews of Hiram and Solomon brought gold from Ophir, they also brought rich cargoes of almug wood and precious jewels.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 11, 'The king used the almug wood to make steps for the Temple of the LORD and the royal palace, and to construct harps and lyres for the musicians. Never before had there been such beautiful instruments in Judah.)', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 12, 'King Solomon gave the queen of Sheba whatever she asked for--gifts of greater value than the gifts she had given him. Then she and all her attendants left and returned to their own land.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 13, 'Each year Solomon received about 25 tons of gold.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 14, 'This did not include the additional revenue he received from merchants and traders. All the kings of Arabia and the governors of the land also brought gold and silver to Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 15, 'King Solomon made two hundred large shields of hammered gold, each containing over 15 pounds of gold.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 16, 'He also made three hundred smaller shields of hammered gold, each containing about 7 1/2 pounds of gold. The king placed these shields in the Palace of the Forest of Lebanon.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 17, 'Then the king made a huge ivory throne and overlaid it with pure gold.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 18, 'The throne had six steps, and there was a footstool of gold attached to it. On both sides of the seat were armrests, with the figure of a lion standing on each side of the throne.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 19, 'Solomon made twelve other lion figures, one standing on each end of each of the six steps. No other throne in all the world could be compared with it!', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 20, 'All of King Solomon''s drinking cups were solid gold, as were all the utensils in the Palace of the Forest of Lebanon. They were not made of silver because silver was considered of little value in Solomon''s day!', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 21, 'The king had a fleet of trading ships manned by the sailors sent by Hiram. Once every three years the ships returned, loaded down with gold, silver, ivory, apes, and peacocks.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 22, 'So King Solomon became richer and wiser than any other king in all the earth.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 23, 'Kings from every nation came to visit him and to hear the wisdom God had given him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 24, 'Year after year, everyone who came to visit brought him gifts of silver and gold, clothing, weapons, spices, horses, and mules.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 25, 'Solomon had four thousand stalls for his chariot horses and twelve thousand horses. He stationed many of them in the chariot cities, and some near him in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 26, 'He ruled over all the kings from the Euphrates River to the land of the Philistines and the border of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 27, 'The king made silver as plentiful in Jerusalem as stones. And valuable cedarwood was as common as the sycamore wood that grows in the foothills of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 28, 'Solomon''s horses were imported from Egypt and many other countries.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 29, 'The rest of the events of Solomon''s reign, from beginning to end, are recorded in The Record of Nathan the Prophet and in The Prophecy of Ahijah from Shiloh, and also in The Visions of Iddo the Seer, concerning Jeroboam son of Nebat.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 30, 'Solomon ruled in Jerusalem over all Israel for forty years.', 'NLT'),
(18, 9, 31, 'When he died, he was buried in the city of his father, David. Then his son Rehoboam became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 1, 'Rehoboam went to Shechem, where all Israel had gathered to make him king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 2, 'When Jeroboam son of Nebat heard of Solomon''s death, he returned from Egypt, for he had fled to Egypt to escape from King Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 3, 'The leaders of Israel sent for Jeroboam, and he and all Israel went together to speak with Rehoboam.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 4, '"Your father was a hard master," they said. "Lighten the harsh labor demands and heavy taxes that your father imposed on us. Then we will be your loyal subjects."', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 5, 'Rehoboam replied, "Come back in three days for my answer." So the people went away.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 6, 'Then King Rehoboam went to discuss the matter with the older men who had counseled his father, Solomon. "What is your advice?" he asked. "How should I answer these people?"', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 7, 'The older counselors replied, "If you are good to the people and show them kindness and do your best to please them, they will always be your loyal subjects."', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 8, 'But Rehoboam rejected the advice of the elders and instead asked the opinion of the young men who had grown up with him and who were now his advisers.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 9, '"What is your advice?" he asked them. "How should I answer these people who want me to lighten the burdens imposed by my father?"', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 10, 'The young men replied, "This is what you should tell those complainers: `My little finger is thicker than my father''s waist--if you think he was hard on you, just wait and see what I''ll be like!', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 11, 'Yes, my father was harsh on you, but I''ll be even harsher! My father used whips on you, but I''ll use scorpions!''"', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 12, 'Three days later, Jeroboam and all the people returned to hear Rehoboam''s decision, just as the king had requested.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 13, 'But Rehoboam spoke harshly to them, for he rejected the advice of the older counselors', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 14, 'and followed the counsel of his younger advisers. He told the people, "My father was harsh on you, but I''ll be even harsher! My father used whips on you, but I''ll use scorpions!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 15, 'So the king paid no attention to the people''s demands. This turn of events was the will of God, for it fulfilled the prophecy of the LORD spoken to Jeroboam son of Nebat by the prophet Ahijah from Shiloh.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 16, 'When all Israel realized that the king had rejected their request, they shouted, "Down with David and his dynasty! We have no share in Jesse''s son! Let''s go home, Israel! Look out for your own house, O David!" So all Israel returned home.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 17, 'But Rehoboam continued to rule over the Israelites who lived in the towns of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 18, 'King Rehoboam sent Adoniram, who was in charge of the labor force, to restore order, but the Israelites stoned him to death. When this news reached King Rehoboam, he quickly jumped into his chariot and fled to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 10, 19, 'The northern tribes of Israel have refused to be ruled by a descendant of David to this day.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 1, 'When Rehoboam arrived at Jerusalem, he mobilized the armies of Judah and Benjamin--180,000 select troops--to fight against the army of Israel and to restore the kingdom to himself.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 2, 'But the LORD said to Shemaiah, the man of God,', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 3, '"Say to Rehoboam son of Solomon, king of Judah, and to all the Israelites in Judah and Benjamin:', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 4, '`This is what the LORD says: Do not fight against your relatives. Go back home, for what has happened is my doing!''" So they obeyed the message of the LORD and did not fight against Jeroboam.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 5, 'Rehoboam remained in Jerusalem and fortified various cities for the defense of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 6, 'He built up Bethlehem, Etam, Tekoa,', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 7, 'Beth-zur, Soco, Adullam,', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 8, 'Gath, Mareshah, Ziph,', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 9, 'Adoraim, Lachish, Azekah,', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 10, 'Zorah, Aijalon, and Hebron. These became the fortified cities of Judah and Benjamin.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 11, 'Rehoboam strengthened their defenses and stationed commanders in them. In each of them, he stored supplies of food, olive oil, and wine.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 12, 'He also put shields and spears in these towns as a further safety measure. So only Judah and Benjamin remained under his control.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 13, 'But all the priests and Levites living among the northern tribes of Israel sided with Rehoboam.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 14, 'The Levites even abandoned their homes and property and moved to Judah and Jerusalem, because Jeroboam and his sons would not allow them to serve the LORD as priests.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 15, 'Jeroboam appointed his own priests to serve at the pagan shrines, where they worshiped the goat and calf idols he had made.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 16, 'From all over Israel, those who sincerely wanted to worship the LORD, the God of Israel, followed the Levites to Jerusalem, where they could offer sacrifices to the LORD, the God of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 17, 'This strengthened the kingdom of Judah, and for three years they supported Rehoboam son of Solomon and earnestly sought to obey the LORD as they had done during the reigns of David and Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 18, 'Rehoboam married his cousin Mahalath, the daughter of David''s son Jerimoth and of Abihail, the daughter of Eliab. (Eliab was one of David''s brothers, a son of Jesse.)', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 19, 'Mahalath had three sons--Jeush, Shemariah, and Zaham.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 20, 'Later Rehoboam married another cousin, Maacah, the daughter of Absalom. Maacah gave birth to Abijah, Attai, Ziza, and Shelomith.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 21, 'Rehoboam loved Maacah more than any of his other wives and concubines. In all, he had eighteen wives and sixty concubines, and they gave birth to twenty-eight sons and sixty daughters.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 22, 'Rehoboam made Maacah''s son Abijah chief among the princes, making it clear that he would be the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 11, 23, 'Rehoboam also wisely gave responsibilities to his other sons and stationed them in the fortified cities throughout the land of Judah and Benjamin. He provided them with generous provisions and arranged for each of them to have several wives.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 1, 'But when Rehoboam was firmly established and strong, he abandoned the law of the LORD, and all Israel followed him in this sin.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 2, 'Because they were unfaithful to the LORD, King Shishak of Egypt attacked Jerusalem in the fifth year of King Rehoboam''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 3, 'He came with twelve hundred chariots, sixty thousand horsemen, and a countless army of foot soldiers, including Libyans, Sukkites, and Ethiopians.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 4, 'Shishak conquered Judah''s fortified cities and then advanced to attack Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 5, 'The prophet Shemaiah then met with Rehoboam and Judah''s leaders, who had all fled to Jerusalem because of Shishak. Shemaiah told them, "This is what the LORD says: You have abandoned me, so I am abandoning you to Shishak."', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 6, 'The king and the leaders of Israel humbled themselves and said, "The LORD is right in doing this to us!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 7, 'When the LORD saw their change of heart, he gave this message to Shemaiah: "Since the people have humbled themselves, I will not completely destroy them and will soon give them some relief. I will not use Shishak to pour out my anger on Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 8, 'But they will become his subjects, so that they can learn how much better it is to serve me than to serve earthly rulers."', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 9, 'So King Shishak of Egypt came to Jerusalem and took away all the treasures of the Temple of the LORD and of the royal palace, including all of Solomon''s gold shields.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 10, 'King Rehoboam later replaced them with bronze shields and entrusted them to the care of the captain of his bodyguard.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 11, 'Whenever the king went to the Temple of the LORD, the guards would carry them along and then return them to the guardroom.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 12, 'Because Rehoboam humbled himself, the LORD''s anger was turned aside, and he did not destroy him completely. And there was still goodness in the land of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 13, 'King Rehoboam firmly established himself in Jerusalem and continued to rule. He was forty-one years old when he became king, and he reigned seventeen years in Jerusalem, the city the LORD had chosen from among all the tribes of Israel as the place to honor his name. Rehoboam''s mother was Naamah, a woman from Ammon.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 14, 'But he was an evil king, for he did not seek the LORD with all his heart.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 15, 'The rest of the events of Rehoboam''s reign, from beginning to end, are recorded in The Record of Shemaiah the Prophet and in The Record of Iddo the Seer, which are part of the genealogical record. Rehoboam and Jeroboam were continually at war with each other.', 'NLT'),
(18, 12, 16, 'When Rehoboam died, he was buried in the City of David. Then his son Abijah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 1, 'Abijah began to rule over Judah in the eighteenth year of Jeroboam''s reign in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 2, 'He reigned in Jerusalem three years. His mother was Maacah, a daughter of Uriel from Gibeah. Then war broke out between Abijah and Jeroboam.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 3, 'Judah, led by King Abijah, fielded 400,000 seasoned warriors, while Jeroboam mustered 800,000 courageous men from Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 4, 'When the army of Judah arrived in the hill country of Ephraim, Abijah stood on Mount Zemaraim and shouted to Jeroboam and the Israelite army: "Listen to me!', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 5, 'Don''t you realize that the LORD, the God of Israel, made an unbreakable covenant with David, giving him and his descendants the throne of Israel forever?', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 6, 'Yet Jeroboam son of Nebat, who was a mere servant of David''s son Solomon, became a traitor to his master.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 7, 'Then a whole gang of scoundrels joined him, defying Solomon''s son Rehoboam when he was young and inexperienced and could not stand up to them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 8, 'Do you really think you can stand against the kingdom of the LORD that is led by the descendants of David? Your army is vast indeed, but with you are those gold calves that Jeroboam made as your gods!', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 9, 'And you have chased away the priests of the LORD and the Levites and have appointed your own priests, just like the pagan nations. You let anyone become a priest these days! Whoever comes to be dedicated with a young bull and seven rams can become a priest of these so-called gods of yours!', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 10, '"But as for us, the LORD is our God, and we have not abandoned him. Only the descendants of Aaron serve the LORD as priests, and the Levites alone may help them in their work.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 11, 'They present burnt offerings and fragrant incense to the LORD every morning and evening. They place the Bread of the Presence on the holy table, and they light the gold lampstand every evening. We are following the instructions of the LORD our God, but you have abandoned him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 12, 'So you see, God is with us. He is our leader. His priests blow their trumpets and lead us into battle against you. O people of Israel, do not fight against the LORD, the God of your ancestors, for you will not succeed!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 13, 'Meanwhile, Jeroboam had secretly sent part of his army around behind the men of Judah to ambush them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 14, 'When Judah realized that they were being attacked from the front and the rear, they cried out to the LORD for help. Then the priests blew the trumpets,', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 15, 'and the men of Judah began to shout. At the sound of their battle cry, God defeated Jeroboam and the Israelite army and routed them before Abijah and the army of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 16, 'The Israelite army fled from Judah, and God handed them over to Judah in defeat.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 17, 'Abijah and his army inflicted heavy losses on them; there were 500,000 casualties among Israel''s finest troops that day.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 18, 'So Judah defeated Israel because they trusted in the LORD, the God of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 19, 'Abijah and his army pursued Jeroboam''s troops and captured some of his towns, including Bethel, Jeshanah, and Ephron, along with their surrounding villages.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 20, 'So Jeroboam of Israel never regained his power during Abijah''s lifetime, and finally the LORD struck him down and he died.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 21, 'By contrast, Abijah of Judah grew more and more powerful. He married fourteen wives and had twenty-two sons and sixteen daughters.', 'NLT'),
(18, 13, 22, 'The rest of the events of Abijah''s reign, including his words and deeds, are recorded in The Commentary of Iddo the Prophet.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 1, 'When Abijah died, he was buried in the City of David. Then his son Asa became the next king. There was peace in the land for ten years,', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 2, 'for Asa did what was pleasing and good in the sight of the LORD his God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 3, 'He removed the pagan altars and the shrines. He smashed the sacred pillars and cut down the Asherah poles.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 4, 'He commanded the people of Judah to seek the LORD, the God of their ancestors, and to obey his law and his commands.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 5, 'Asa also removed the pagan shrines, as well as the incense altars from every one of Judah''s towns. So Asa''s kingdom enjoyed a period of peace.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 6, 'During those peaceful years, he was able to build up the fortified cities throughout Judah. No one tried to make war against him at this time, for the LORD was giving him rest from his enemies.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 7, 'Asa told the people of Judah, "Let us build towns and fortify them with walls, towers, gates, and bars. The land is ours because we sought the LORD our God, and he has given us rest from our enemies." So they went ahead with these projects and brought them to completion.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 8, 'King Asa had an army of 300,000 warriors from the tribe of Judah, armed with large shields and spears. He also had an army of 280,000 warriors from the tribe of Benjamin, armed with small shields and bows. Both armies were composed of courageous fighting men.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 9, 'Once an Ethiopian named Zerah attacked Judah with an army of a million men and three hundred chariots. They advanced to the city of Mareshah,', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 10, 'so Asa deployed his armies for battle in the valley north of Mareshah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 11, 'Then Asa cried out to the LORD his God, "O LORD, no one but you can help the powerless against the mighty! Help us, O LORD our God, for we trust in you alone. It is in your name that we have come against this vast horde. O LORD, you are our God; do not let mere men prevail against you!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 12, 'So the LORD defeated the Ethiopians in the presence of Asa and the army of Judah, and the enemy fled.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 13, 'Asa and his army pursued them as far as Gerar, and so many Ethiopians fell that they were unable to rally. They were destroyed by the LORD and his army, and the army of Judah carried off vast quantities of plunder.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 14, 'While they were at Gerar, they attacked all the towns in that area, and terror from the LORD came upon the people there. As a result, vast quantities of plunder were taken from these towns, too.', 'NLT'),
(18, 14, 15, 'They also attacked the camps of herdsmen and captured many sheep and camels before finally returning to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 1, 'Then the Spirit of God came upon Azariah son of Oded,', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 2, 'and he went out to meet King Asa as he was returning from the battle. "Listen to me, Asa!" he shouted. "Listen, all you people of Judah and Benjamin! The LORD will stay with you as long as you stay with him! Whenever you seek him, you will find him. But if you abandon him, he will abandon you.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 3, 'For a long time, Israel was without the true God, without a priest to teach them, and without God''s law.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 4, 'But whenever you were in distress and turned to the LORD, the God of Israel, and sought him out, you found him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 5, 'During those dark times, it was not safe to travel. Problems troubled the nation on every hand.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 6, 'Nation fought against nation, and city against city, for God was troubling you with every kind of problem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 7, 'And now, you men of Judah, be strong and courageous, for your work will be rewarded."', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 8, 'When Asa heard this message from Azariah the prophet, he took courage and removed all the idols in the land of Judah and Benjamin and in the towns he had captured in the hill country of Ephraim. And he repaired the altar of the LORD, which stood in front of the foyer of the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 9, 'Then Asa called together all the people of Judah and Benjamin, along with the people of Ephraim, Manasseh, and Simeon who had settled among them. Many had moved to Judah during Asa''s reign when they saw that the LORD his God was with him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 10, 'The people gathered at Jerusalem in late spring, during the fifteenth year of Asa''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 11, 'On that day they sacrificed to the LORD some of the animals they had taken as plunder in the battle--seven hundred oxen and seven thousand sheep and goats.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 12, 'Then they entered into a covenant to seek the LORD, the God of their ancestors, with all their heart and soul.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 13, 'They agreed that anyone who refused to seek the LORD, the God of Israel, would be put to death--whether young or old, man or woman.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 14, 'They shouted out their oath of loyalty to the LORD with trumpets blaring and horns sounding.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 15, 'All were happy about this covenant, for they had entered into it with all their hearts. Eagerly they sought after God, and they found him. And the LORD gave them rest from their enemies on every side.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 16, 'King Asa even deposed his grandmother Maacah from her position as queen mother because she had made an obscene Asherah pole. He cut down the pole, broke it up, and burned it in the Kidron Valley.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 17, 'Although the pagan shrines were not completely removed from Israel, Asa remained fully committed to the LORD throughout his life.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 18, 'He brought into the Temple of God the silver and gold and the utensils that he and his father had dedicated.', 'NLT'),
(18, 15, 19, 'So there was no more war until the thirty-fifth year of Asa''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 1, 'In the thirty-sixth year of Asa''s reign, King Baasha of Israel invaded Judah and fortified Ramah in order to prevent anyone from entering or leaving King Asa''s territory in Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 2, 'Asa responded by taking the silver and gold from the treasuries of the LORD''s Temple and from the royal palace. He sent it to King Ben-hadad of Aram, who was ruling in Damascus, along with this message:', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 3, '"Let us renew the treaty that existed between your father and my father. See, I am sending you a gift of silver and gold. Break your treaty with King Baasha of Israel so that he will leave me alone."', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 4, 'Ben-hadad agreed to King Asa''s request and sent his armies to attack Israel. They conquered the towns of Ijon, Dan, Abel-beth-maacah, and all the store cities in Naphtali.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 5, 'As soon as Baasha of Israel heard what was happening, he abandoned his project of fortifying Ramah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 6, 'Then King Asa called out all the men of Judah to carry away the building stones and timbers that Baasha had been using to fortify Ramah. Asa used these materials to fortify the towns of Geba and Mizpah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 7, 'At that time Hanani the seer came to King Asa and told him, "Because you have put your trust in the king of Aram instead of in the LORD your God, you missed your chance to destroy the army of the king of Aram.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 8, 'Don''t you remember what happened to the Ethiopians and Libyans and their vast army, with all of their chariots and horsemen? At that time you relied on the LORD, and he handed them all over to you.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 9, 'The eyes of the LORD search the whole earth in order to strengthen those whose hearts are fully committed to him. What a fool you have been! From now on, you will be at war."', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 10, 'Asa became so angry with Hanani for saying this that he threw him into prison. At that time, Asa also began to oppress some of his people.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 11, 'The rest of the events of Asa''s reign, from beginning to end, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Judah and Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 12, 'In the thirty-ninth year of his reign, Asa developed a serious foot disease. Even when the disease became life threatening, he did not seek the LORD''s help but sought help only from his physicians.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 13, 'So he died in the forty-first year of his reign.', 'NLT'),
(18, 16, 14, 'He was buried in the tomb he had carved out for himself in the City of David. He was laid on a bed perfumed with sweet spices and ointments, and at his funeral the people built a huge fire in his honor.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 1, 'Then Jehoshaphat, Asa''s son, became the next king. He strengthened Judah to stand against any attack from Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 2, 'He stationed troops in all the fortified cities of Judah, and he assigned additional garrisons to the land of Judah and to the towns of Ephraim that his father, Asa, had conquered.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 3, 'The LORD was with Jehoshaphat because he followed the example of his father''s early years and did not worship the images of Baal.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 4, 'He sought his father''s God and obeyed his commands instead of following the practices of the kingdom of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 5, 'So the LORD established Jehoshaphat''s control over the kingdom of Judah. All the people of Judah brought gifts to Jehoshaphat, so he became very wealthy and highly esteemed.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 6, 'He was committed to the ways of the LORD. He knocked down the pagan shrines and destroyed the Asherah poles.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 7, 'In the third year of his reign, Jehoshaphat sent out his officials to teach in all the towns of Judah. These officials included Ben-hail, Obadiah, Zechariah, Nethanel, and Micaiah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 8, 'He sent Levites along with them, including Shemaiah, Nethaniah, Zebadiah, Asahel, Shemiramoth, Jehonathan, Adonijah, Tobijah, and Tob-adonijah. He also sent out the priests, Elishama and Jehoram.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 9, 'They took copies of the Book of the Law of the LORD and traveled around through all the towns of Judah, teaching the people.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 10, 'Then the fear of the LORD fell over all the surrounding kingdoms so that none of them declared war on Jehoshaphat.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 11, 'Some of the Philistines brought him gifts and silver as tribute, and the Arabs brought seventy-seven hundred rams and seventy-seven hundred male goats.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 12, 'So Jehoshaphat became more and more powerful and built fortresses and store cities throughout Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 13, 'He stored numerous supplies in Judah''s towns and stationed an army of seasoned troops at Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 14, 'His army was enrolled according to ancestral clans. From Judah, there were 300,000 troops organized in units of one thousand, under the command of Adnah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 15, 'Next in command was Jehohanan, who commanded 280,000 troops.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 16, 'Next was Amasiah son of Zicri, who volunteered for the LORD''s service, with 200,000 troops under his command.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 17, 'From Benjamin, there were 200,000 troops equipped with bows and shields. They were under the command of Eliada, a veteran soldier.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 18, 'Next in command was Jehozabad, who commanded 180,000 armed men.', 'NLT'),
(18, 17, 19, 'These were the troops stationed in Jerusalem to serve the king, besides those Jehoshaphat stationed in the fortified cities throughout Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 1, 'Now Jehoshaphat enjoyed great riches and high esteem, and he arranged for his son to marry the daughter of King Ahab of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 2, 'A few years later, he went to Samaria to visit Ahab, who prepared a great banquet for him and his officials. They butchered great numbers of sheep and oxen for the feast. Then Ahab enticed Jehoshaphat to join forces with him to attack Ramoth-gilead.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 3, '"Will you join me in fighting against Ramoth-gilead?" Ahab asked. And Jehoshaphat replied, "Why, of course! You and I are brothers, and my troops are yours to command. We will certainly join you in battle."', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 4, 'Then Jehoshaphat added, "But first let''s find out what the LORD says."', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 5, 'So King Ahab summoned his prophets, four hundred of them, and asked them, "Should we go to war against Ramoth-gilead or not?" They all replied, "Go ahead, for God will give you a great victory!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 6, 'But Jehoshaphat asked, "Isn''t there a prophet of the LORD around, too? I would like to ask him the same question."', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 7, 'King Ahab replied, "There is still one prophet of the LORD, but I hate him. He never prophesies anything but bad news for me! His name is Micaiah son of Imlah.You shouldn''t talk like that," Jehoshaphat said. "Let''s hear what he has to say."', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 8, 'So the king of Israel called one of his officials and said, "Quick! Go and get Micaiah son of Imlah."', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 9, 'King Ahab of Israel and King Jehoshaphat of Judah, dressed in their royal robes, were sitting on thrones at the threshing floor near the gate of Samaria. All of Ahab''s prophets were prophesying there in front of them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 10, 'One of them, Zedekiah son of Kenaanah, made some iron horns and proclaimed, "This is what the LORD says: With these horns you will gore the Arameans to death!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 11, 'All the other prophets agreed. "Yes," they said, "go up to Ramoth-gilead and be victorious. The LORD will give you a glorious victory!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 12, 'Meanwhile, the messenger who went to get Micaiah said to him, "Look, all the prophets are promising victory for the king. Be sure that you agree with them and promise success."', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 13, 'But Micaiah replied, "As surely as the LORD lives, I will say only what my God tells me to say."', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 14, 'When Micaiah arrived before the king, Ahab asked him, "Micaiah, should we go to war against Ramoth-gilead or not?" And Micaiah replied, "Go right ahead! It will be a glorious victory!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 15, 'But the king replied sharply, "How many times must I demand that you speak only the truth when you speak for the LORD?"', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 16, 'So Micaiah told him, "In a vision I saw all Israel scattered on the mountains, like sheep without a shepherd. And the LORD said, `Their master has been killed. Send them home in peace.''"', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 17, '"Didn''t I tell you?" the king of Israel said to Jehoshaphat. "He does it every time. He never prophesies anything but bad news for me."', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 18, 'Then Micaiah continued, "Listen to what the LORD says! I saw the LORD sitting on his throne with all the armies of heaven on his right and on his left.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 19, 'And the LORD said, `Who can entice King Ahab of Israel to go into battle against Ramoth-gilead so that he can be killed there?'' There were many suggestions,', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 20, 'until finally a spirit approached the LORD and said, `I can do it!''" `How will you do this?'' the LORD asked.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 21, '"And the spirit replied, `I will go out and inspire all Ahab''s prophets to speak lies.''" `You will succeed,'' said the LORD. `Go ahead and do it.''', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 22, '"So you see, the LORD has put a lying spirit in the mouths of your prophets. For the LORD has determined disaster for you."', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 23, 'Then Zedekiah son of Kenaanah walked up to Micaiah and slapped him across the face. "When did the Spirit of the LORD leave me to speak to you?" he demanded.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 24, 'And Micaiah replied, "You will find out soon enough, when you find yourself hiding in some secret room!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 25, 'King Ahab of Israel then ordered, "Arrest Micaiah and take him back to Amon, the governor of the city, and to my son Joash.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 26, 'Give them this order from the king: `Put this man in prison, and feed him nothing but bread and water until I return safely from the battle!''"', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 27, 'But Micaiah replied, "If you return safely, the LORD has not spoken through me!" Then he added to those standing around, "Take note of what I have said."', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 28, 'So the king of Israel and King Jehoshaphat of Judah led their armies against Ramoth-gilead.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 29, 'Now King Ahab said to Jehoshaphat, "As we go into battle, I will disguise myself so no one will recognize me, but you wear your royal robes." So Ahab disguised himself, and they went into battle.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 30, 'Now the king of Aram had issued these orders to his charioteers: "Attack only the king of Israel!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 31, 'So when the Aramean charioteers saw Jehoshaphat in his royal robes, they went after him. "There is the king of Israel!" they shouted. But Jehoshaphat cried out to the LORD to save him, and God helped him by turning the attack away from him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 32, 'As soon as the charioteers realized he was not the king of Israel, they stopped chasing him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 33, 'An Aramean soldier, however, randomly shot an arrow at the Israelite troops, and the arrow hit the king of Israel between the joints of his armor. "Get me out of here!" Ahab groaned to the driver of his chariot. "I have been badly wounded!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 18, 34, 'The battle raged all that day, and Ahab propped himself up in his chariot facing the Arameans until evening. Then, just as the sun was setting, he died.', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 1, 'When King Jehoshaphat of Judah arrived safely home to Jerusalem,', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 2, 'Jehu son of Hanani the seer went out to meet him. "Why should you help the wicked and love those who hate the LORD?" he asked the king. "What you have done has brought the LORD''s anger against you.', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 3, 'There is some good in you, however, for you have removed the Asherah poles throughout the land, and you have committed yourself to seeking God."', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 4, 'So Jehoshaphat lived in Jerusalem, but he went out among the people, traveling from Beersheba to the hill country of Ephraim, encouraging the people to return to the LORD, the God of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 5, 'He appointed judges throughout the nation in all the fortified cities,', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 6, 'and he gave them these instructions: "Always think carefully before pronouncing judgment. Remember that you do not judge to please people but to please the LORD. He will be with you when you render the verdict in each case that comes before you.', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 7, 'Fear the LORD and judge with care, for the LORD our God does not tolerate perverted justice, partiality, or the taking of bribes."', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 8, 'Jehoshaphat appointed some of the Levites and priests and clan leaders in Israel to serve as judges in Jerusalem for cases concerning both the law of the LORD and civil disputes.', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 9, 'These were his instructions to them: "You must always act in the fear of the LORD, with integrity and with undivided hearts.', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 10, 'Whenever a case comes to you from fellow citizens in an outlying town, whether a murder case or some other violation of God''s instructions, commands, laws, or regulations, you must warn them not to sin against the LORD, so that his anger will not come against you and them. Do this and you will not be guilty.', 'NLT'),
(18, 19, 11, '"Amariah the high priest will have final say in all cases concerning the LORD. Zebadiah son of Ishmael, a leader from the tribe of Judah, will have final say in all civil cases. The Levites will assist you in making sure that justice is served. Take courage as you fulfill your duties, and may the LORD be with those who do what is right."', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 1, 'After this, the armies of the Moabites, Ammonites, and some of the Meunites declared war on Jehoshaphat.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 2, 'Messengers came and told Jehoshaphat, "A vast army from Edom is marching against you from beyond the Dead Sea. They are already at Hazazon-tamar." (This was another name for En-gedi.)', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 3, 'Jehoshaphat was alarmed by this news and sought the LORD for guidance. He also gave orders that everyone throughout Judah should observe a fast.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 4, 'So people from all the towns of Judah came to Jerusalem to seek the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 5, 'Jehoshaphat stood before the people of Judah and Jerusalem in front of the new courtyard at the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 6, 'He prayed, "O LORD, God of our ancestors, you alone are the God who is in heaven. You are ruler of all the kingdoms of the earth. You are powerful and mighty; no one can stand against you!', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 7, 'O our God, did you not drive out those who lived in this land when your people arrived? And did you not give this land forever to the descendants of your friend Abraham?', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 8, 'Your people settled here and built this Temple for you.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 9, 'They said, `Whenever we are faced with any calamity such as war, disease, or famine, we can come to stand in your presence before this Temple where your name is honored. We can cry out to you to save us, and you will hear us and rescue us.''', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 10, '"And now see what the armies of Ammon, Moab, and Mount Seir are doing. You would not let our ancestors invade those nations when Israel left Egypt, so they went around them and did not destroy them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 11, 'Now see how they reward us! For they have come to throw us out of your land, which you gave us as an inheritance.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 12, 'O our God, won''t you stop them? We are powerless against this mighty army that is about to attack us. We do not know what to do, but we are looking to you for help."', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 13, 'As all the men of Judah stood before the LORD with their little ones, wives, and children,', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 14, 'the Spirit of the LORD came upon one of the men standing there. His name was Jahaziel son of Zechariah, son of Benaiah, son of Jeiel, son of Mattaniah, a Levite who was a descendant of Asaph.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 15, 'He said, "Listen, King Jehoshaphat! Listen, all you people of Judah and Jerusalem! This is what the LORD says: Do not be afraid! Don''t be discouraged by this mighty army, for the battle is not yours, but God''s.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 16, 'Tomorrow, march out against them. You will find them coming up through the ascent of Ziz at the end of the valley that opens into the wilderness of Jeruel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 17, 'But you will not even need to fight. Take your positions; then stand still and watch the LORD''s victory. He is with you, O people of Judah and Jerusalem. Do not be afraid or discouraged. Go out there tomorrow, for the LORD is with you!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 18, 'Then King Jehoshaphat bowed down with his face to the ground. And all the people of Judah and Jerusalem did the same, worshiping the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 19, 'Then the Levites from the clans of Kohath and Korah stood to praise the LORD, the God of Israel, with a very loud shout.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 20, 'Early the next morning the army of Judah went out into the wilderness of Tekoa. On the way Jehoshaphat stopped and said, "Listen to me, all you people of Judah and Jerusalem! Believe in the LORD your God, and you will be able to stand firm. Believe in his prophets, and you will succeed."', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 21, 'After consulting the leaders of the people, the king appointed singers to walk ahead of the army, singing to the LORD and praising him for his holy splendor. This is what they sang: "Give thanks to the LORD; his faithful love endures forever!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 22, 'At the moment they began to sing and give praise, the LORD caused the armies of Ammon, Moab, and Mount Seir to start fighting among themselves.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 23, 'The armies of Moab and Ammon turned against their allies from Mount Seir and killed every one of them. After they had finished off the army of Seir, they turned on each other.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 24, 'So when the army of Judah arrived at the lookout point in the wilderness, there were dead bodies lying on the ground for as far as they could see. Not a single one of the enemy had escaped.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 25, 'King Jehoshaphat and his men went out to gather the plunder. They found vast amounts of equipment, clothing, and other valuables--more than they could carry. There was so much plunder that it took them three days just to collect it all!', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 26, 'On the fourth day they gathered in the Valley of Blessing, which got its name that day because the people praised and thanked the LORD there. It is still called the Valley of Blessing today.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 27, 'Then they returned to Jerusalem, with Jehoshaphat leading them, full of joy that the LORD had given them victory over their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 28, 'They marched into Jerusalem to the music of harps, lyres, and trumpets and proceeded to the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 29, 'When the surrounding kingdoms heard that the LORD himself had fought against the enemies of Israel, the fear of God came over them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 30, 'So Jehoshaphat''s kingdom was at peace, for his God had given him rest on every side.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 31, 'So Jehoshaphat ruled over the land of Judah. He was thirty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem twenty-five years. His mother was Azubah, the daughter of Shilhi.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 32, 'Jehoshaphat was a good king, following the ways of his father, Asa. He did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 33, 'During his reign, however, he failed to remove all the pagan shrines, and the people never fully committed themselves to following the God of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 34, 'The rest of the events of Jehoshaphat''s reign, from beginning to end, are recorded in The Record of Jehu Son of Hanani, which is included in The Book of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 35, 'But near the end of his life, King Jehoshaphat of Judah made an alliance with King Ahaziah of Israel, who was a very wicked man.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 36, 'Together they built a fleet of trading ships at the port of Ezion-geber.', 'NLT'),
(18, 20, 37, 'Then Eliezer son of Dodavahu from Mareshah prophesied against Jehoshaphat. He said, "Because you have allied yourself with King Ahaziah, the LORD will destroy your work." So the ships met with disaster and never put out to sea.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 1, 'When Jehoshaphat died, he was buried with his ancestors in the City of David. Then his son Jehoram became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 2, 'Jehoram''s brothers--the other sons of Jehoshaphat--were Azariah, Jehiel, Zechariah, Azariahu, Michael, and Shephatiah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 3, 'Their father had given each of them valuable gifts of silver, gold, and costly items, and also the ownership of some of Judah''s fortified cities. However, Jehoram became king because he was the oldest.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 4, 'But when Jehoram had become solidly established as king, he killed all his brothers and some of the other leaders of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 5, 'Jehoram was thirty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem eight years.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 6, 'But Jehoram followed the example of the kings of Israel and was as wicked as King Ahab, for he had married one of Ahab''s daughters. So Jehoram did what was evil in the LORD''s sight.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 7, 'But the LORD was not willing to destroy David''s dynasty, for he had made a covenant with David and promised that his descendants would continue to rule forever.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 8, 'During Jehoram''s reign, the Edomites revolted against Judah and crowned their own king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 9, 'So Jehoram went to attack Edom with his full army and all his chariots. The Edomites surrounded him and his charioteers, but he escaped at night under cover of darkness.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 10, 'Edom has been independent from Judah to this day. The town of Libnah revolted about that same time, because Jehoram had abandoned the LORD, the God of his ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 11, 'He had built pagan shrines in the hill country of Judah and had led the people of Jerusalem and Judah to give themselves to pagan gods.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 12, 'Then Elijah the prophet wrote Jehoram this letter: "This is what the LORD, the God of your ancestor David, says: You have not followed the good example of your father, Jehoshaphat, or your grandfather King Asa of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 13, 'Instead, you have been as evil as the kings of Israel. You have led the people of Jerusalem and Judah to worship idols, just as King Ahab did in Israel. And you have even killed your own brothers, men who were better than you.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 14, 'So now the LORD is about to strike you, your people, your children, your wives, and all that is yours with a heavy blow.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 15, 'You yourself will be stricken with a severe intestinal disease until it causes your bowels to come out."', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 16, 'Then the LORD stirred up the Philistines and the Arabs, who lived near the Ethiopians, to attack Jehoram.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 17, 'They marched against Judah, broke down its defenses, and carried away everything of value in the royal palace, including his sons and his wives. Only his youngest son, Ahaziah, was spared.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 18, 'It was after this that the LORD struck Jehoram with the severe intestinal disease.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 19, 'In the course of time, at the end of two years, the disease caused his bowels to come out, and he died in agony. His people did not build a great fire to honor him at his funeral as they had done for his ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 21, 20, 'Jehoram was thirty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem eight years. No one was sorry when he died. He was buried in the City of David, but not in the royal cemetery.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 1, 'Then the people of Jerusalem made Ahaziah, Jehoram''s youngest son, their next king. The marauding bands of Arabs had killed all the older sons. So Ahaziah son of Jehoram reigned as king of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 2, 'Ahaziah was twenty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem one year. His mother was Athaliah, a granddaughter of King Omri of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 3, 'Ahaziah also followed the evil example of King Ahab''s family, for his mother encouraged him in doing wrong.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 4, 'He did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, just as Ahab had done. After the death of his father, members of Ahab''s family became his advisers, and they led him to ruin.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 5, 'Following their evil advice, Ahaziah made an alliance with King Joram, the son of King Ahab of Israel. They went out to fight King Hazael of Aram at Ramoth-gilead, and the Arameans wounded Joram in the battle.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 6, 'Joram returned to Jezreel to recover from his wounds, and King Ahaziah of Judah went to Jezreel to visit him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 7, 'But this turned out to be a fatal mistake, for God had decided to punish Ahaziah. It was during this visit that Ahaziah went out with Joram to meet Jehu son of Nimshi, whom the LORD had appointed to end the dynasty of Ahab.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 8, 'While Jehu was executing judgment against the family of Ahab, he happened to meet some of Judah''s officials and Ahaziah''s relatives who were attending Ahaziah. So Jehu killed them all.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 9, 'Then Jehu''s men searched for Ahaziah, and they found him hiding in the city of Samaria. They brought him to Jehu, who killed him. Ahaziah was given a decent burial because the people said, "He was the grandson of Jehoshaphat--a man who sought the LORD with all his heart." None of the surviving members of Ahaziah''s family was capable of ruling the kingdom.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 10, 'When Athaliah, the mother of King Ahaziah of Judah, learned that her son was dead, she set out to destroy the rest of Judah''s royal family.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 11, 'But Ahaziah''s sister Jehosheba, the daughter of King Jehoram, took Ahaziah''s infant son, Joash, and stole him away from among the rest of the king''s children, who were about to be killed. She put Joash and his nurse in a bedroom. In this way, Jehosheba, the wife of Jehoiada the priest, hid the child so that Athaliah could not murder him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 22, 12, 'Joash remained hidden in the Temple of God for six years while Athaliah ruled over the land.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 1, 'In the seventh year of Athaliah''s reign, Jehoiada the priest decided to act. He got up his courage and made a pact with five army commanders: Azariah son of Jeroham, Ishmael son of Jehohanan, Azariah son of Obed, Maaseiah son of Adaiah, and Elishaphat son of Zicri.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 2, 'These men traveled secretly throughout Judah and summoned the Levites and clan leaders in Judah''s towns to come to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 3, 'They all gathered at the Temple of God, where they made a covenant with Joash, the young king. Jehoiada said to them, "The time has come for the king''s son to reign! The LORD has promised that a descendant of David will be our king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 4, 'This is what you must do. When the priests and Levites come on duty on the Sabbath, a third of them will serve as gatekeepers.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 5, 'Another third will go over to the royal palace, and the final third will be at the Foundation Gate. Everyone else should stay in the courtyards of the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 6, 'Remember, only the priests and Levites on duty may enter the Temple of the LORD, for they are set apart as holy. The rest of the people must obey the LORD''s instructions and stay outside.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 7, 'You Levites, form a bodyguard for the king and keep your weapons in hand. Any unauthorized person who enters the Temple must be killed. Stay right beside the king at all times."', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 8, 'So the Levites and the people did everything just as Jehoiada the priest ordered. The commanders took charge of the men reporting for duty that Sabbath, as well as those who were going off duty. Jehoiada the priest did not let anyone go home after their shift ended.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 9, 'Then Jehoiada supplied the commanders with the spears and shields that had once belonged to King David and were stored in the Temple of God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 10, 'He stationed the guards around the king, with their weapons ready. They formed a line from the south side of the Temple around to the north side and all around the altar.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 11, 'Then Jehoiada and his sons brought out Joash, the king''s son, and placed the crown on his head. They presented Joash with a copy of God''s laws and proclaimed him king. Then they anointed him, and everyone shouted, "Long live the king!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 12, 'When Athaliah heard the noise of the people running and the shouts of praise to the king, she hurried to the LORD''s Temple to see what was happening.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 13, 'And she saw the newly crowned king standing in his place of authority by the pillar at the Temple entrance. The officers and trumpeters were surrounding him, and people from all over the land were rejoicing and blowing trumpets. Singers with musical instruments were leading the people in a great celebration. When Athaliah saw all this, she tore her clothes in despair and shouted, "Treason! Treason!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 14, 'Then Jehoiada the priest ordered the commanders who were in charge of the troops, "Take her out of the Temple, and kill anyone who tries to rescue her. Do not kill her here in the Temple of the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 15, 'So they seized her and led her out to the gate where horses enter the palace grounds, and they killed her there.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 16, 'Then Jehoiada made a covenant between himself and the king and the people that they would be the LORD''s people.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 17, 'And all the people went over to the temple of Baal and tore it down. They demolished the altars and smashed the idols, and they killed Mattan the priest of Baal in front of the altars.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 18, 'Jehoiada now put the Levitical priests in charge of the Temple of the LORD, following all the instructions given by David. He also commanded them to present burnt offerings to the LORD, as prescribed by the law of Moses, and to sing and rejoice as David had instructed.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 19, 'He stationed gatekeepers at the gates of the LORD''s Temple to keep those who were ceremonially unclean from entering.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 20, 'Then the commanders, nobles, rulers, and all the people escorted the king from the Temple of the LORD. They went through the Upper Gate and into the palace, and they seated the king on the royal throne.', 'NLT'),
(18, 23, 21, 'So all the people of the land rejoiced, and the city was peaceful because Athaliah had been killed.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 1, 'Joash was seven years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem forty years. His mother was Zibiah, from Beersheba.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 2, 'Joash did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight throughout the lifetime of Jehoiada the priest.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 3, 'Jehoiada chose two wives for Joash, and he had sons and daughters.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 4, 'Some time later, Joash decided to repair and restore the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 5, 'He summoned the priests and Levites and gave them these instructions: "Go at once to all the towns of Judah and collect the required annual offerings, so that we can repair the Temple of your God. Do not delay!" But the Levites did not act right away.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 6, 'So the king called for Jehoiada the high priest and asked him, "Why haven''t you demanded that the Levites go out and collect the Temple taxes from the towns of Judah and from Jerusalem? Moses, the servant of the LORD, levied this tax on the community of Israel in order to maintain the Tabernacle of the Covenant. "', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 7, 'Over the years, the followers of wicked Athaliah had broken into the Temple of God, and they had used all the dedicated things from the Temple of the LORD to worship the images of Baal.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 8, 'So now Joash gave instructions for a chest to be made and set outside the gate leading to the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 9, 'Then a proclamation was sent throughout Judah and Jerusalem, telling the people to bring to the LORD the tax that Moses, the servant of God, had required of the Israelites in the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 10, 'This pleased all the leaders and the people, and they gladly brought their money and filled the chest with it.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 11, 'Whenever the chest became full, the Levites carried it to the king''s officials. Then the court secretary and an officer of the high priest counted the money and took the chest back to the Temple again. This went on day after day, and a large amount of money was collected.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 12, 'The king and Jehoiada gave the money to the construction supervisors, who hired masons and carpenters to restore the Temple of the LORD. They also hired metalworkers, who made articles of iron and bronze for the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 13, 'So the men in charge of the renovation worked hard, and they made steady progress. They restored the Temple of God according to its original design and strengthened it.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 14, 'When all the repairs were finished, they brought the remaining money to the king and Jehoiada. It was used to make utensils for the Temple of the LORD--utensils for worship services and for burnt offerings, including ladles and other vessels made of gold and silver. And the burnt offerings were sacrificed continually in the Temple of the LORD during the lifetime of Jehoiada the priest.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 15, 'Jehoiada lived to a very old age, finally dying at 130.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 16, 'He was buried among the kings in the City of David, because he had done so much good in Israel for God and his Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 17, 'But after Jehoiada''s death, the leaders of Judah came and bowed before King Joash and persuaded the king to listen to their advice.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 18, 'They decided to abandon the Temple of the LORD, the God of their ancestors, and they worshiped Asherah poles and idols instead! Then the anger of God burned against Judah and Jerusalem because of their sin.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 19, 'The LORD sent prophets to bring them back to him, but the people would not listen.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 20, 'Then the Spirit of God came upon Zechariah son of Jehoiada the priest. He stood before the people and said, "This is what God says: Why do you disobey the LORD''s commands so that you cannot prosper? You have abandoned the LORD, and now he has abandoned you!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 21, 'Then the leaders plotted to kill Zechariah, and by order of King Joash himself, they stoned him to death in the courtyard of the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 22, 'That was how King Joash repaid Jehoiada for his love and loyalty--by killing his son. Zechariah''s last words as he died were, "May the LORD see what they are doing and hold them accountable!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 23, 'At the beginning of the year, the Aramean army marched against Joash. They invaded Judah and Jerusalem and killed all the leaders of the nation. Then they sent all the plunder back to their king in Damascus.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 24, 'Although the Arameans attacked with only a small army, the LORD helped them conquer the much larger army of Judah. The people of Judah had abandoned the LORD, the God of their ancestors, so judgment was executed against Joash.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 25, 'The Arameans withdrew, leaving Joash severely wounded. But his own officials decided to kill him for murdering the son of Jehoiada the priest. They assassinated him as he lay in bed. Then he was buried in the City of David, but not in the royal cemetery.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 26, 'The assassins were Jozabad, the son of an Ammonite woman named Shimeath, and Jehozabad, the son of a Moabite woman named Shomer.', 'NLT'),
(18, 24, 27, 'The complete story about the sons of Joash, the prophecies about him, and the record of his restoration of the Temple of God are written in The Commentary on the Book of the Kings. When Joash died, his son Amaziah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 1, 'Amaziah was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem twenty-nine years. His mother was Jehoaddin, from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 2, 'Amaziah did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight, but not wholeheartedly.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 3, 'When Amaziah was well established as king, he executed the men who had assassinated his father.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 4, 'However, he did not kill the children of the assassins, for he obeyed the command of the LORD written in the Book of the Law of Moses: "Parents must not be put to death for the sins of their children, nor the children for the sins of their parents. Those worthy of death must be executed for their own crimes."', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 5, 'Another thing Amaziah did was to organize the army, assigning leaders to each clan from Judah and Benjamin. Then he took a census and found that he had an army of 300,000 men twenty years old and older, all trained in the use of spear and shield.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 6, 'He also paid about 7,500 pounds of silver to hire 100,000 experienced fighting men from Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 7, 'But a man of God came to the king and said, "O king, do not hire troops from Israel, for the LORD is not with Israel. He will not help those people of Ephraim!', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 8, 'If you let them go with your troops into battle, you will be defeated no matter how well you fight. God will overthrow you, for he has the power to help or to frustrate."', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 9, 'Amaziah asked the man of God, "But what should I do about the silver I paid to hire the army of Israel?" The man of God replied, "The LORD is able to give you much more than this!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 10, 'So Amaziah discharged the hired troops and sent them back to Ephraim. This made them angry with Judah, and they returned home in a great rage.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 11, 'Then Amaziah summoned his courage and led his army to the Valley of Salt, where they killed ten thousand Edomite troops from Seir.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 12, 'They captured another ten thousand and took them to the top of a cliff and threw them off, dashing them to pieces on the rocks below.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 13, 'Meanwhile, the hired troops that Amaziah had sent home raided several of the towns of Judah between Samaria and Beth-horon, killing three thousand people and carrying off great quantities of plunder.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 14, 'When King Amaziah returned from defeating the Edomites, he brought with him idols taken from the people of Seir. He set them up as his own gods, bowed down in front of them, and presented sacrifices to them!', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 15, 'This made the LORD very angry, and he sent a prophet to ask, "Why have you worshiped gods who could not even save their own people from you?"', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 16, 'But the king interrupted him and said, "Since when have I asked your advice? Be quiet now before I have you killed!" So the prophet left with this warning: "I know that God has determined to destroy you because you have done this and have not accepted my counsel."', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 17, 'After consulting with his advisers, King Amaziah of Judah sent this challenge to Israel''s king Jehoash, the son of Jehoahaz and grandson of Jehu: "Come and meet me in battle!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 18, 'But King Jehoash of Israel replied to King Amaziah of Judah with this story: "Out in the Lebanon mountains, a thistle sent a message to a mighty cedar tree: `Give your daughter in marriage to my son.'' But just then a wild animal came by and stepped on the thistle, crushing it!', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 19, 'You may be very proud of your conquest of Edom, but my advice is to stay home. Why stir up trouble that will bring disaster on you and the people of Judah?"', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 20, 'But Amaziah would not listen, for God was arranging to destroy him for worshiping the gods of Edom.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 21, 'So King Jehoash of Israel mobilized his army against King Amaziah of Judah. The two armies drew up their battle lines at Beth-shemesh in Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 22, 'Judah was routed by the army of Israel, and its army scattered and fled for home.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 23, 'King Jehoash of Israel captured King Amaziah of Judah at Beth-shemesh and brought him back to Jerusalem. Then Jehoash ordered his army to demolish six hundred feet of Jerusalem''s wall, from the Ephraim Gate to the Corner Gate.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 24, 'He carried off all the gold and silver and all the utensils from the Temple of God that had been in the care of Obed-edom. He also seized the treasures of the royal palace, along with hostages, and then returned to Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 25, 'King Amaziah of Judah lived on for fifteen years after the death of King Jehoash of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 26, 'The rest of the events of Amaziah''s reign, from beginning to end, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Judah and Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 27, 'After Amaziah turned away from the LORD, there was a conspiracy against his life in Jerusalem, and he fled to Lachish. But his enemies sent assassins after him, and they killed him there.', 'NLT'),
(18, 25, 28, 'They brought him back to Jerusalem on a horse, and he was buried with his ancestors in the City of David.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 1, 'The people of Judah then crowned Amaziah''s sixteen-year-old son, Uzziah, as their next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 2, 'After his father''s death, Uzziah rebuilt the town of Elath and restored it to Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 3, 'Uzziah was sixteen when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem fifty-two years. His mother was Jecoliah, from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 4, 'He did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight, just as his father, Amaziah, had done.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 5, 'Uzziah sought God during the days of Zechariah, who instructed him in the fear of God. And as long as the king sought the LORD, God gave him success.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 6, 'He declared war on the Philistines and broke down the walls of Gath, Jabneh, and Ashdod. Then he built new towns in the Ashdod area and in other parts of Philistia.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 7, 'God helped him not only with his wars against the Philistines, but also in his battles with the Arabs of Gur and in his wars with the Meunites.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 8, 'The Meunites paid annual tribute to him, and his fame spread even to Egypt, for he had become very powerful.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 9, 'Uzziah built fortified towers in Jerusalem at the Corner Gate, at the Valley Gate, and at the angle in the wall.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 10, 'He also constructed forts in the wilderness and dug many water cisterns, because he kept great herds of livestock in the foothills of Judah and on the plains. He was also a man who loved the soil. He had many workers who cared for his farms and vineyards, both on the hillsides and in the fertile valleys.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 11, 'Uzziah had an army of well-trained warriors, ready to march into battle, unit by unit. This great army of fighting men had been mustered and organized by Jeiel, the secretary of the army, and his assistant, Maaseiah. They were under the direction of Hananiah, one of the king''s officials.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 12, 'Twenty-six hundred clan leaders commanded these regiments of seasoned warriors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 13, 'The army consisted of 307,500 men, all elite troops. They were prepared to assist the king against any enemy.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 14, 'Uzziah provided the entire army with shields, spears, helmets, coats of mail, bows, and sling stones.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 15, 'And he produced machines mounted on the walls of Jerusalem, designed by brilliant men to shoot arrows and hurl stones from the towers and the corners of the wall. His fame spread far and wide, for the LORD helped him wonderfully until he became very powerful.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 16, 'But when he had become powerful, he also became proud, which led to his downfall. He sinned against the LORD his God by entering the sanctuary of the LORD''s Temple and personally burning incense on the altar.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 17, 'Azariah the high priest went in after him with eighty other priests of the LORD, all brave men.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 18, 'They confronted King Uzziah and said, "It is not for you, Uzziah, to burn incense to the LORD. That is the work of the priests alone, the sons of Aaron who are set apart for this work. Get out of the sanctuary, for you have sinned. The LORD God will not honor you for this!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 19, 'Uzziah was furious and refused to set down the incense burner he was holding. But as he was standing there with the priests before the incense altar in the LORD''s Temple, leprosy suddenly broke out on his forehead.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 20, 'When Azariah and the other priests saw the leprosy, they rushed him out. And the king himself was eager to get out because the LORD had struck him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 21, 'So King Uzziah had leprosy until the day he died. He lived in isolation, excluded from the Temple of the LORD. His son Jotham was put in charge of the royal palace, and he governed the people of the land.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 22, 'The rest of the events of Uzziah''s reign, from beginning to end, are recorded by the prophet Isaiah son of Amoz.', 'NLT'),
(18, 26, 23, 'So Uzziah died, and since he had leprosy, he was buried nearby in a burial field belonging to the kings. Then his son Jotham became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 27, 1, 'Jotham was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem sixteen years. His mother was Jerusha, the daughter of Zadok.', 'NLT'),
(18, 27, 2, 'He did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight, just as his father, Uzziah, had done. But unlike him, Jotham did not enter the Temple of the LORD. Nevertheless, the people continued in their corrupt ways.', 'NLT'),
(18, 27, 3, 'Jotham rebuilt the Upper Gate to the LORD''s Temple and also did extensive rebuilding on the wall at the hill of Ophel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 27, 4, 'He built towns in the hill country of Judah and constructed fortresses and towers in the wooded areas.', 'NLT'),
(18, 27, 5, 'Jotham waged war against the Ammonites and conquered them. For the next three years, he received from them an annual tribute of 7,500 pounds of silver, 50,000 bushels of wheat, and 50,000 bushels of barley.', 'NLT'),
(18, 27, 6, 'King Jotham became powerful because he was careful to live in obedience to the LORD his God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 27, 7, 'The rest of the events of Jotham''s reign, including his wars and other activities, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Israel and Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 27, 8, 'He was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem sixteen years.', 'NLT'),
(18, 27, 9, 'When he died, he was buried in the City of David, and his son Ahaz became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 1, 'Ahaz was twenty years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem sixteen years. He did not do what was pleasing in the sight of the LORD, as his ancestor David had done.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 2, 'Instead, he followed the example of the kings of Israel and cast images for the worship of Baal.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 3, 'He offered sacrifices in the valley of the son of Hinnom, even sacrificing his own sons in the fire. He imitated the detestable practices of the pagan nations whom the LORD had driven from the land ahead of the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 4, 'He offered sacrifices and burned incense at the pagan shrines and on the hills and under every green tree.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 5, 'That is why the LORD his God allowed the king of Aram to defeat Ahaz and to exile large numbers of his people to Damascus. The armies of Israel also defeated Ahaz and inflicted many casualties on his army.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 6, 'In a single day Pekah son of Remaliah, Israel''s king, killed 120,000 of Judah''s troops because they had abandoned the LORD, the God of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 7, 'Then Zicri, a warrior from Ephraim, killed Maaseiah, the king''s son; Azrikam, the king''s palace commander; and Elkanah, the king''s second-in-command.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 8, 'The armies of Israel captured 200,000 women and children from Judah and took tremendous amounts of plunder, which they took back to Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 9, 'But a prophet of the LORD named Oded was there in Samaria when the army of Israel returned home. He went out to meet them and said, "The LORD, the God of your ancestors, was angry with Judah and let you defeat them. But you have gone too far, killing them without mercy, and all heaven is disturbed.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 10, 'And now you are planning to make slaves of these people from Judah and Jerusalem. What about your own sins against the LORD your God?', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 11, 'Listen to me and return these captives you have taken, for they are your own relatives. Watch out, because now the LORD''s fierce anger has been turned against you!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 12, 'Then some of the leaders of Israel--Azariah son of Jehohanan, Berekiah son of Meshillemoth, Jehizkiah son of Shallum, and Amasa son of Hadlai--agreed with this and confronted the men returning from battle.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 13, '"You must not bring the prisoners here!" they declared. "We cannot afford to add to our sins and guilt. Our guilt is already great, and the LORD''s fierce anger is already turned against Israel."', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 14, 'So the warriors released the prisoners and handed over the plunder in the sight of all the leaders and people.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 15, 'Then the four men mentioned by name came forward and distributed clothes from the plunder to the prisoners who were naked. They provided clothing and sandals to wear, gave them enough food and drink, and dressed their wounds with olive oil. They put those who were weak on donkeys and took all the prisoners back to their own land--to Jericho, the city of palms. Then they returned to Samaria.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 16, 'About that time King Ahaz of Judah asked the king of Assyria for help against his enemies.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 17, 'The armies of Edom had again invaded Judah and taken captives.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 18, 'And the Philistines had raided towns located in the foothills of Judah and in the Negev. They had already captured Beth-shemesh, Aijalon, Gederoth, Soco with its villages, Timnah with its villages, and Gimzo with its villages, and the Philistines had occupied these towns.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 19, 'The LORD was humbling Judah because of King Ahaz of Judah, for he had encouraged his people to sin and had been utterly unfaithful to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 20, 'So when King Tiglath-pileser of Assyria arrived, he oppressed King Ahaz instead of helping him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 21, 'Ahaz took valuable items from the LORD''s Temple, the royal palace, and from the homes of his officials and gave them to the king of Assyria as tribute. But even this did not help him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 22, 'And when trouble came to King Ahaz, he became even more unfaithful to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 23, 'He offered sacrifices to the gods of Damascus who had defeated him, for he said, "These gods helped the kings of Aram, so they will help me, too, if I sacrifice to them." But instead, they led to his ruin and the ruin of all Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 24, 'The king took the utensils from the Temple of God and broke them into pieces. He shut the doors of the LORD''s Temple so that no one could worship there and then set up altars to pagan gods in every corner of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 25, 'He made pagan shrines in all the towns of Judah for offering sacrifices to other gods. In this way, he aroused the anger of the LORD, the God of his ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 26, 'The rest of the events of Ahaz''s reign and all his dealings, from beginning to end, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Judah and Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 28, 27, 'When King Ahaz died, he was buried in Jerusalem but not in the royal cemetery. Then his son Hezekiah became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 1, 'Hezekiah was twenty-five years old when he became the king of Judah, and he reigned in Jerusalem twenty-nine years. His mother was Abijah, the daughter of Zechariah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 2, 'He did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight, just as his ancestor David had done.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 3, 'In the very first month of the first year of his reign, Hezekiah reopened the doors of the Temple of the LORD and repaired them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 4, 'He summoned the priests and Levites to meet him at the courtyard east of the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 5, 'He said to them, "Listen to me, you Levites! Purify yourselves, and purify the Temple of the LORD, the God of your ancestors. Remove all the defiled things from the sanctuary.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 6, 'Our ancestors were unfaithful and did what was evil in the sight of the LORD our God. They abandoned the LORD and his Temple; they turned their backs on him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 7, 'They also shut the doors to the Temple''s foyer, and they snuffed out the lamps. They stopped burning incense and presenting burnt offerings at the sanctuary of the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 8, 'That is why the LORD''s anger has fallen upon Judah and Jerusalem. He has made us an object of dread, horror, and ridicule, as you can so plainly see.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 9, 'Our fathers have been killed in battle, and our sons and daughters and wives are in captivity.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 10, 'But now I will make a covenant with the LORD, the God of Israel, so that his fierce anger will turn away from us.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 11, 'My dear Levites, do not neglect your duties any longer! The LORD has chosen you to stand in his presence, to minister to him, and to lead the people in worship and make offerings to him."', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 12, 'Then these Levites got right to work: From the clan of Kohath: Mahath son of Amasai and Joel son of Azariah. From the clan of Merari: Kish son of Abdi and Azariah son of Jehallelel. From the clan of Gershon: Joah son of Zimmah and Eden son of Joah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 13, 'From the family of Elizaphan: Shimri and Jeiel. From the family of Asaph: Zechariah and Mattaniah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 14, 'From the family of Heman: Jehiel and Shimei. From the family of Jeduthun: Shemaiah and Uzziel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 15, 'These men called together their fellow Levites, and they purified themselves. Then they began to purify the Temple of the LORD, just as the king had commanded. They were careful to follow all the LORD''s instructions in their work.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 16, 'The priests went into the sanctuary of the Temple of the LORD to cleanse it, and they took out to the Temple courtyard all the defiled things they found. From there the Levites carted it all out to the Kidron Valley.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 17, 'The work began on a day in early spring, and in eight days they had reached the foyer of the LORD''s Temple. Then they purified the Temple of the LORD itself, which took another eight days. So the entire task was completed in sixteen days.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 18, 'Then the Levites went to King Hezekiah and gave him this report: "We have purified the Temple of the LORD, the altar of burnt offering with all its utensils, and the table of the Bread of the Presence with all its utensils.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 19, 'We have also recovered all the utensils taken by King Ahaz when he was unfaithful and closed the Temple. They are now in front of the altar of the LORD, purified and ready for use."', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 20, 'Early the next morning King Hezekiah gathered the city officials and went to the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 21, 'They brought seven bulls, seven rams, seven lambs, and seven male goats as a sin offering for the kingdom, for the Temple, and for Judah. The king commanded the priests, who were descendants of Aaron, to sacrifice the animals on the altar of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 22, 'So they killed the bulls, and the priests took the blood and sprinkled it on the altar. Next they killed the rams and sprinkled their blood on the altar. And finally, they did the same with the lambs.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 23, 'The male goats for the sin offering were then brought before the king and the assembly of people, who laid their hands on them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 24, 'The priests then killed the goats as a sin offering and sprinkled their blood on the altar to make atonement for the sins of all Israel. The king had specifically commanded that this burnt offering and sin offering should be made for all Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 25, 'King Hezekiah then stationed the Levites at the Temple of the LORD with cymbals, harps, and lyres. He obeyed all the commands that the LORD had given to King David through Gad, the king''s seer, and the prophet Nathan.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 26, 'The Levites then took their positions around the Temple with the instruments of David, and the priests took their positions with the trumpets.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 27, 'Then Hezekiah ordered that the burnt offering be placed on the altar. As the burnt offering was presented, songs of praise to the LORD were begun, accompanied by the trumpets and other instruments of David, king of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 28, 'The entire assembly worshiped the LORD as the singers sang and the trumpets blew, until all the burnt offerings were finished.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 29, 'Then the king and everyone with him bowed down in worship.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 30, 'King Hezekiah and the officials ordered the Levites to praise the LORD with the psalms of David and Asaph the seer. So they offered joyous praise and bowed down in worship.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 31, 'Then Hezekiah declared, "The dedication ceremony has come to an end. Now bring your sacrifices and thanksgiving offerings to the Temple of the LORD." So the people brought their sacrifices and thanksgiving offerings, and those whose hearts were willing brought burnt offerings, too.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 32, 'The people brought to the LORD seventy bulls, one hundred rams, and two hundred lambs for burnt offerings.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 33, 'They also brought six hundred bulls and three thousand sheep as sacrifices.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 34, 'But there were too few priests to prepare all the burnt offerings, so their relatives the Levites helped them until the work was finished and until more priests had been purified. For the Levites had been more conscientious about purifying themselves than the priests.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 35, 'There was an abundance of burnt offerings, along with the usual drink offerings, and a great deal of fat from the many peace offerings. So the Temple of the LORD was restored to service.', 'NLT'),
(18, 29, 36, 'And Hezekiah and all the people rejoiced greatly because of what God had done for the people, for everything had been accomplished so quickly.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 1, 'King Hezekiah now sent word to all Israel and Judah, and he wrote letters of invitation to Ephraim and Manasseh. He asked everyone to come to the Temple of the LORD at Jerusalem to celebrate the Passover of the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 2, 'The king, his officials, and all the community of Jerusalem decided to celebrate Passover a month later than usual.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 3, 'They were unable to celebrate it at the regular time because not enough priests could be purified by then, and the people had not yet assembled at Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 4, 'This plan for keeping the Passover seemed right to the king and all the people.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 5, 'So they sent a proclamation throughout all Israel, from Beersheba in the south to Dan in the north, inviting everyone to come to Jerusalem to celebrate the Passover of the LORD, the God of Israel. The people had not been celebrating it in great numbers as prescribed in the law.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 6, 'At the king''s command, messengers were sent throughout Israel and Judah. They carried letters which said: "O people of Israel, return to the LORD, the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Israel, so that he will return to the few of us who have survived the conquest of the Assyrian kings.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 7, 'Do not be like your ancestors and relatives who abandoned the LORD, the God of their ancestors, and became an object of derision, as you yourselves can see.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 8, 'Do not be stubborn, as they were, but submit yourselves to the LORD. Come to his Temple which he has set apart as holy forever. Worship the LORD your God so that his fierce anger will turn away from you.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 9, 'For if you return to the LORD, your relatives and your children will be treated mercifully by their captors, and they will be able to return to this land. For the LORD your God is gracious and merciful. If you return to him, he will not continue to turn his face from you."', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 10, 'The messengers went from town to town throughout Ephraim and Manasseh and as far as the territory of Zebulun. But most of the people just laughed at the messengers and made fun of them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 11, 'However, some from Asher, Manasseh, and Zebulun humbled themselves and went to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 12, 'At the same time, God''s hand was on the people in the land of Judah, giving them a strong desire to unite in obeying the orders of the king and his officials, who were following the word of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 13, 'And so a huge crowd assembled at Jerusalem in midspring to celebrate Passover and the Festival of Unleavened Bread.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 14, 'They set to work and removed the pagan altars from Jerusalem. They took away all the incense altars and threw them into the Kidron Valley.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 15, 'On the appointed day in midspring, one month later than usual, the people slaughtered their Passover lambs. Then the priests and Levites became ashamed, so they purified themselves and brought burnt offerings to the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 16, 'They took their places at the Temple according to the regulations found in the law of Moses, the man of God. The Levites brought the sacrificial blood to the priests, who then sprinkled it on the altar.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 17, 'Since many of the people there had not purified themselves, the Levites had to slaughter their Passover lambs for them, to set them apart for the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 18, 'Most of those who came from Ephraim, Manasseh, Issachar, and Zebulun had not purified themselves. But King Hezekiah prayed for them, and they were allowed to eat the Passover meal anyway, even though this was contrary to God''s laws. For Hezekiah said, "May the LORD, who is good, pardon those', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 19, 'who decide to follow the LORD, the God of their ancestors, even though they are not properly cleansed for the ceremony."', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 20, 'And the LORD listened to Hezekiah''s prayer and healed the people.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 21, 'So the people of Israel who were present in Jerusalem celebrated the Festival of Unleavened Bread for seven days with great joy. Each day the Levites and priests sang to the LORD, accompanied by loud instruments.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 22, 'Hezekiah encouraged the Levites for the skill they displayed as they served the LORD. So for seven days the celebration continued. Peace offerings were sacrificed, and the people confessed their sins to the LORD, the God of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 23, 'The entire assembly then decided to continue the festival another seven days, so they celebrated joyfully for another week.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 24, 'King Hezekiah gave the people one thousand bulls and seven thousand sheep for offerings, and the officials donated one thousand bulls and ten thousand sheep. Meanwhile, many more priests purified themselves.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 25, 'The entire assembly of Judah rejoiced, including the priests, the Levites, all who came from the land of Israel, the foreigners who came to the festival, and all those who lived in Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 26, 'There was great joy in the city, for Jerusalem had not seen a celebration like this one since the days of Solomon, King David''s son.', 'NLT'),
(18, 30, 27, 'Then the Levitical priests stood and blessed the people, and God heard them from his holy dwelling in heaven.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 1, 'Now when the festival ended, the Israelites who attended went to all the towns of Judah, Benjamin, Ephraim, and Manasseh, and they smashed the sacred pillars, cut down the Asherah poles, and removed the pagan shrines and altars. After this, the Israelites returned to their own towns and homes.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 2, 'Hezekiah then organized the priests and Levites into divisions to offer the burnt offerings and peace offerings, and to worship and give thanks and praise to the LORD at the gates of the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 3, 'The king also made a personal contribution of animals for the daily morning and evening burnt offerings, as well as for the weekly Sabbath festivals and monthly new moon festivals, and for the other annual festivals as required in the law of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 4, 'In addition, he required the people in Jerusalem to bring the prescribed portion of their income to the priests and Levites, so they could devote themselves fully to the law of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 5, 'The people responded immediately and generously with the first of their crops and grain, new wine, olive oil, honey, and all the produce of their fields. They brought a tithe of all they owned.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 6, 'The people who had moved to Judah from Israel, and the people of Judah themselves, brought in the tithes of their cattle and sheep and a tithe of the things that had been dedicated to the LORD their God, and they piled them up in great heaps.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 7, 'The first of these tithes was brought in late spring, and the heaps continued to grow until early autumn.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 8, 'When Hezekiah and his officials came and saw these huge piles, they thanked the LORD and his people Israel!', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 9, '"Where did all this come from?" Hezekiah asked the priests and Levites.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 10, 'And Azariah the high priest, from the family of Zadok, replied, "Since the people began bringing their gifts to the LORD''s Temple, we have had enough to eat and plenty to spare, for the LORD has blessed his people."', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 11, 'Hezekiah decided to have storerooms prepared in the Temple of the LORD, and this was done.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 12, 'Then all the gifts and tithes were faithfully brought to the Temple. Conaniah the Levite was put in charge, assisted by his brother Shimei.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 13, 'The supervisors under them were Jehiel, Azaziah, Nahath, Asahel, Jerimoth, Jozabad, Eliel, Ismakiah, Mahath, and Benaiah. These appointments were made by King Hezekiah and Azariah, the chief official in the Temple of God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 14, 'Kore son of Imnah the Levite, who was the gatekeeper at the East Gate, was put in charge of distributing the freewill offerings of God, the gifts, and the things that had been dedicated to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 15, 'His faithful assistants were Eden, Miniamin, Jeshua, Shemaiah, Amariah, and Shecaniah. They distributed the gifts among the families of priests in their towns, by their divisions, dividing the gifts fairly among young and old alike.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 16, 'They also distributed the gifts to all males three years old or older, regardless of their place in the genealogical records, who came daily to the LORD''s Temple to perform their official duties, by their divisions.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 17, 'And they distributed gifts to the priests who were listed in the genealogical records by families, and to the Levites twenty years old or older who were listed according to their jobs and their divisions.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 18, 'Food allotments were also given to all the families listed in the genealogical records, including the little babies, the wives, and the sons and daughters. For they had all been faithful in purifying themselves.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 19, 'As for the priests, the descendants of Aaron, who were living in the open villages around the towns, men were appointed to distribute portions to every male among the priests and to all the Levites listed in the genealogical records.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 20, 'In this way, King Hezekiah handled the distribution throughout all Judah, doing what was pleasing and good in the sight of the LORD his God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 31, 21, 'In all that he did in the service of the Temple of God and in his efforts to follow the law and the commands, Hezekiah sought his God wholeheartedly. As a result, he was very successful.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 1, 'After Hezekiah had faithfully carried out this work, King Sennacherib of Assyria invaded Judah. He laid siege to the fortified cities, giving orders for his army to break through their walls.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 2, 'When Hezekiah realized that Sennacherib also intended to attack Jerusalem,', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 3, 'he consulted with his officials and military advisers, and they decided to stop the flow of the springs outside the city.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 4, 'They organized a huge work crew to stop the flow of the springs, cutting off the brook that ran through the fields. For they said, "Why should the kings of Assyria come here and find plenty of water?"', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 5, 'Then Hezekiah further strengthened his defenses by repairing the wall wherever it was broken down and by adding to the fortifications and constructing a second wall outside the first. He also reinforced the Millo in the City of David and manufactured large numbers of weapons and shields.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 6, 'He appointed military officers over the people and asked them to assemble before him in the square at the city gate. Then Hezekiah encouraged them with this address:', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 7, '"Be strong and courageous! Don''t be afraid of the king of Assyria or his mighty army, for there is a power far greater on our side!', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 8, 'He may have a great army, but they are just men. We have the LORD our God to help us and to fight our battles for us!" These words greatly encouraged the people.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 9, 'Then King Sennacherib of Assyria, while still besieging the town of Lachish, sent officials to Jerusalem with this message for Hezekiah and all the people in the city:', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 10, '"This is what King Sennacherib of Assyria says: What are you trusting in that makes you think you can survive my siege of Jerusalem?', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 11, 'Hezekiah has said, `The LORD our God will rescue us from the king of Assyria.'' Surely Hezekiah is misleading you, sentencing you to death by famine and thirst!', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 12, 'Surely you must realize that Hezekiah is the very person who destroyed all the LORD''s shrines and altars. He commanded Judah and Jerusalem to worship at only the one altar at the Temple and to make sacrifices on it alone.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 13, '"Surely you must realize what I and the other kings of Assyria before me have done to all the people of the earth! Were any of the gods of those nations able to rescue their people from my power?', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 14, 'Name just one time when any god, anywhere, was able to rescue his people from me! What makes you think your God can do any better?', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 15, 'Don''t let Hezekiah fool you! Don''t let him deceive you like this! I say it again--no god of any nation has ever yet been able to rescue his people from me or my ancestors. How much less will your God rescue you from my power!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 16, 'And Sennacherib''s officials further mocked the LORD God and his servant Hezekiah, heaping insult upon insult.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 17, 'The king also sent letters scorning the LORD, the God of Israel. He wrote, "Just as the gods of all the other nations failed to rescue their people from my power, so the God of Hezekiah will also fail."', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 18, 'The Assyrian officials who brought the letters shouted this in the Hebrew language to the people gathered on the walls of the city, trying to terrify them so it would be easier to capture the city.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 19, 'These officials talked about the God of Jerusalem as though he were one of the pagan gods, made by human hands.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 20, 'Then King Hezekiah and the prophet Isaiah son of Amoz cried out in prayer to God in heaven.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 21, 'And the LORD sent an angel who destroyed the Assyrian army with all its commanders and officers. So Sennacherib returned home in disgrace to his own land. And when he entered the temple of his god, some of his own sons killed him there with a sword.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 22, 'That is how the LORD rescued Hezekiah and the people of Jerusalem from King Sennacherib of Assyria and from all the others who threatened them. So there was peace at last throughout the land.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 23, 'From then on King Hezekiah became highly respected among the surrounding nations, and many gifts for the LORD arrived at Jerusalem, with valuable presents for King Hezekiah, too.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 24, 'About that time, Hezekiah became deathly ill. He prayed to the LORD, who healed him and gave him a miraculous sign.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 25, 'But Hezekiah did not respond appropriately to the kindness shown him, and he became proud. So the LORD''s anger came against him and against Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 26, 'Then Hezekiah repented of his pride, and the people of Jerusalem humbled themselves. So the LORD''s anger did not come against them during Hezekiah''s lifetime.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 27, 'Hezekiah was very wealthy and held in high esteem. He had to build special treasury buildings for his silver, gold, precious stones, and spices, and for his shields and other valuable items.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 28, 'He also constructed many storehouses for his grain, new wine, and olive oil; and he made many stalls for his cattle and folds for his flocks of sheep and goats.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 29, 'He built many towns and acquired vast flocks and herds, for God had given him great wealth.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 30, 'He blocked up the upper spring of Gihon and brought the water down through a tunnel to the west side of the City of David. And so he succeeded in everything he did.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 31, 'However, when ambassadors arrived from Babylon to ask about the remarkable events that had taken place in the land, God withdrew from Hezekiah in order to test him and to see what was really in his heart.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 32, 'The rest of the events of Hezekiah''s reign and his acts of devotion are recorded in The Vision of the Prophet Isaiah Son of Amoz, which is included in The Book of the Kings of Judah and Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 32, 33, 'When Hezekiah died, he was buried in the upper area of the royal cemetery, and all Judah and Jerusalem honored him at his death. Then his son Manasseh became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 1, 'Manasseh was twelve years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem fifty-five years.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 2, 'He did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, imitating the detestable practices of the pagan nations whom the LORD had driven from the land ahead of the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 3, 'He rebuilt the pagan shrines his father Hezekiah had destroyed. He constructed altars for the images of Baal and set up Asherah poles. He also bowed before all the stars of heaven and worshiped them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 4, 'He even built pagan altars in the Temple of the LORD, the place where the LORD had said his name should be honored forever.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 5, 'He put these altars for the stars of heaven in both courtyards of the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 6, 'Manasseh even sacrificed his own sons in the fire in the valley of the son of Hinnom. He practiced sorcery, divination, and witchcraft, and he consulted with mediums and psychics. He did much that was evil in the LORD''s sight, arousing his anger.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 7, 'Manasseh even took a carved idol he had made and set it up in God''s Temple, the very place where God had told David and his son Solomon: "My name will be honored here forever in this Temple and in Jerusalem--the city I have chosen from among all the other tribes of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 8, 'If the Israelites will obey my commands--all the instructions, laws, and regulations given through Moses--I will not send them into exile from this land that I gave their ancestors."', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 9, 'But Manasseh led the people of Judah and Jerusalem to do even more evil than the pagan nations whom the LORD had destroyed when the Israelites entered the land.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 10, 'The LORD spoke to Manasseh and his people, but they ignored all his warnings.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 11, 'So the LORD sent the Assyrian armies, and they took Manasseh prisoner. They put a ring through his nose, bound him in bronze chains, and led him away to Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 12, 'But while in deep distress, Manasseh sought the LORD his God and cried out humbly to the God of his ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 13, 'And when he prayed, the LORD listened to him and was moved by his request for help. So the LORD let Manasseh return to Jerusalem and to his kingdom. Manasseh had finally realized that the LORD alone is God!', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 14, 'It was after this that Manasseh rebuilt the outer wall of the City of David, from west of the Gihon Spring in the Kidron Valley to the Fish Gate, and continuing around the hill of Ophel, where it was built very high. And he stationed his military officers in all of the fortified cities of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 15, 'Manasseh also removed the foreign gods from the hills and the idol from the LORD''s Temple. He tore down all the altars he had built on the hill where the Temple stood and all the altars that were in Jerusalem, and he dumped them outside the city.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 16, 'Then he restored the altar of the LORD and sacrificed peace offerings and thanksgiving offerings on it. He also encouraged the people of Judah to worship the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 17, 'However, the people still sacrificed at the pagan shrines, but only to the LORD their God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 18, 'The rest of the events of Manasseh''s reign, his prayer to God, and the words the seers spoke to him in the name of the LORD, the God of Israel, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 19, 'Manasseh''s prayer, the account of the way God answered him, and an account of all his sins and unfaithfulness are recorded in The Record of the Seers. It includes a list of the locations where he built pagan shrines and set up Asherah poles and idols before he repented.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 20, 'When Manasseh died, he was buried at his palace. Then his son Amon became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 21, 'Amon was twenty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem two years.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 22, 'He did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, just as his father Manasseh had done. He worshiped and sacrificed to all the idols his father had made.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 23, 'But unlike his father, he did not humble himself before the LORD. Instead, Amon sinned even more.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 24, 'At last Amon''s own officials plotted against him and assassinated him in his palace.', 'NLT'),
(18, 33, 25, 'But the people of the land killed all those who had conspired against King Amon, and they made his son Josiah the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 1, 'Josiah was eight years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem thirty-one years.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 2, 'He did what was pleasing in the LORD''s sight and followed the example of his ancestor David. He did not turn aside from doing what was right.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 3, 'During the eighth year of his reign, while he was still young, Josiah began to seek the God of his ancestor David. Then in the twelfth year, he began to purify Judah and Jerusalem, destroying all the pagan shrines, the Asherah poles, and the carved idols and cast images.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 4, 'He saw to it that the altars for the images of Baal and their incense altars were torn down. He also made sure that the Asherah poles, the carved idols, and the cast images were smashed and scattered over the graves of those who had sacrificed to them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 5, 'Then he burned the bones of the pagan priests on their own altars, and so he purified Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 6, 'He did the same thing in the towns of Manasseh, Ephraim, and Simeon, even as far as Naphtali.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 7, 'He destroyed the pagan altars and the Asherah poles, and he crushed the idols into dust. He cut down the incense altars throughout the land of Israel and then returned to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 8, 'In the eighteenth year of his reign, after he had purified the land and the Temple, Josiah appointed Shaphan son of Azaliah, Maaseiah the governor of Jerusalem, and Joah son of Joahaz, the royal historian, to repair the Temple of the LORD his God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 9, 'They gave Hilkiah the high priest the money that had been collected by the Levites who served as gatekeepers at the Temple of God. The gifts were brought by people from Manasseh, Ephraim, and from all the remnant of Israel, as well as from all Judah, Benjamin, and the people of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 10, 'He entrusted the money to the men assigned to supervise the restoration of the LORD''s Temple. Then they paid the workers who did the repairs and renovation.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 11, 'Thus, they hired carpenters and masons and purchased cut stone for the walls and timber for the rafters and beams. They restored what earlier kings of Judah had allowed to fall into ruin.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 12, 'The workers served faithfully under the leadership of Jahath and Obadiah, Levites of the Merarite clan, and Zechariah and Meshullam, Levites of the Kohathite clan. Other Levites, all of whom were skilled musicians,', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 13, 'were put in charge of the laborers of the various trades. Still others assisted as secretaries, officials, and gatekeepers.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 14, 'As Hilkiah the high priest was recording the money collected at the LORD''s Temple, he found the Book of the Law of the LORD as it had been given through Moses.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 15, 'Hilkiah said to Shaphan the court secretary, "I have found the Book of the Law in the LORD''s Temple!" Then Hilkiah gave the scroll to Shaphan.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 16, 'Shaphan took the scroll to the king and reported, "Your officials are doing everything they were assigned to do.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 17, 'The money that was collected at the Temple of the LORD has been given to the supervisors and workmen."', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 18, 'Shaphan also said to the king, "Hilkiah the priest has given me a scroll." So Shaphan read it to the king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 19, 'When the king heard what was written in the law, he tore his clothes in despair.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 20, 'Then he gave these orders to Hilkiah, Ahikam son of Shaphan, Acbor son of Micaiah, Shaphan the court secretary, and Asaiah the king''s personal adviser:', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 21, '"Go to the Temple and speak to the LORD for me and for all the remnant of Israel and Judah. Ask him about the words written in this scroll that has been found. The LORD''s anger has been poured out against us because our ancestors have not obeyed the word of the LORD. We have not been doing what this scroll says we must do."', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 22, 'So Hilkiah and the other men went to the newer Mishneh section of Jerusalem to consult with the prophet Huldah. She was the wife of Shallum son of Tikvah and grandson of Harhas, the keeper of the Temple wardrobe.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 23, 'She said to them, "The LORD, the God of Israel, has spoken! Go and tell the man who sent you,', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 24, '`This is what the LORD says: I will certainly destroy this city and its people. All the curses written in the scroll you have read will come true.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 25, 'For the people of Judah have abandoned me and worshiped pagan gods, and I am very angry with them for everything they have done. My anger will be poured out against this place, and nothing will be able to stop it.''', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 26, '"But go to the king of Judah who sent you to seek the LORD and tell him: `This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says concerning the message you have just heard:', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 27, 'You were sorry and humbled yourself before God when you heard what I said against this city and its people. You humbled yourself and tore your clothing in despair and wept before me in repentance. So I have indeed heard you, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 28, 'I will not send the promised disaster against this city and its people until after you have died and been buried in peace. You will not see the disaster I am going to bring on this place.''" So they took her message back to the king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 29, 'Then the king summoned all the leaders of Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 30, 'And the king went up to the Temple of the LORD with all the people of Judah and Jerusalem and the priests and the Levites--all the people from the greatest to the least. There the king read to them the entire Book of the Covenant that had been found in the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 31, 'The king took his place of authority beside the pillar and renewed the covenant in the LORD''s presence. He pledged to obey the LORD by keeping all his commands, regulations, and laws with all his heart and soul. He promised to obey all the terms of the covenant that were written in the scroll.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 32, 'And he required everyone in Jerusalem and the people of Benjamin to make a similar pledge. As the people of Jerusalem did this, they renewed their covenant with God, the God of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 34, 33, 'So Josiah removed all detestable idols from the entire land of Israel and required everyone to worship the LORD their God. And throughout the rest of his lifetime, they did not turn away from the LORD, the God of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 1, 'Then Josiah announced that the Passover of the LORD would be celebrated in Jerusalem on the appointed day in early spring. The Passover lambs were slaughtered at twilight of that day.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 2, 'Josiah also assigned the priests to their duties and encouraged them in their work at the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 3, 'He issued this order to the Levites, who had been set apart to serve the LORD and were teachers in Israel: "Since the Ark is now in Solomon''s Temple and you do not need to carry it back and forth on your shoulders, spend your time serving the LORD your God and his people Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 4, 'Report for duty according to the family divisions of your ancestors, following the written instructions of King David of Israel and the instructions of his son Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 5, 'Then stand in your appointed holy places and help the families assigned to you as they bring their offerings to the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 6, 'Slaughter the Passover lambs, purify yourselves, and prepare to help those who come. Follow all the instructions that the LORD gave through Moses."', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 7, 'Then Josiah contributed from his personal property thirty thousand lambs and young goats for the people''s Passover offerings, and three thousand bulls.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 8, 'The king''s officials also made willing contributions to the people, priests, and Levites. Hilkiah, Zechariah, and Jehiel, the administrators of God''s Temple, gave the priests twenty-six hundred lambs and young goats and three hundred bulls as Passover offerings.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 9, 'The Levite leaders--Conaniah and his brothers Shemaiah and Nethanel, and Hashabiah, Jeiel, and Jozabad--gave five thousand lambs and young goats and five hundred bulls to the Levites for their Passover offerings.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 10, 'When everything was ready for the Passover celebration, the priests and the Levites took their places, organized by their divisions, according to the king''s orders.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 11, 'The Levites then slaughtered the Passover lambs and presented the blood to the priests, who sprinkled the blood on the altar while the Levites prepared the animals.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 12, 'They divided the burnt offerings among the people by their family groups, so they could offer them to the LORD according to the instructions recorded in the Book of Moses. They did the same with the bulls.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 13, 'Then they roasted the Passover lambs as prescribed; and they boiled the holy offerings in pots, kettles, and pans, and brought them out quickly so the people could eat them.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 14, 'Afterward the Levites prepared a meal for themselves and for the priests, because the priests had been busy from morning till night offering the burnt offerings and the fat portions. The Levites took responsibility for all these preparations.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 15, 'The musicians, descendants of Asaph, were in their assigned places, following the orders given by David, Asaph, Heman, and Jeduthun, the king''s seer. The gatekeepers guarded the gates and did not need to leave their posts of duty, for their meals were brought to them by their fellow Levites.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 16, 'The entire ceremony for the LORD''s Passover was completed that day. All the burnt offerings were sacrificed on the altar of the LORD, as King Josiah had ordered.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 17, 'All the Israelites present in Jerusalem celebrated Passover and the Festival of Unleavened Bread for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 18, 'Never since the time of the prophet Samuel had there been such a Passover. None of the kings of Israel had ever kept a Passover as Josiah did, involving all the priests and Levites, all the people of Jerusalem, and people from all over Judah and Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 19, 'This Passover celebration took place in the eighteenth year of Josiah''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 20, 'After Josiah had finished restoring the Temple, King Neco of Egypt led his army up from Egypt to do battle at Carchemish on the Euphrates River, and Josiah and his army marched out to fight him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 21, 'But King Neco sent ambassadors to Josiah with this message: "What do you want with me, king of Judah? I have no quarrel with you today! I only want to fight the nation with which I am at war. And God has told me to hurry! Do not interfere with God, who is with me, or he will destroy you."', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 22, 'But Josiah refused to listen to Neco, to whom God had indeed spoken, and he would not turn back. Instead, he led his army into battle on the plain of Megiddo. He laid aside his royal robes so the enemy would not recognize him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 23, 'But the enemy archers hit King Josiah with their arrows and wounded him. He cried out to his men, "Take me from the battle, for I am badly wounded!"', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 24, 'So they lifted Josiah out of his chariot and placed him in another chariot. Then they brought him back to Jerusalem, where he died. He was buried there in the royal cemetery. And all Judah and Jerusalem mourned for him.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 25, 'The prophet Jeremiah composed funeral songs for Josiah, and to this day choirs still sing these sad songs about his death. These songs of sorrow have become a tradition and are recorded in The Book of Laments.', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 26, 'The rest of the events of Josiah''s reign and his acts of devotion done according to the written law of the LORD,', 'NLT'),
(18, 35, 27, 'from beginning to end, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Israel and Judah.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 1, 'Then the people of the land took Josiah''s son Jehoahaz and made him the next king in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 2, 'Jehoahaz was twenty-three years old when he became king, but he reigned only three months.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 3, 'Then he was deposed by Neco, the king of Egypt, who demanded a tribute from Judah of 7,500 pounds of silver and 75 pounds of gold.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 4, 'The king of Egypt appointed Eliakim, the brother of Jehoahaz, as the next king of Judah and Jerusalem, and he changed Eliakim''s name to Jehoiakim. Then Neco took Jehoahaz to Egypt as a prisoner.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 5, 'Jehoiakim was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem eleven years. But he did what was evil in the sight of the LORD his God.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 6, 'Then King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon came to Jerusalem and captured it, and he bound Jehoiakim in chains and led him away to Babylon.', 'NLT');
